<!-- pp. 1-20 -->

## Prologue: The Habit Cure

### Lisa Allen's Transformation

- **Lisa Allen**: 34-year-old research subject who transformed her life
- Started smoking/drinking at 16, struggled with obesity, had $10,000 debt
- Longest job lasted under a year
- After transformation: lean, fit, no debt, in 39th month at graphic design firm
- Lost 60 pounds, ran a marathon, completed master's degree, bought home

### The Turning Point in Cairo

- Husband announced affair during vacation planning
- Lisa's response: mourning → obsessive spying → drunk confrontation at girlfriend's house
- Cairo morning: woke to mosque call to prayer, tried to light a pen instead of cigarette
- Four months of crying, binge eating, insomnia, depression
- Breakthrough moment: "I felt desperate, like I had to change something, at least one thing I could control"
- Decision: trek through Egyptian desert as a goal
- Required quitting smoking to prepare for expedition

### The Cascade Effect

- Quitting smoking led to jogging
- Jogging changed eating, sleeping, saving, work scheduling, planning
- Eventually: half-marathons → marathon → grad school → house → engagement
- **Key insight**: One shift in perception triggered changes radiating to every part of life
- Brain scans showed old habit patterns **overridden** by new patterns
- Old behaviors still visible neurologically but crowded out by new urges

### The Keystone Habit Concept

- **Keystone habit**: Focusing on one pattern teaches how to reprogram other routines
- Lisa focused on smoking first; everyone in study went through similar process
- Companies can transform by changing habits: **Procter & Gamble**, **Starbucks**, **Alcoa**, **Target**
- Not just individuals — organizations and societies can shift through habit change

### The Research Study

- **National Institutes of Health** funded three-year study
- Subjects: former smokers, chronic overeaters, problem drinkers, obsessive shoppers
- All remade lives in relatively short periods
- Methods: vital signs monitoring, video cameras in homes, DNA sequencing, brain imaging
- Goal: understand how habits work neurologically and what triggers change
- Lisa's brain scans: areas for craving/hunger still active, but new activity in behavioral inhibition/self-discipline regions

### Habit Definition and Impact

> "All our life, so far as it has definite form, is but a mass of habits." — **William James** (1892)

- Most daily choices feel like decisions but are **habits**
- **Duke University** (2006): over 40% of daily actions are habits, not actual decisions
- Habits have enormous impact on health, productivity, financial security, happiness
- Only in past two decades have scientists begun understanding how habits work and change

### Book Structure

**Part One**: The Habits of Individuals
- Neurology of habit formation
- Building new habits and changing old ones
- **Febreze** story (**Procter & Gamble**)
- **Alcoholics Anonymous**
- **Tony Dungy** and **National Football League**

**Part Two**: The Habits of Successful Organizations
- **Paul O'Neill** at **Alcoa** (aluminum manufacturer → Dow Jones top performer via one keystone habit)
- **Starbucks** instilling willpower habits
- Why talented surgeons fail when organizational habits fail
- Hospital safety

**Part Three**: The Habits of Societies
- **Martin Luther King, Jr.** and civil rights movement
- Montgomery, Alabama social habits
- **Rick Warren** building nation's largest church (Saddleback Valley, California)
- Ethical questions: murderer arguing habits led him to kill

> "Habits can be changed, if we understand how they work."

### The Science Behind Habits

- Draws on hundreds of academic studies, 300+ scientist/executive interviews, research at dozens of companies
- Website: http://www.thepowerofhabit.com
- **Technical definition**: choices we deliberately make at some point, then stop thinking about but continue doing daily
- Once conscious decision → automatic behavior
- Natural consequence of neurology
- Understanding the mechanism enables rebuilding patterns

### Author's Journey: Iraq Example

- Author became interested in habit science eight years ago as reporter in Baghdad
- **U.S. military**: one of biggest habit-formation experiments in history
- Basic training creates habits for shooting, thinking, communicating under fire
- Battlefield commands draw on practiced behaviors (automaticity)

#### The Kufa Experiment

- Army major running impromptu habit modification program in **Kufa** (small city 90 miles south of capital)
- Analyzed riot videotapes, identified pattern: crowd gathers in plaza → grows for hours → food vendors appear → someone throws rock/bottle → violence
- Major's request to mayor: keep food vendors out of plazas
- Result: crowd gathered at **Masjid al-Kufa** (Great Mosque), grew, chanted angry slogans
- At dusk: crowd restless and hungry, looked for usual kebab sellers, none present
- Spectators left, chanters got dispirited, by 8 PM everyone gone — **no riot**

#### The Major's Insight

- Spent entire career steeped in habit psychology
- Boot camp habits: loading weapon, sleeping in war zone, maintaining focus amid chaos, making decisions while exhausted
- Money-saving habits, exercise habits, communication habits
- Learned organizational habits: subordinates making decisions without permission, right routines enabling work with difficult people
- Community as giant collection of habits influencing thousands
- Depending on influence → violence or peace
- Launched dozens of experiments in Kufa to influence residents' habits

> "Understanding habits is the most important thing I've learned in the army. It's changed everything about how I see the world. You want to fall asleep fast and wake up feeling good? Pay attention to your nighttime patterns and what you automatically do when you get up. You want to make running easy? Create triggers to make it a routine. I drill my kids on this stuff. My wife and I write out habit plans for our marriage. This is all we talk about in command meetings. Not one person in Kufa would have told me that we could influence crowds by taking away the kebab stands, but once you see everything as a bunch of habits, it's like someone gave you a flashlight and a crowbar and you can get to work."

### The Major's Background

- Small-town Georgia origin
- Perpetually spitting sunflower seeds or chewing tobacco
- Before military: best career options were repairing telephone lines or becoming methamphetamine entrepreneur
- Now: oversaw 800 troops in sophisticated fighting organization

> "I'm telling you, if a hick like me can learn this stuff, anyone can. I tell my soldiers all the time, there's nothing you can't do if you get the habits right."

### Scientific Understanding of Habits

- Past decade: explosion of understanding
- Neurology and psychology of habits and pattern functioning in lives, societies, organizations
- Can break habits into parts and rebuild to specifications
- Know how to make people eat less, exercise more, work more efficiently, live healthier
- Transforming habits isn't necessarily easy or quick, isn't always simple
- **But it is possible. And now we understand how.**

## Chapter 1: The Habit Loop — How Habits Work

### I. Eugene Pauly (E.P.)

- Fall 1993: walked into lab at San Diego for scheduled appointment
- Elderly, over 6 feet tall, neatly dressed, thick white hair
- Arthritis caused slight limp, walked slowly with wife's hand
- Year earlier: preparing dinner at home in Playa del Rey when wife mentioned son Michael coming over
- Eugene: "Who's Michael?" — didn't recognize his own son's name

### The Illness

- Started vomiting and stomach cramps
- Within 24 hours: severe dehydration → emergency room
- Temperature hit 105°F, became delirious then violent
- After sedation: physician slid needle between vertebrae to extract cerebrospinal fluid
- Fluid cloudy and sluggish (normally clear and quick-flowing)
- Diagnosis: **viral encephalitis** — virus from cold sores/fever blisters
- In rare cases: virus enters brain, inflicting catastrophic damage

### Brain Damage and Recovery

- Doctors: nothing could counter damage already done, large antiviral dose might prevent spreading
- Eugene slipped into coma for ten days, close to death
- Gradually: drugs fought disease, fever receded, virus disappeared
- When awake: weak, disoriented, couldn't swallow properly, couldn't form sentences
- Sometimes gasped as if momentarily forgetting how to breathe
- Eventually: well enough for battery of tests
- Body including nervous system largely unscathed
- Head scans: **ominous shadows near brain center**
- Virus destroyed oval of tissue close to cranium and spinal column
- Doctor warned wife Beverly: "He might not be the person you remember. You need to be ready if your husband is gone."

### Rehabilitation

- Moved to different hospital wing
- Within a week: swallowing easily
- Another week: talking normally, asking for Jell-O and salt
- Flipping TV channels, complaining about boring soap operas
- Five weeks later in rehab center: walking hallways, offering unsolicited advice about weekend plans
- Doctor to Beverly: "I don't think I've ever seen anyone come back like this. I don't want to raise your hopes, but this is amazing."

### Memory Problems

- Beverly concerned: disease changed husband in unsettling ways
- Couldn't remember day of week or doctors'/nurses' names despite repeated introductions
- "Why do they keep asking me all these questions?" he asked after physician left
- Things got stranger when home
- Didn't remember friends, trouble following conversations
- Some mornings: get out of bed, walk to kitchen, cook bacon and eggs, climb back under covers, turn on radio
- Forty minutes later: same thing (get up, cook bacon and eggs, back to bed, radio)
- Then do it again

### Larry Squire's Research

- Beverly contacted specialist at **University of California, San Diego**: memory loss researcher
- **Larry Squire**: 52-year-old professor, three decades studying neuroanatomy of memory
- Specialty: how brain stores events
- Work with Eugene opened new world to him and hundreds of researchers
- Studies would show: even someone who can't remember own age can develop **inconceivably complex habits**
- Everyone relies on similar neurological processes every day
- Research would reveal subconscious mechanisms impacting countless choices (seem like well-reasoned thought but influenced by barely recognized urges)

### Eugene's Brain Damage

- Squire had studied brain scans for weeks
- Almost all damage limited to **five-centimeter area near head center**
- Virus almost entirely destroyed **medial temporal lobe**
- Scientists suspected this sliver responsible for cognitive tasks: recall of past, regulation of emotions
- Completeness of destruction didn't surprise Squire (viral encephalitis consumes tissue with ruthless, surgical precision)
- What shocked him: **how familiar the images seemed**

### H.M. — The Famous Patient

- **Thirty years earlier**: Squire as PhD student at MIT worked with group studying **"H.M."** (one of most famous medical history patients)
- Real name: **Henry Molaison** (identity shrouded throughout life)
- Age seven: hit by bicycle, landed hard on head
- Soon afterward: seizures and blackouts
- At sixteen: first grand mal seizure (affects entire brain)
- Losing consciousness up to ten times daily
- By 27: desperate, anti-convulsive drugs hadn't helped
- Smart but couldn't hold a job, still lived with parents
- Wanted normal existence, sought experimental surgery
<!-- pp. 21-40 -->

## Chapter 1: The Habit Loop (continued)

### H.M.'s Surgery and Memory Loss

- 1953 surgery removed **hippocampus** and surrounding tissue to stop
seizures
- Seizures stopped, but H.M. lost ability to form new memories —
couldn't retain information for more than 20 seconds
- Remembered pre-1953 events (1929 crash, Normandy) but nothing
after surgery
- From 1953 until death in 2008, every person, song, room was fresh
each time
- Introduced himself to doctors repeatedly, didn't recognize his own
grandchildren

### Eugene Pauly's Case

- **Larry Squire** (memory researcher) studied **Eugene Pauly**, who had
similar brain damage from viral encephalitis
- Eugene's hippocampus escaped injury, but surrounding areas damaged
- Unlike H.M., Eugene could hold conversations and seemed normal at
first
- Worked as aerospace technician, remembered youth in California,
merchant marines, Australia trip
- Could recall events before ~1960, but had trouble with recent decades

### Eugene's Retained Habits

- **Intelligence tests showed sharp mind** despite inability to form new
memories
- **Retained all habits from youth** — thanked people when given water,
introduced himself when someone entered
- Couldn't draw map of house, said "I'm not really sure" how to leave
his room
- Yet walked to bathroom without hesitation, flushed toilet, washed
hands, returned to chair
- **Key mystery**: How could someone who couldn't map his house find
the bathroom automatically?

### Eugene's Daily Walks

- Beverly (wife) took Eugene on daily walks, same route every morning
- Doctors warned he'd never find way home if lost
- One morning Eugene slipped out while Beverly was dressing
- She found him 15 minutes later watching History Channel, pinecones
on table
- He had wandered out, collected souvenirs, and **found his way home**
- Soon walking every morning independently, returning with objects
(wallet, puppy) he couldn't remember acquiring

### The Breakthrough Experiment

- Squire's team suspected **unconscious habit formation** was guiding
Eugene
- Asked Eugene to draw map of block where he lived — couldn't do it
- Asked where kitchen was — couldn't say
- Asked what he'd do if hungry — stood up, walked to kitchen, opened
cabinet, took jar of nuts
- On walks, Eugene led the way confidently, never asked for directions
- When visitor asked where he lived, Eugene said "I don't know, exactly"
then walked up sidewalk, opened door, turned on TV

> "It was clear to Squire that Eugene was absorbing new information.
But where inside his brain was that information residing?"

### MIT's Basal Ganglia Research

- **MIT Brain and Cognitive Sciences** labs study habit formation in rats
with microscopic sensors
- 1990s research focused on **basal ganglia** — oval of cells deep in brain
- Basal ganglia: evolutionarily ancient, similar across fish/reptiles/
mammals
- Controls automatic behaviors: breathing, swallowing, startle response
- Previously associated with diseases like **Parkinson's**
- Researchers wondered if basal ganglia played role in **habits** too

### The T-Shaped Maze Experiment

- Rats with sensors implanted in skulls placed in T-shaped maze with
chocolate at one end
- Partition opened with loud click sound
- Initially rats wandered aimlessly, sniffing corners, scratching walls
- **Brain probes showed furious activity** entire time — analyzing every
scent, sight, sound
- Eventually most rats found chocolate, but no discernible pattern in
their wandering

### Brain Activity Changes Over Repetition

- After hundreds of runs through same maze, rats' behavior changed:
- Stopped sniffing corners and making wrong turns
- Zipped through faster and faster
- **Mental activity decreased** — route became automatic, rats thought
less
- Within a week, brain structures related to memory quieted
- Rat internalized "run straight, hang left, eat chocolate" — **barely
needed to think**

### The Basal Ganglia Takes Over

- Internalization relied on **basal ganglia**
- This ancient structure took over as rat ran faster and brain worked
less
- **Basal ganglia stored habits** even while rest of brain went to sleep
- Graph shows brain activity high at first encounter, settles down after
route becomes familiar

### Chunking: The Process of Habit Formation

- Brain converts sequence of actions into automatic routine
- Called **"chunking"** — root of how habits form
- Dozens or hundreds of behavioral chunks we rely on daily
- Simple: putting toothpaste on brush automatically
- Complex: backing car out of driveway

### The Elaborate Act of Backing Out

- When first learning to drive, backing out required major concentration:
- Opening garage, unlocking door, adjusting seat, inserting key, turning
clockwise
- Moving rearview/side mirrors, checking obstacles, foot on brake,
gearshift to reverse
- Mentally estimating distance, monitoring traffic, calculating reflected
images
- Translating mirror images to actual distances, applying slight pressure
to pedals
- Now done with hardly any thought — **routine occurs by habit**

### Why the Brain Creates Habits

- Brain constantly looking for ways to **save effort**
- Left to own devices, brain will make almost any routine into habit
- **Effort-saving instinct is huge advantage**:
  - Efficient brain requires less room → smaller head → easier childbirth
  → fewer infant/mother deaths
  - Allows us to stop thinking about basic behaviors (walking, eating)
  - Can devote mental energy to inventing spears, irrigation, airplanes,
  video games

### The Danger of Automatic Routines

- Conserving mental effort is tricky
- If brain powers down at wrong moment, might miss something important
(predator, speeding car)
- **Basal ganglia devised clever system** to determine when to let habits
take over
- Happens whenever chunk of behavior starts or ends

### Brain Activity Spikes at Beginning and End

- Graph shows activity spikes when rat hears click (beginning) and finds
chocolate (end)
- Spikes determine when to cede control to habit and which habit to use
- Behind partition: brain spends effort at beginning looking for cue
- If hears click → use maze habit; if hears meow → different pattern
- At end when reward appears, brain shakes awake to confirm everything
unfolded as expected

### The Three-Step Loop

- **Cue**: trigger telling brain to go into automatic mode and which
habit to use
- **Routine**: physical, mental, or emotional action
- **Reward**: helps brain determine if particular loop worth remembering
for future

> "Over time, this loop—cue, routine, reward; cue, routine, reward—
becomes more and more automatic. The cue and reward become intertwined
until a powerful sense of anticipation and craving emerges. Eventually,
whether in a chilly MIT laboratory or your driveway, a habit is born."

### Habits Can Be Changed

- Habits aren't destiny — can be **ignored, changed, or replaced**
- Discovery of habit loop reveals basic truth: when habit emerges, **brain
stops fully participating in decision making**
- Works hard or diverts focus to other tasks unless you deliberately
*fight* a habit
- Unless you find new routines, pattern will unfold automatically

### Breaking Habits Into Components

- Understanding habit loop structure makes habits easier to control
- Once you break habit into components, you can **fiddle with the gears**

> **Ann Graybiel** (MIT scientist): "We've done experiments where we
trained rats to run down a maze until it was a habit, and then we
extinguished the habit by changing the placement of the reward. Then one
day, we'll put the reward in the old place, and, by golly, the old habit
will reemerge right away. Habits never really disappear. They're encoded
into the structures of our brain, and that's a huge advantage for us,
because it would be awful if we had to relearn how to drive after every
vacation. The problem is that your brain can't tell the difference
between bad and good habits, and so if you have a bad one, it's always
lurking there, waiting for the right cues and rewards."

### Why Habits Are Hard to Break

- Hard to create exercise habits or change what we eat
- Once routine of sitting on couch or snacking at doughnut box develops,
patterns remain inside our heads
- Same rule applies: if we create new neurological routines that
overpower old behaviors, we can **force bad tendencies into background**
- Studies show going for jog or ignoring doughnuts becomes as automatic
as any other habit

### The Necessity of Habits

- Without habit loops, brains would shut down from minutiae of daily
life
- People with **basal ganglia damage** often mentally paralyzed
- Trouble with basic activities: opening door, deciding what to eat
- Lose ability to ignore insignificant details
- One study: patients couldn't recognize facial expressions (fear,
disgust) because perpetually uncertain which part of face to focus on
- Did you pause this morning to decide left vs. right shoe first? Brush
teeth before or after shower?
- Of course not — **decisions are habitual, effortless**

### Habits Can Be Dangerous

- Brain's dependence on automatic routines can be dangerous
- **Habits are often as much curse as benefit**

## Eugene's Later Life

### Eugene Forms New Habits Despite Amnesia

- Squire became convinced Eugene was learning new behaviors
- Brain scans showed basal ganglia escaped injury from encephalitis
- Could Eugene, with severe brain damage, still use **cue-routine-reward
loop**?
- Could this explain walking around block and finding jar of nuts?

### The Cardboard Test

- Squire designed experiment: 16 objects glued to cardboard rectangles
- Divided into 8 pairs (choice A and B)
- One piece in each pair had "correct" sticker on bottom
- Eugene shown pairs, asked to choose, then told to flip over to see
if correct
- Common memory test — most people memorize "correct" items after few
rounds
- Monkeys memorize all items after 8-10 days

### Eugene's Results

- Eugene **couldn't remember any "correct" items** no matter how many
times tested
- Repeated experiment twice weekly for months, 40 pairings each day
- Didn't recall why he was there or previous sessions
- But **performance improved**: 85% correct after 28 days, 95% at 36 days
- After one test asked researcher "How am I doing this?"

### Eugene Doesn't Remember His Success

- Researcher asked "Tell me what is going on in your head. Do you say
to yourself, 'I remember seeing that one'?"
- Eugene: "No. It's here somehow or another" (pointed to head) "and the
hand goes out."
- To Squire, this made perfect sense:
  - **Cue**: pair of objects always presented in same combination
  - **Routine**: choose one object, look for sticker (even if no idea
  why compelled to turn over)
  - **Reward**: satisfaction after finding sticker proclaiming "correct"
  - Eventually **habit loop emerged**

### Verification Test

- Squire put all 16 items in front of Eugene, asked to put "correct"
objects in one pile
- Eugene: "Gosh sakes, how to remember this?"
- Reached for object, started to turn over — experimenter stopped him
- Task was to put items in *piles*, not turn them over
- Eugene: "That's just a habit, I think."
- **Couldn't do it** — objects outside habit loop context made no sense

### Proof of Habit Formation

- Experiments proved Eugene could **form new habits** even when involving
tasks/objects he couldn't remember
- Explained morning walks — cues (trees, mailboxes) consistent every
time
- Though couldn't recognize house, habits guided him to front door
- Also explained eating breakfast 3-4 times daily despite not being
hungry
- As long as right cues present (radio, morning light through windows),
automatically followed script from basal ganglia

### Dozens of Unnoticed Habits

- Many other habits in Eugene's life no one noticed until researchers
looked
- Daughter would visit: talk in living room, go to kitchen to visit
mother, leave waving goodbye
- Eugene forgot earlier conversation by time she left
- Would get angry she was leaving without chatting, then forget why
upset
- **Emotional habit** had already started, persisted "red hot and beyond
his understanding, until it burned itself out"

> Beverly: "Sometimes he would bang the table or curse, and if you asked
him why, he'd say 'I don't know, but I'm mad!' He would kick his chair,
or snap at whoever came into the room. Then, a few minutes later, he
would smile and talk about the weather. It was like, once it started,
he had to finish the frustration."

### Habits Are Surprisingly Delicate

- Squire's experiments showed habits are surprisingly delicate
- If Eugene's cues changed slightest bit, habits fell apart
- Few times walked around block and something different (street repairs,
windstorm), Eugene got lost no matter how close to home
- Kind neighbor had to show him way to door
- If daughter stopped to chat 10 seconds before walking out, anger habit
never emerged

### Revolutionary Impact on Neuroscience

- Squire's experiments **revolutionized scientific understanding** of how
brain works
- Proved once and for all: **possible to learn and make unconscious
choices without remembering anything** about lesson or decision making
- Eugene showed **habits, as much as memory and reason, are at root of
how we behave**
- Might not remember experiences that create habits, but once lodged in
brains they **influence how we act — often without our realization**

## The Science of Habit Formation Explodes

### Research Expansion Since Squire's Work

- Since Squire's first paper on Eugene, habit formation became major
field of study
- Researchers at Duke, Harvard, UCLA, Yale, USC, Princeton, University
of Pennsylvania, schools in UK, Germany, Netherlands
- Corporate scientists at **Procter & Gamble, Microsoft, Google, hundreds
of companies**
- Focus: understanding neurology and psychology of habits, strengths/
weaknesses, why they emerge, how they can be changed

### Components of Habits

- **Cues** can be almost anything: candy bar, TV commercial, certain place,
time of day, emotion, sequence of thoughts, company of particular people
- **Routines** can be incredibly complex or simple (some measured in
milliseconds)
- **Rewards** range from food/drugs causing physical sensations to
emotional payoffs (pride from praise or self-congratulation)

### Key Findings About Habits

- In almost every experiment, echoes of **Squire's discoveries with
Eugene**:
- Habits are **powerful but delicate**
- Can emerge **outside our consciousness** or be **deliberately designed**
- Often occur **without our permission** but can be **reshaped by fiddling
with parts**
- Shape our lives **far more than we realize** — so strong they cause
brains to cling to them at exclusion of all else, including common sense

### The Mice Experiment (National Institute on Alcohol Abuse)

- Researchers trained mice to press levers in response to certain cues
until behavior became habit
- Mice always rewarded with food
- Then scientists **poisoned the food** (made animals violently ill) or
**electrified floor** (shock when walked toward reward)
- Mice knew food and cage were dangerous — offered poisoned pellets in
bowl or saw electrified panels, stayed away
- When saw old cues, **unthinkingly pressed lever and ate food or walked
across floor** even as vomited or jumped from electricity
- **Habit was so ingrained mice couldn't stop themselves**

### Fast Food Analogy

- Not hard to find analog in human world
- Fast food makes sense when kids starving and you're driving home after
long day
- Meals inexpensive, taste good
- One dose of processed meat, salty fries, sugary soda = relatively
small health risk
- Not like you do it all the time

### How Fast Food Habits Form

- But habits emerge without our permission
- Studies: families usually don't *intend* to eat fast food regularly
- Once a month pattern slowly becomes once a week, then twice a week
- As cues and rewards create habit, kids consuming unhealthy amounts of
hamburgers and fries
- When researchers at **University of North Texas and Yale** studied why
families increased fast food consumption, found **series of cues and
rewards most customers never knew were influencing behaviors**
- Discovered **the habit loop**

### McDonald's Deliberate Habit Engineering

- Every McDonald's looks the same — company deliberately standardizes
stores' architecture and employee scripts
- Everything is **consistent cue to trigger eating routines**
- Foods at some chains specifically engineered to deliver **immediate
rewards**:
- Fries designed to begin disintegrating moment hit tongue
- Delivers hit of salt and grease as fast as possible
- Causes **pleasure centers to light up** and brain to lock in pattern
- All the better for **tightening the habit loop**

### Habit Delicacy and Control

- Even these habits are delicate
- When fast food restaurant closes, families often start eating at home
rather than seek alternative location
- Even small shifts can end pattern
- Since often don't recognize habit loops as they grow, **blind to
ability to control them**
- By learning to observe cues and rewards, we can **change the routines**

## Eugene's Final Years

### Life Achieves Equilibrium

- By 2000, seven years after illness, Eugene's life achieved equilibrium
- Walked every morning
- Ate what he wanted, sometimes 5-6 times a day
- Wife knew as long as TV tuned to History Channel, Eugene would settle
into plush chair
- Couldn't tell difference between reruns or new programs

### Negative Habits Emerge

- As Eugene got older, habits started impacting life negatively
- Sedentary, watching TV for hours because never grew bored
- Physicians worried about heart
- Doctors told Beverly to keep him on strict diet of healthy foods
- Difficult to influence how frequently he ate or what consumed
- Never recalled admonitions
- Even if refrigerator had fruits/vegetables, Eugene would root around
until found bacon and eggs — **that was his routine**
- As bones became brittle, needed to be more careful walking
- In his mind, was twenty years younger — never remembered to step
carefully

> **Squire**: "All my life I was fascinated by memory. Then I met E.P.,
and saw how rich life can be even if you can't remember it. The brain
has this amazing ability to find happiness even when the memories of it
are gone."

### Beverly's Interventions

- Beverly tried to use understanding of habits to help Eugene avoid
problems
- **Short-circuit worst patterns by inserting new cues**:
- If didn't keep bacon in fridge, Eugene wouldn't eat multiple unhealthy
breakfasts
- When put salad next to chair, he'd sometimes pick at it
- As meal became habit, stopped searching kitchen for treats
- **Diet gradually improved**

### Eugene's Heart Attack and Hospitalization

- Despite efforts, Eugene's health declined
- Spring day watching TV, suddenly shouted
- Beverly ran in, saw him clutching chest — called ambulance
- Hospital diagnosed **minor heart attack**
- Pain passed, Eugene fighting to get off gurney
- That night kept pulling off monitors to roll over and sleep
- Nurses tried taping leads, threatening restraints — nothing worked
- Forgot threats as soon as issued

### The Pride Intervention

- Daughter told nurse to try **complimenting him on willingness to sit
still**
- Repeat compliment over and over each time saw him

> **Carol Rayes** (daughter): "We wanted to, you know, get his pride
involved. We'd say, 'Oh, Dad, you're really doing something important
for science by keeping these doodads in place.'"

- Nurses started to dote on him — **he loved it**
- After couple days, did whatever they asked
- Eugene returned home a week later

### Eugene's Fall and Final Days

- Fall 2008, while walking through living room, Eugene **tripped on ledge
near fireplace, fell, broke hip**
- Hospital: Squire and team worried he'd have panic attacks because
wouldn't know where he was
- Left notes by bedside explaining what happened
- Posted photos of children on walls
- Wife and kids came every day
- Eugene never grew worried, never asked why in hospital

> **Squire**: "He seemed at peace with all the uncertainty by that point.
It had been fifteen years since he had lost his memory. It was as if
part of his brain knew there were some things he would never understand
and was okay with that."

### Beverly's Final Conversations

- Beverly came to hospital every day
- Told Eugene she loved him, about kids and their good life
- Pointed to pictures, talked about how much he was adored
- Married 57 years, 42 of those "real, normal marriage"

> "Sometimes it was hard, because I wanted my old husband back so much.
But at least I knew he was happy."

### Eugene's Death

- Few weeks later, daughter came to visit: "What's the plan?"
- Eugene: took her outside in wheelchair to hospital lawn
- "It's a beautiful day. Pretty nice weather, huh?"
- She told him about kids playing with dog
- Thought he might come home soon, sun going down
- Started to get ready to take him inside
- Eugene looked at her

> "I'm lucky to have a daughter like you. I'm lucky that you're my dad.
Gosh, it's a beautiful day. What do you think about the weather?"

- That night, 1 AM, Beverly's phone rang
- Doctor: Eugene suffered **massive heart attack**, staff did everything
possible but couldn't revive him
- **He was gone**
- After death, celebrated by researchers, brain images studied in hundreds
of labs and medical schools

> **Beverly**: "I know he would have been really proud to know how much
he contributed to science. He told me once, pretty soon after we got
married, that he wanted to do something important with his life,
something that mattered. And he did. He just never remembered any of
it."

<!-- pp. 41-60 -->

## Chapter 2: The Craving Brain — How to Create New Habits

### Claude Hopkins and the Pepsodent Campaign

- **Claude C. Hopkins**: legendary advertising executive in early
1900s, master of creating consumer habits through marketing
- Convinced Americans to buy Schlitz beer ("cleaned with live
steam"), Palmolive soap (Cleopatra used it), Puffed Wheat ("shot
from guns")
- Authored *My Life in Advertising*, detailing money-spending
difficulties
- Hopkins initially rejected Pepsodent toothpaste campaign —
selling toothpaste was "financial suicide" despite America's
rotting teeth (WWI recruits' poor dental hygiene was a national
security risk)
- Nobody brushed despite dental problems — the issue was that
hardly anyone bought toothpaste because hardly anyone brushed

### Hopkins's Strategy: Cue, Routine, Reward

- Hopkins identified **tooth film** as the cue — a natural mucin
buildup on teeth that had always existed but nobody noticed
- Could be removed by eating an apple or running your tongue over
teeth, but Hopkins positioned toothpaste as the solution
- Campaign ads: "Just run your tongue across your teeth — you'll
*feel a film*"
- The **cue** (tooth film) was universal, simple, impossible to
ignore
- The **reward**: beautiful teeth, prettier smile
- Within five years, Pepsodent became one of best-known products
globally
- Before Pepsodent: only 7% of Americans had toothpaste; a decade
later: 65%
- By WWII end, military downgraded teeth concerns because soldiers
were brushing daily

> "I made for myself a million dollars on Pepsodent. The key was
> that I had learned the right human psychology." — Claude Hopkins

### Hopkins's Two Rules for Creating Habits

1. **Find a simple and obvious cue**
2. **Clearly define the rewards**

- Hopkins's principles became conventional wisdom among marketers,
educators, public health professionals, politicians, CEOs
- Still influence everything from cleaning supply marketing to
government disease eradication tools
- Hopkins used these rules across products: Quaker Oats (energy
for 24 hours), tonics for stomachaches/joint pain (drink at first
symptom)

> "The time has come when advertising has in some hands reached the
> status of a science. Advertising, once a gamble, has thus become,
> under able direction, one of the safest of business ventures." —
> Claude Hopkins

### The Missing Third Rule

- Hopkins's two rules aren't enough — there's a **third rule**
Hopkins relied on without knowing it
- Explains why it's hard to ignore doughnuts but easy to maintain
a morning jog routine

### The Febreze Failure at P&G

- **Drake Stimson**: P&G rising star, math and psychology
background, led Febreze marketing team in 1996
- **P&G**: massive consumer goods firm (Pringles, Oil of Olay,
Bounty, CoverGirl, Dawn, Downy, Duracell), collected more data
than almost any merchant, $35 billion in revenues
- **HPBCD (hydroxypropyl beta cyclodextrin)**: chemist discovered it
removed odors when his wife noticed he didn't smell like smoke
- Spent millions perfecting formula — colorless, odorless liquid
that could eliminate almost any smell
- NASA eventually used it to clean shuttle interiors
- Cheap to manufacture, didn't leave stains

### The Park Ranger Discovery

- Stimson's team visited hundreds of Phoenix/Salt Lake/Boise
households
- **Park ranger in Phoenix**: late twenties, single, trapped
animals (coyotes, raccoons, mountain lions, skunks)
- Everything in her life smelled like skunk — house, truck,
clothing, boots, hands, curtains, bed
- Her love life was crippled by the skunk smell
- Went on four dates with a nice guy, but after inviting him over
he "took a break" — she wondered if it was the smell

> "I want to thank you. This spray has changed my life."

- After receiving Febreze samples, she sprayed everything — couch,
curtains, rug, bedspread, jeans, uniform, car interior
- Invited friends over who couldn't smell the skunk anymore
- Stimson thought: *We're going to make a fortune with this stuff*

### The Marketing Campaign Flops

- Designed two TV commercials following Hopkins's rules: obvious
cue, clear reward
- **Ad 1**: Woman with smoking section jacket — cue: cigarette
smell, reward: odor eliminated
- **Ad 2**: Woman worried about dog Sophie on couch — cue: pet
smells (70 million households with animals), reward: house doesn't
smell like kennel
- Launched in 1996 test cities, gave away samples, built Febreze
mountains in stores
- Sales started small and got smaller over two months
- P&G researchers visited homes — shelves filled with untouched
Febreze bottles
- One woman forgot about it: "I used it for a while, but then I
forgot about it. I think it's back here somewhere."

### The Fundamental Problem: No Cue

- **Febreze was a dud** — disaster for Stimson
- Divisional president called emergency meeting to cut losses
- New research team brought in from Stanford, Carnegie Mellon, and
elsewhere (consumer psychology experts)
- First insight: woman with nine cats outside Phoenix
- Her house was clean and organized despite nine cats
- She vacuumed daily, didn't open windows (wind blew in dust)
- When scientists entered living room, cat scent was overwhelming
— one gagged
- **She didn't notice the smell** — only once a month
- Same pattern in dozens of smelly homes: people couldn't detect
bad smells in their lives

### Desensitization Insight

- If you live with nine cats, you become desensitized to their
scent
- If you smoke cigarettes, it damages olfactory capacity so you
can't smell smoke
- Scents fade with constant exposure — even the strongest
- **The product's cue was hidden from those who needed it most**
- Bad scents weren't noticed frequently enough to trigger regular
habit
- People with greatest need to use Febreze never smelled the odors
that should have reminded them
- The spray ended up in backs of closets

### Wolfram Schultz and the Neuroscience of Craving

- **Wolfram Schultz**: neuroscience professor at University of
Cambridge
- Messy desk described as "black hole" by colleagues
- Revolutionized understanding of how cues, rewards, and habits
interact over 20 years
- Provided scientific road map explaining why Pepsodent succeeded
and what it took to make Febreze sell

### Julio the Monkey Experiment

- **Julio**: eight-pound macaque with hazel eyes, thin electrode
in brain to observe neuronal activity
- Task: touch lever when colored shapes appeared on screen
(yellow spirals, red squiggles, blue lines)
- Correct lever touch → drop of blackberry juice
- Julio loved blackberry juice
- Initially only mildly interested, squirming in chair
- Once first juice arrived, Julio became focused on monitor
- As repetitions continued, habit formed: shapes = cue, touch
lever = routine, blackberry juice = reward
- Julio stared at screen with "laserlike intensity," pouncing when
shapes appeared
- When juice arrived, Julio licked his lips contentedly

### The "I Got a Reward!" Pattern

- Schultz's probes recorded neurological pattern when Julio
received reward
- Brain activity spiked, suggesting happiness
- Transcript of neurological activity shows what it looks like
when a monkey's brain says "I got a reward!"
- From neurological perspective, Julio's behavior became a habit
through repetition

### The Critical Discovery: Anticipation

- As habit strengthened, Julio's brain began **anticipating** the
blackberry juice
- Schultz's probes started recording "I got a reward!" pattern
*before* juice arrived — the instant Julio saw shapes on screen
- The cue (shapes) alone triggered pleasure response in brain
- Julio's behavior shifted from basic learning to habit when
anticipation emerged

### Testing the Anticipation with Disruptions

- Schultz adjusted experiment: sometimes juice didn't arrive,
arrived late, or was diluted (half as sweet)
- When juice didn't arrive or was delayed, Julio got angry, made
unhappy noises, became mopey
- Schultz watched new neurological pattern emerge: **craving**
- When Julio anticipated juice but didn't receive it, desire and
frustration pattern erupted in skull
- Anticipation-triggered joy became craving that, if unsatisfied,
drove Julio to anger or depression

### Craving Makes the Habit Loop Work

- Researchers in other labs found similar patterns with other
monkeys
- Once monkey developed habit — once brain *anticipated* reward —
distractions held no allure
- Monkeys stayed glued to screens, same way gamblers play slots
after losing winnings
- **This explains why habits are so powerful: they create
neurological cravings**
- Most cravings emerge gradually, so we're often blind to their
influence
- As we associate cues with rewards, subconscious craving emerges
in brains that starts habit loop spinning

### The Cinnabon Example

- Cornell researcher noticed how Cinnabon stores were positioned in
shopping malls
- Most food sellers in food courts, but Cinnabon away from other
food stalls
- Cinnabon executives want cinnamon roll smell to waft down
hallways uninterrupted
- Shoppers subconsciously start craving a roll
- By the time consumer turns corner and sees Cinnabon, craving is
"a roaring monster inside his head"
- He'll reach, unthinkingly, for wallet — habit loop spinning
because craving emerged

### Craving and Anticipation Drive the Loop

> "There is nothing programmed into our brains that makes us see a
> box of doughnuts and automatically want a sugary treat. But once
> our brain learns that a doughnut box contains yummy sugar and
> other carbohydrates, it will start *anticipating* the sugar
> high. Our brains will push us toward the box. Then, if we don't
> eat the doughnut, we'll feel disappointed." — Wolfram Schultz

- **Craving for endorphins/neurochemicals makes exercise habitual**
(92% in one study)
- **Craving for sense of accomplishment makes exercise habitual**
(67% in another group)
- Cue and reward alone aren't enough for lasting habit
- Only when brain starts *expecting* the reward — craving
endorphins or sense of accomplishment — does it become automatic
to lace up jogging shoes
- The cue must also trigger a craving for the reward

### Schultz's Personal Example

- Schultz has two-year-old son
- When feeding son dinner (chicken nuggets), Schultz reaches over
and eats one himself without thinking
- "It's a habit. And now I'm gaining weight."
- Same process lets him create good habits: "I work hard because I
expect pride from a discovery. I exercise because I expect feeling
good afterward. I just wish I could pick and choose better."

### The Febreze Turnaround

- After cat woman interview disaster, Stimson's team looked
outside usual channels
- Read Wolfram Schultz experiments
- Asked Harvard Business School professor to conduct psychological
tests
- Interviewed customer after customer looking for cue that would
make Febreze regular part of consumers' lives

### The Scottsdale Woman Discovery

- Woman in forties with four kids in suburb near Scottsdale
- House clean but not compulsively tidy
- To researchers' surprise, she loved Febreze and used it daily
- No smelly problems — no pets, no smoking
- She used it for "normal cleaning — a couple of sprays when I'm
done in a room. It's a nice way to make everything smell good as
a final touch."

### The New Strategy: Febreze as a Reward

- Key insight: position Febreze to convey sense of relief park
ranger felt
- Make Febreze something that allows people to rid themselves of
embarrassing smells
- New commercials kept simple: obvious cue, clear reward
- Stimson and colleagues began airing new ads in 1996 (same test
cities)
- Gave away samples, paid grocers to build Febreze mountains near
registers
- Sat back anticipating bonuses
- Two months passed — sales started small and got smaller
- Panicked company sent researchers to see what was happening
- Housewives had received free samples but forgot about them

<!-- pp. 61-80 -->

## Chapter 1: The Habit Loop (continued)

### The Febreze Turnaround: Creating Craving

P&G's **Drake Stimson** studied videotapes of customers cleaning homes.
Key observation: women smiled and felt satisfied *after* cleaning, not during.
The reward wasn't about eliminating bad smells—it was about a
mini-celebration at the end of the cleaning routine.

**Strategic pivot**: Repositioned Febreze as a *reward* rather than a problem
solver.
Added more perfume to the formula, creating a distinct pleasant scent.
Changed advertising from "Gets bad smells out of fabrics" to "Cleans life's
smells."
Commercials showed women spraying freshly made beds and laundered clothing—
using Febreze as a finishing touch, not a problem fixer.

> "Spraying feels like a little mini-celebration when I'm done with a room."
> — Febreze customer

**Results**: Summer 1998 relaunch. Sales doubled within two months. Within a
year, $230 million in sales. Febreze spawned dozens of spinoffs and now
generates over $1 billion annually. P&G's formula worked because they created
*craving*—the desire to make everything smell as nice as it looked.

### Claude Hopkins and Pepsodent: The Missing Ingredient

**Claude Hopkins** never discussed cravings in his autobiography, yet
accidentally used the principle. In final years, he lectured on "Laws of
Scientific Advertising," comparing himself to Edison and Washington. But he
didn't know about the neurological basis of habit loops—MIT research was
seventy years away.

Hopkins experienced with **Pepsodent** weren't straightforward. He boasted
about discovering tooth film as a cue and offering beautiful teeth as a
reward, but competitors had used identical language before him. Ads predating
Pepsodent:

- **Dr. Sheffield's Crème Dentifrice**: "prevent deposits of *tartar* around
necks of teeth"
- **Sanitol Tooth Paste**: "white enamel is only *hidden* by a coating of
film"
- **S.S. White Toothpaste**: "Beautiful, satin smooth teeth are often the
secret of a pretty girl's attractiveness"

None of these campaigns worked. Hopkins succeeded where others failed.

**The secret ingredient**: Pepsodent contained **citric acid** and **mint
oil** that created a cool, tingling sensation on tongue and gums. The
ingredients were irritants. Competitors later discovered customers said they
felt their mistake if they forgot to use Pepsodent—they missed that cool,
tingling sensation. They expected—they *craved*—that slight irritation. If
not there, mouths didn't feel clean.

Hopkins wasn't selling beautiful teeth. He was selling a *sensation*.

> "Consumers need some kind of signal that a product is working. The tingling
> doesn't make the toothpaste work any better. It just convinces people it's
> doing the job." — **Tracy Sinclair**, brand manager for Oral-B and Crest

Within decades, almost every toothpaste contained tingling additives. Today,
almost all toothpastes contain chemicals whose sole job is making your mouth
tingle after you brush.

### Applying the Craving Formula

**Exercise habit**: Choose cue (gym immediately upon waking) and reward
(smoothie, endorphin rush). Anticipate the reward. That craving makes pushing
through gym doors easier.

**Eating habit**: **National Weight Control Registry** study of 6,000+ people
who lost 30+ pounds found 78% ate breakfast every morning (time-cued meal).
Successful dieters envisioned specific rewards—bikini they wanted to wear,
pride from stepping on scale. They focused on craving for that reward when
temptations arose, cultivating mild obsession. The craving drove the habit
loop.

### The Craving Gap: Why We Don't Apply Sunscreen

Many behaviors we *ought* to do never become habits. Less than 10% of
Americans apply sunscreen daily, yet everyone brushes teeth. Why?

**No craving for sunscreen**. Some companies try creating tingling sensations
or other signals to cue expectation, hoping to replicate the toothpaste
success.

**Foaming as craving trigger**: Shampoo, laundry detergent, and toothpaste
don't need to foam—companies add foaming chemicals (like sodium laureth
sulfate) because people expect suds. Once customer expects foam, the habit
starts growing. Same principle across product categories.

**Febreze's final place**: After people clean kitchen or tidy bedrooms, some
spray Febreze as a reward—having learned to crave the pleasant scent that
signals completion.

