## Chapter 3: The Golden Rule of Habit Change

### I. Tony Dungy and the Tampa Bay Buccaneers

November 17, 1996. **Tony Dungy** becomes head coach of **Tampa Bay
Buccaneers**—one of NFL's worst teams. Record: 2-8. Haven't won on West Coast
in sixteen years. One columnist nicknamed them "America's Orange Doormat."
ESPN predicts Dungy could be fired before year ends.

Dungy had spent seventeen years as assistant coach (University of Minnesota,
Pittsburgh Steelers, Kansas City Chiefs, Minnesota Vikings). Four previous
head coaching interviews, all unsuccessful. Problem: his coaching philosophy.

**Dungy's philosophy**: Key to winning is changing players' habits. Stop
making so many decisions during a game. Get them to react automatically,
habitually. Instill the right habits, and the team would win.

> "Champions don't do extraordinary things. They do ordinary things, but they
> do them without thinking, too fast for the other team to react. They follow
> the habits they've learned."

Owners' objection: How create *new* habits? Dungy's answer: He wasn't going
to create new habits. Players spent their lives building habits that got them
to NFL. No athlete abandons those patterns simply because a new coach says to.

**Strategy**: Change players' *old* habits rather than creating new ones.
Secret to changing habits: use what's already inside players' heads. Habits
are three-step loop—cue, routine, reward—but Dungy only wanted to attack the
middle step, the *routine*.

### The Golden Rule of Habit Change

His coaching strategy embodies **The Golden Rule of habit change**: You can
never truly extinguish bad habits. Rather, to change a habit, you must keep
the old cue, deliver the old reward, but insert a new routine.

**If you use the same cue and provide the same reward, you can shift the
routine and change the habit.** Almost any behavior can be transformed if cue
and reward stay the same.

Influences treatments for alcoholism, obesity, obsessive-compulsive disorders,
hundreds of other destructive behaviors. Attempts to give up snacking often
fail unless there's a new routine to satisfy old cues and reward urges.
Smoker usually can't quit unless she finds activity to replace cigarettes
when nicotine craving triggered.

**Dungy's four failed interviews**: Explained habit-based philosophy to team
owners. They listened politely, thanked him, hired someone else.

Then, 1996, the woeful Buccaneers called. Dungy flew to Tampa Bay, laid out
his plan. Day after final interview, they offered him the job.

### Dungy's System in Action: The Key Play

Late game, 8:19 remaining. San Diego Chargers on their own twenty-yard line.
If Bucs' defense doesn't act now, game effectively over.

**Dungy's approach**: Opposite of complicated playbooks. When defensive
players line up, obvious to everyone which play they're using. Dungy taught
only a handful of formations, practiced them until behaviors automatic.
Milliseconds matter in football. His strategy: be faster than everyone else
by making reactions automatic.

**Regan Upshaw** (Buccaneers defensive end) settles into three-point stance.
Instead of absorbing maximum information, Upshaw focuses only on specific
cues Dungy taught: outside foot of opposite lineman (toes back = preparing to
step backward and block); lineman's shoulders (rotated inward); space between
lineman and next player (narrower than expected).

Upshaw practiced reacting to these cues so many times he doesn't have to
think. He just follows his habits.

San Diego quarterback **Stan Humphries** takes snap, drops back. Within first
second, Upshaw springs across scrimmage line. Within next second, runs four
more paces downfield. Within next second, moves three strides closer to
quarterback, path impossible for offensive lineman to predict.

As play moves into fourth second, Humphries sees Upshaw from corner of eye.
That's when Humphries makes his mistake: He starts *thinking*.

Humphries spots rookie tight end **Brian Roche** twenty yards downfield.
Another receiver much closer waving arms (safe choice). Under pressure,
Humphries performs split-second analysis, cocks arm, heaves to Roche.

That hurried decision precisely what Dungy hoped for. Buccaneer safety **John
Lynch** starts moving—his routine automatic. Lynch positioned ten yards from
Roche before ball leaves quarterback's hands, waiting. Lynch reads cues
(quarterback's face mask, hands, receivers' spacing), starts moving before
clear where ball will land. Before Roche can react, Lynch takes off toward
Chargers' end zone. Lynch runs 10, 15, 20, then almost 25 yards before pushed
out of bounds. Entire play: less than ten seconds.

Two minutes later, Bucs score touchdown. Five minutes later, field goal. In
between, Dungy's defense shuts down each San Diego comeback attempt.
**Buccaneers win, 25 to 17**—one of biggest upsets of the season.

> "It feels like something was different out there." — Lynch

> "We're starting to believe." — Dungy

---

## Chapter 3: The Golden Rule of Habit Change (continued)

### II. Bill Wilson and Alcoholics Anonymous

1934, Lower East Side basement, New York City. One of largest attempts at
wide-scale habit change was born.

**Bill Wilson**, thirty-nine-year-old alcoholic. First drink during officers'
training camp, New Bedford, Massachusetts, before shipping to France and WWI.
Sunday night party: rarebit and beer. First sip of Bronx cocktail (gin, dry
and sweet vermouth, orange juice) felt like "the elixir of life."

By mid-1930s, marriage falling apart, fortune from stocks vaporized. Consumed
three bottles of booze daily. November afternoon in gloom, old drinking buddy
called, invited Wilson over. Mixed pitcher of pineapple juice and gin. Friend
poured Wilson a glass.

Friend handed it back: sober two months. Wilson astonished. Friend talked
about hell, temptation, sin, the devil. Told Wilson: "Realize you are licked,
admit it, and get willing to turn your life over to God."

Wilson thought the guy was nuts but polished off the booze and went to bed.

December 1934: **Charles B. Towns Hospital for Drug and Alcohol Addictions**,
upscale Manhattan detox. Physician started hourly infusions of hallucinogenic
drug **belladonna**. Wilson floated in and out of consciousness.

Then Wilson began writhing in agony. Withdrawal pains felt like insects
crawling across skin. Nauseous, but pain too intense to stay still.

> "If there is a God, let Him show Himself! I am ready to do anything.
> Anything!" — Wilson yelled to empty room

At that moment, white light filled room, pain ceased, felt as if on
mountaintop, "and that a wind not of air but of spirit was blowing." Felt
like free man. "Slowly the ecstasy subsided. I lay on the bed, but now for a
time I was in another world, a new world of consciousness."

**Bill Wilson would never have another drink.** For next thirty-six years,
until he died of emphysema in 1971, devoted himself to founding, building,
spreading **Alcoholics Anonymous**.

**AA's scale and success**: Estimated 2.1 million people seek help from AA
each year; as many as 10 million alcoholics may have achieved sobriety
through the group. Success rates difficult to measure due to anonymity, but
millions credit program with saving lives. AA's twelve steps have become
cultural lodestones incorporated into treatment programs for overeating,
gambling, debt, sex, drugs, hoarding, self-mutilation, smoking, video game
addictions, emotional dependency, dozens of other destructive behaviors.
Group's techniques offer one of most powerful formulas for change.

**Unexpected foundation**: AA has almost no grounding in science or most
accepted therapeutic methods.

### AA's Unconventional Methods

Alcoholism is physical addiction with psychological and perhaps genetic roots.
What's interesting: AA doesn't directly attack many psychiatric or
biochemical issues researchers say are core of why alcoholics drink. AA's
methods seem to sidestep scientific and medical findings altogether, as well
as types of intervention many psychiatrists say alcoholics really need.

**What AA provides**: Method for attacking the *habits* that surround alcohol
use. AA is giant machine for changing habit loops. Though habits associated
with alcoholism are extreme, lessons AA provides demonstrate how almost any
habit—even most obstinate—can be changed.

### Wilson's Twelve Steps and AA's Structure

Wilson didn't read academic journals or consult doctors before founding AA.
Few years after achieving sobriety, wrote now-famous **twelve steps** in rush
one night while sitting in bed. Chose number twelve because there were twelve
apostles. Some aspects not just unscientific—can seem downright strange.

**"Ninety meetings in ninety days"**: stretch of time chosen seemingly at
random.

**Step Three**: "a decision to turn our will and our lives over to the care
of God as we understand him." Seven of twelve steps mention God or
spirituality—odd for program founded by onetime agnostic openly hostile
toward organized religion.

AA meetings don't have prescribed schedule or curriculum. Usually begin with
member telling story, after which others can chime in. No professionals guide
conversations, few rules about how meetings supposed to function.

**Contrast with modern science**: In past five decades, almost every aspect of
psychiatry and addiction research revolutionized by discoveries in behavioral
sciences, pharmacology, understanding of brain. AA has remained frozen in
time.

### Academic Reevaluation of AA

Because of program's lack of rigor, academics and researchers often criticized
it. AA's emphasis on spirituality made it seem more like cult than treatment.

However, **past fifteen years**, reevaluation has begun. Researchers say
program's methods offer valuable lessons. Faculty at Harvard, Yale, University
of Chicago, University of New Mexico, dozens of other research centers found
**science within AA similar to one Tony Dungy used on football field**.
Findings endorse the **Golden Rule of habit change**: AA succeeds because it
helps alcoholics use the same cues, get the same reward, but shifts the
routine.

### How AA Works: Identifying Cues and Rewards

Researchers say AA works because program forces people to identify cues and
rewards that encourage alcoholic habits, then helps them find new behaviors.

When Claude Hopkins was selling Pepsodent, he found way to create new habit
by triggering new craving. But to change old habit, you must address an old
craving. **You have to keep same cues and rewards as before, feed the craving
by inserting new routine.**

**Steps four and five**: "a searching and fearless inventory of ourselves"
and admit "to God, to ourselves, and to another human being the exact nature
of our wrongs."

> "It's not obvious from the way they're written, but to complete those steps,
> someone has to create a list of all the triggers for their alcoholic urges.
> When you make a self-inventory, you're figuring out all the things that make
> you drink. And admitting to someone else all the bad things you've done is a
> pretty good way of figuring out the moments where everything spiraled out of
> control." — **J. Scott Tonigan**, University of New Mexico researcher

Then AA asks alcoholics to search for rewards they get from alcohol. What
cravings drive habit loop? Often, intoxication itself doesn't make the list.
Alcoholics crave drink because it offers escape, relaxation, companionship,
blunting of anxieties, opportunity for emotional release. Might crave
cocktail to forget worries. But they don't necessarily crave feeling drunk.
Physical effects of alcohol often one of least rewarding parts of drinking
for addicts.

> "There is a hedonistic element to alcohol. But people also use alcohol
> because they want to forget something or to satisfy other cravings, and
> these relief cravings occur in totally different parts of the brain than the
> craving for physical pleasure." — **Ulf Mueller**, German neurologist

To offer alcoholics same rewards they get at bar, AA has built system of
meetings and companionship—the "sponsor" each member works with—that strives
to offer as much escape, distraction, and catharsis as Friday night bender.
If someone needs relief, they can get it from talking to sponsor or attending
group gathering, rather than toasting a drinking buddy.

> "AA forces you to create new routines for what to do each night instead of
> drinking. You can relax and talk through your anxieties at the meetings. The
> triggers and payoffs stay the same, it's just the behavior that changes." —
> Tonigan

### The Magdeburg Brain Surgery Study

2007: **Ulf Mueller** and colleagues at University of Magdeburg implanted
small electrical devices inside brains of five alcoholics who had repeatedly
tried to give up booze. Each spent at least six months in rehab without
success. One had been through detox more than sixty times.

Devices positioned inside **basal ganglia** (same part where MIT researchers
found habit loop). Emitted electrical charge that interrupted neurological
reward triggering habitual cravings. After men recovered from operations,
exposed to cues that had once triggered alcoholic urges (photos of beer,
trips to bar). Normally impossible to resist drink. But devices "overrode"
each man's neurological cravings. They didn't touch a drop.

> "One of them told me the craving disappeared as soon as we turned the
> electricity on. Then, we turned it off, and the craving came back
> immediately." — Mueller

**Eradicating neurological cravings wasn't enough** to stop drinking habits.
Four of them relapsed soon after surgery, usually after stressful event. They
picked up bottle because that's how they automatically dealt with anxiety.

However, once they learned alternate routines for dealing with stress,
drinking stopped for good. One patient attended AA meetings. Others went to
therapy. Once they incorporated new routines for coping with stress and
anxiety into their lives, successes were dramatic. Man who had gone to detox
sixty times never had another drink. Two other patients started drinking at
twelve, were alcoholics by eighteen, drank every day, now sober for four
years.

**Notice Golden Rule adherence**: Even when alcoholics' brains changed through
surgery, wasn't enough. Old cues and cravings for rewards still there,
waiting to pounce. Alcoholics only permanently changed once they learned new
routines that drew on old triggers and provided familiar relief.

> "Some brains are so addicted to alcohol that only surgery can stop it. But
> those people also need new ways for dealing with life." — Mueller

AA provides similar, though less invasive, system for inserting new routines
into old habit loops. As scientists have begun understanding how AA works,
they've started applying program's methods to other habits, such as two-year-
olds' tantrums, sex addictions, even minor behavioral tics. As AA's methods
have spread, they've been refined into therapies that can be used to disrupt
almost any pattern.

### III. Mandy and Habit Reversal Training

Summer 2006: twenty-four-year-old graduate student named **Mandy** walked into
counseling center at **Mississippi State University**. Most of her life,
bitten her nails, gnawing until they bled. For chronic nail biters, however,
it's problem of different scale. Mandy would often bite until nails pulled
away from skin underneath. Fingertips covered with tiny scabs. Ends of
fingers had become blunted without nails to protect them, sometimes tingled
or itched (sign of nerve injury). Biting habit damaged her social life.
Embarrassed, kept hands in pockets, on dates became preoccupied with balling
fingers into fists. Tried to stop by painting nails with foul-tasting
polishes or promising herself, starting *right now*, muster willpower to quit.
But soon as began homework or watching television, fingers ended up in mouth.

Counseling center referred Mandy to doctoral psychology student studying
treatment known as **"habit reversal training."** Psychologist well
acquainted with Golden Rule of habit change. Knew changing Mandy's nail
biting habit required inserting new routine into her life.

> "What do you feel right before you bring your hand up to your mouth to bite
> your nails?" — therapist

> "There's a little bit of tension in my fingers. It hurts a little bit here,
> at the edge of the nail. Sometimes I'll run my thumb along, looking for
> hangnails, and when I feel something catch, I'll bring it up to my mouth.
> Then I'll go finger by finger, biting all the rough edges. Once I start, it
> feels like I have to do all of them." — Mandy

Asking patients to describe what triggers habitual behavior called **awareness
training**. Like AA's insistence on forcing alcoholics to recognize their
cues, it's first step in habit reversal training. Tension Mandy felt in nails
cued her nail biting habit.

> "Most people's habits have occurred for so long they don't pay attention to
> what causes it anymore." — **Brad Dufrene**, who treated Mandy

Next, therapist asked Mandy to describe *why* she bit nails. At first,
trouble coming up with reasons. As they talked, became clear she bit when
bored. Therapist put her in typical situations (watching television, doing
homework), and she started nibbling. When worked through all nails, felt
brief sense of completeness. That was habit's reward: physical stimulation
she had come to crave.

At end of first session, therapist sent Mandy home with assignment: Carry
around index card, each time you feel cue (tension in fingertips), make check
mark on card. Came back week later with twenty-eight checks. Was, by that
point, acutely aware of sensations that preceded her habit. Knew how many
times occurred during class or while watching television.

Then therapist taught Mandy what is known as **"competing response."**
Whenever felt tension in fingertips, should immediately put hands in pockets
or under legs, or grip pencil or something else that made it impossible to
put fingers in mouth. Then search for something that would provide quick
physical stimulation—such as rubbing arm or rapping knuckles on desk—anything
that would produce physical response.

**The cues and rewards stayed the same. Only the routine changed.**

<!-- pp. 81-100 -->

## Chapter 3: The Golden Rule of Habit Change (continued)

### Mandy's Success with Nail Biting

- After practicing in therapist's office for 30 minutes, Mandy got
assignment: use index card to track tension in fingertips and mark
when successfully overriding the habit
- Week later: bitten nails only 3 times, used competing response 7
times, rewarded self with manicure
- After a month: nail-biting habit completely gone, competing
routines became automatic
- One habit had replaced another

> "It seems ridiculously simple, but once you're aware of how your
habit works, once you recognize the cues and rewards, you're halfway
to changing it. The truth is, the brain can be reprogrammed. You
just have to be deliberate about it." — **Nathan Azrin**

### Habit Reversal Therapy Applications

- **Habit reversal therapy** now treats: verbal/physical tics,
depression, smoking, gambling, anxiety, bedwetting, procrastination,
OCD, and other behavioral problems
- Core principle: we don't understand the cravings driving behaviors
until we look for them
- Mandy never realized **craving for physical stimulation** was
causing nail biting — once dissected, easy to find new routine
providing same reward

### Identifying the True Reward

- To stop snacking: is the reward satisfying hunger or interrupting
boredom?
- If brief release, can find another routine (quick walk, 3 minutes
on Internet) providing same interruption without calories
- **Smoking cessation studies**: dozens show that identifying
cues/rewards for cigarettes, then choosing new routines (Nicorette,
push-ups, stretching) makes quitting more likely
- Caffeine in afternoon can increase odds smokers quit if they need
stimulation

> "If you identify the cues and rewards, you can change the routine."

### The Missing Ingredient: Belief

- For most habits, identifying cues and changing routines works
- But for some habits, **one other ingredient necessary: belief**

### Tony Dungy and the Tampa Bay Buccaneers

- 1996: **Tony Dungy** became head coach of Tampa Bay Buccaneers
- Team plagued by theories: management messed up, untested coach,
spoiled city, injured players, lack of talent

> "Those are the supposed reasons. Now here is a fact: Nobody is
going to outwork us." — **Tony Dungy**

- Dungy's strategy: shift team's behaviors until performances became
automatic
- Didn't need thickest playbook or hundreds of formations — just a
few key moves done right every time

### The Mental Game Problem

- Perfection hard to achieve in football
- **Herm Edwards** (assistant coach): "Every play in football—every
play—someone messes up. Most of the time, it's not physical. It's
mental."
- Players mess up when thinking too much or second-guessing plays
- Dungy wanted to take decision making out of the game

### Teaching Visual Keys

- Dungy started by watching how team already played
- Example: **Derrick Brooks** (outside linebacker) watching QB's
legs/hips after ball snap, looking for gaps in line
- These visual cues = **"keys"** — critical to every play
- Dungy's innovation: use keys as cues for reworked habits

> "I want you to use those same keys. But at first, focus only on
the running back. That's it. Do it without thinking. Once you're in
position, *then* start looking for the QB." — **Tony Dungy** to
Brooks

### Removing Decision Making

- Modest shift: Brooks's eyes went to same cues, but Dungy put them
in sequence and told him choice to make when seeing each key
- Brilliance: removed need for decision making
- Allowed Brooks to move faster — everything became reaction, not
choice
- Dungy gave every player similar instructions, practiced formations
over and over

### Early Struggles and Breakthrough

- Took almost a year for habits to take hold
- Team lost early, easy games
- Sports columnists asked why Bucs wasting time on "psychological
quackery"
- Slowly began improving — patterns became familiar, unfolded
automatically
- Dungy's second season: won first 5 games, made play-offs for first
time in 15 years
- 1999: won division championship

### Media Attention and Family Life

- Dungy's coaching style drew national attention
- Media loved: soft-spoken demeanor, religious piety, balancing work
and family
- Brought sons **Eric** and **Jamie** to stadium to hang out during
practice
- They did homework in his office, picked up towels in locker room
- Success had finally arrived

### The Choking Problem

- 2000-2001: Bucs made play-offs again
- But troubling pattern: often played tight, disciplined games, then
**everything fell apart during crucial, high-stress moments**
- 1999: racking up 6 wins in row at end of season, blew conference
championship against St. Louis Rams
- 2000: one game from Super Bowl, disintegrated against Philadelphia
Eagles (lost 21-3)
- 2001: lost to Eagles again (31-9), blowing chance of advancing

> "We would practice, and everything would come together and then
we'd get to a big game and it was like the training disappeared.
Afterward, my players would say, 'Well, it was a critical play and I
went back to what I knew,' or 'I felt like I had to step it up.'
What they were *really* saying was they trusted our system most of
the time, but when everything was on the line, that belief broke
down."

- End of 2001 season: general manager fired Dungy
- Bucs won Super Bowl next year using Dungy's formations/players and
habits he shaped
- Dungy watched on TV as replacement coach lifted Lombardi trophy

## Chapter 3: The Golden Rule of Habit Change (continued)

### AA and the Power of Belief

- About 60 people in church listening to **John** (alcoholic) share
his story
- AA meetings: "Hi, John," "I'm an alcoholic"

### John's Story

- First decided to get help when son broke arm in car accident
- Having affair at work, drinking escalated
- Had 2 vodkas at desk, Chili's with friend, two-for-one happy hour
- Had to pick up kids (wife didn't know about affair), slammed into
stop sign
- Son **Sam** flew against windshield, broke arm — blood on dash,
cracked windshield
- Checked into clinic for 13 months, felt in control, went to
meetings regularly
- Eventually stopped going: *"I'm not such a loser that I need to
hang out with a bunch of drunks"*

### The Relapse

- Mom got cancer ~2 years after getting sober
- She called him at work, said cancer "pretty advanced"
- First thing after hanging up: found a bar
- Drunk for next 2 years until wife moved out
- Friend teaching him to use **cocaine** — would do line in office,
get "little drip into back of throat" 5 minutes later
- On way to pick up kids, felt fine, pulled into intersection when
light red, huge truck slammed into car
- Actually flipped car on side — passenger side completely crushed
(where Sam usually sat, would have been killed)
- Arrested for DUI

### The Turning Point: Belief

- Started going to meetings again, sponsor told him: without higher
power in life, nothing else matters
- Didn't want to admit powerlessness
- Knew if something didn't change, would kill kids

> "So I started working at that, working at believing in something
bigger than me. And it's working. I don't know if it's God or
something else, but there is a power that has helped me stay sober
for seven years now and I'm in awe of it."

- Some mornings wakes up feeling like gonna fall down
- Looks for higher power, calls sponsor
- By time ready for shower, head is straight

### Research on AA's Success

- First cracks in theory that AA succeeded solely by reprogramming
habits appeared decade ago
- Stories from alcoholics like John: researchers found habit
replacement worked until **stresses of life got too high**
- Cancer diagnosis, marriage falling apart — alcoholics often fell
off wagon
- If habit replacement so effective, why fail at critical moments?

### The Missing Ingredient: Belief

- **Alcohol Research Group** (California) noticed pattern in
interviews
- Alcoholics said same thing: identifying cues and choosing new
routines important, but without another ingredient, new habits never
fully took hold
- **The secret: God**
- Researchers hated this (God/spirituality not testable hypotheses)
- Churches filled with drunks who continue drinking despite pious
faith

### 2005 Study: Religious Belief and Sobriety

- Group of scientists at **UC Berkeley, Brown University, National
Institutes of Health** asked alcoholics about religious/spiritual
topics
- Looked at data for correlation between religious belief and
staying sober
- Pattern emerged: alcoholics practicing habit replacement could stay
sober until stressful event — then certain number started drinking
again
- **But**: alcoholics who believed (like John) that higher power
entered their lives were more likely to make it through stressful
periods with sobriety intact

### Belief, Not God

- Wasn't God that mattered — **it was belief itself**
- Once people learned how to believe in something, that skill spilled
over to other parts of lives
- Started believing they could change
- **Belief = ingredient that made reworked habit loop into permanent
behavior**

> "I wouldn't have said this a year ago—that's how fast our
understanding is changing, but belief seems critical. You don't have
to believe in God, but you do need the capacity to believe that
things will get better." — **Tonigan**, University of New Mexico

> "Even if you give people better habits, it doesn't repair why they
started drinking in the first place. Eventually they'll have a bad
day, and no new routine is going to make everything seem okay. What
can make a difference is *believing* that they can cope with that
stress without alcohol."

### How AA Trains Belief

- AA trains belief by putting alcoholics in meetings where **belief
is integral part of twelve steps**
- Lets people practice believing things will get better, until things
actually do
- **Lee Ann Kaskutas** (Alcohol Research Group): "At some point,
people in AA look around room and think, *if it worked for that guy,
I guess it can work for me*. There's something powerful about groups
and shared experiences. People might be skeptical about their ability
to change if by themselves, but group will convince them to suspend
disbelief. **A community creates belief.**"

### John's Experience

- After truck accident, someone asked for volunteers to put away
chairs
- John raised hand — wasn't big thing, took 5 minutes, felt good to
do something not all about *me*
- Started John on different path
- Wasn't ready to give in to group first time, but when came back,
ready to start believing in something

## Chapter 3: The Golden Rule of Habit Change (continued)

### Dungy Moves to Indianapolis Colts

- Week after Dungy's firing by Bucs, **Indianapolis Colts** owner
left impassioned 15-minute message
- Colts had one of NFL's best quarterbacks (**Peyton Manning**) but
just finished dreadful season
- Dungy moved to Indianapolis, became head coach

### Success with the Colts

- Immediately implemented same game plan: remaking routines, teaching
players to use old cues to build reworked habits
- First season (Colts): went 10-6, qualified for play-offs
- Next season: 12-4, came within one game of Super Bowl
- Dungy's celebrity grew — newspaper/TV profiles appeared
- Fans flew in to visit church he attended
- Sons became fixtures in Colts' locker room/sidelines
- 2005: eldest son **Jamie** graduated high school, went to college
in Florida

### The Same Troubling Pattern

- Even as successes mounted, same troubling patterns emerged
- Colts would play season of disciplined, winning football, then
under play-off pressure, choke

> "Belief is the biggest part of success in professional football.
The team *wanted* to believe, but when things got really tense, they
went back to their comfort zones and old habits." — **Tony Dungy**

- 2005: finished regular season with 14 wins and 2 losses (best
record in history)

### The Tragedy: Jamie's Death

- 3 days before Christmas, Dungy's phone rang middle of night
- Wife answered, handed receiver — one of his players
- Son **Jamie** brought to hospital earlier in evening with
**compression injuries on throat**
- Girlfriend found him **hanging in apartment, belt around neck**
- Paramedics rushed to hospital, efforts at revival unsuccessful — he
was gone
- Chaplain flew to spend Christmas with family

> "Life will never be the same again, but you won't always feel like
you do right now." — chaplain

### Team's Response

- Few days after funeral, Dungy returned to sidelines
- Wife and team encouraged him to go back to work
- "I was overwhelmed by their love and support"
- "As group, we had always leaned on each other in difficult times; I
needed them now more than ever"
- Team lost first play-off game, concluding season

### Something Changed

- In aftermath of watching Dungy during tragedy, "something changed"
- "We had seen Coach through this terrible thing and all of us wanted
to help him somehow"
- Simplistic/cavalier to suggest young man's death can impact
football games
- Dungy always said nothing more important than family
- **But**: in wake of Jamie's passing, as Colts started preparing for
next season, something shifted
- Players gave in to Dungy's vision of how football should be played
in way they hadn't before
- **They started to believe**

### The 2006 Season

- Player (anonymity): "I had spent previous seasons worrying about
contract and salary. When Coach came back after funeral, I wanted to
give him everything I could, take away his hurt. I kind of gave
myself to the team."
- Another player: "Some men like hugging each other. I don't. I
haven't hugged my sons in a decade. But after Coach came back, I
walked over and hugged him as long as I could, because I wanted him
to know I was there for him."

### Conviction Emerged from Tragedy

- After death, team started playing differently
- **Conviction emerged** among players about strength of Dungy's
strategy
- In practices/scrimmages leading up to 2006 season, Colts played
tight, precise football

> "Most football teams aren't really teams. They're just guys who
work together. But we became a *team*. It felt amazing. Coach was the
spark, but it was about more than him. After he came back, it felt
like we really believed in each other, like we knew how to play
together in a way we didn't before."

- For Colts, belief in team/Dungy's tactics/ability to win began to
emerge out of tragedy
- But similar belief can emerge **without any adversity**

### The 1994 Harvard Study

- **1994 Harvard study** that examined people who radically changed
lives
- Some remade habits after personal tragedy (divorce, life-
threatening illness)
- Others changed after watching friend go through something awful
(like Dungy's players watching him struggle)
- Just as frequently: **no tragedy preceded transformations**
- Changed because embedded in **social groups that made change
easier**

### Examples of Group-Driven Change

- Woman's entire life shifted when signed up for psychology class,
met wonderful group
- "It opened a Pandora's box. I could not tolerate status quo any
longer. I had changed in my core."
- Man found new friends among whom he could practice being gregarious
- "When I make effort to overcome shyness, I feel it's not really me
acting, that it's someone else. But by practicing with new group, it
stopped feeling like acting. He started to believe he wasn't shy,
then eventually wasn't anymore."

### Community Makes Change Believable

- When people join groups where change seems possible, **potential
for change becomes more real**
- Most people who overhaul lives: no seminal moments or life-altering
disasters
- Simply **communities** (sometimes just one other person) who make
change believable
- Woman's life transformed after day spent cleaning toilets, weeks
discussing with cleaning crew whether to leave husband

> "Change occurs among other people. It seems real when we can see it
in other people's eyes." — **Todd Heatherton**, psychologist

### The Mechanisms of Belief

- Precise mechanisms of belief still little understood
- Not certain why psychology class can convince woman everything is
different, or why Dungy's team came together after coach's son passed
- Many people talk to friends about unhappy marriages and never leave
spouses; lots teams watch coaches experience adversity and never gel
- **But we know**: for habits to permanently change, **people must
believe change is feasible**
- Same process making AA effective (power of group to teach how to
believe) happens whenever people come together to help one another
change
- **Belief is easier when occurs within community**

### The 2006 Conference Championship

- 10 months after Jamie's death, 2006 football season began
- Colts played peerless football, winning first 9 games, finishing
year 12-4
- Won first play-off game, beat Baltimore Ravens for divisional title
- One step from Super Bowl, playing for conference championship (game
Dungy lost 8 times before)
- Matchup: January 21, 2007, against **New England Patriots** (team
that snuffed out Colts' Super Bowl aspirations twice)

### First Half Collapse

- Colts started strong, but before first half ended, began falling
apart
- Players afraid of making mistakes or eager to get past final hurdle
- Lost track of where supposed to be focusing
- Stopped relying on habits, started thinking too much
- Sloppy tackling led to turnovers
- **Peyton Manning**'s pass intercepted, returned for touchdown
- Patriots pulled ahead 21 to 3
- **No team in NFL history ever overcome so big deficit in conference
championship**
- Dungy's team, once again, going to lose

### Halftime Speech

- Halftime: team filed into locker room, Dungy asked everyone to
gather around
- **They had to believe**

> "We faced this same situation—against this same team—in 2003. In
that game, they had come within one yard of winning. One yard. Get
your sword ready because this time we're going to win. This is *our*
game. It's *our* time."

### Second Half Turnaround

- Colts came out in second half, started playing as they had in every
preceding game
- Stayed focused on cues and habits
- Carefully executed plays practiced past 5 years until became
automatic
- Offense on opening drive: ground out 76 yards over 14 plays, scored
touchdown
- 3 minutes later, scored again

### The Final Minutes

- Fourth quarter wound down, teams traded points
- Dungy's Colts tied game, never managed to pull ahead
- 3:49 left: Patriots scored, putting Dungy's players at 3-point
disadvantage (34 to 31)
- Colts got ball, began driving down field
- Moved 70 yards in 19 seconds, crossed into end zone
- First time Colts had lead (38 to 34)
- **60 seconds left on clock** — if Dungy's team could stop Patriots
from scoring touchdown, Colts would win

### Sixty Seconds is an Eternity

- **Tom Brady** (Patriots QB) had scored touchdowns in far less time
- Within seconds of start of play, Brady moved team halfway down
field
- 17 seconds remaining: Patriots within striking distance, poised for
final big play that would hand Dungy another defeat and crush team's
Super Bowl dreams

### Marlin Jackson's Interception

- Patriots approached line of scrimmage
- **Marlin Jackson** (Colts cornerback) stood 10 yards back from line
- Looked at visual cues: width of gaps between Patriot linemen and
depth of running back's stance
- Both told him: going to be passing play
- **Tom Brady** took snap, dropped back to pass
- Jackson already moving — Brady cocked arm, heaved ball
- Intended target: Patriot receiver 22 yards away, wide open near
middle of field
- Jackson was already running at angle, following his habits
- Rushed past receiver's right shoulder, cutting in front just as
ball arrived
- **Jackson plucked ball out of air for interception**, ran few more
steps, slid to ground hugging ball
- Whole play took less than 5 seconds
- **Game was over. Dungy and Colts had won.**

### Two Weeks Later: Super Bowl Victory

- 2 weeks later: won Super Bowl
- Dozens of reasons might explain why Colts finally became champions
- Maybe got lucky, maybe just their time
- **Dungy's players say**: it's because they *believed*, and because
belief made everything they had learned—all routines practiced until
became automatic—**stick, even at most stressful moments**

> "We're proud to have won this championship for our leader, Coach
Dungy." — **Peyton Manning**

> "We did it." — Dungy to his wife

## Chapter 3: The Golden Rule of Habit Change (Summary)

### How Habits Change

- Unfortunately, **no specific set of steps guaranteed to work for
every person**
- Habit cannot be eradicated — **must be replaced**
- Habits most malleable when **Golden Rule of habit change** applied:
keep same cue and same reward, new routine can be inserted

### But That's Not Enough

- For habit to stay changed, **people must believe change is
possible**
- Most often, **belief emerges with help of group**

### Practical Examples

- **Quit smoking**: figure out different routine satisfying cravings
filled by cigarettes
- Then find support group/collection of former smokers/community to
help believe you can stay away, use that group when might stumble
- **Lose weight**: study habits to determine why *really* leave desk
for snack
- Then find someone else to take walk with, gossip at their desk
rather than cafeteria, group that tracks weight-loss goals together,
or someone who keeps stock of apples rather than chips nearby

### The Evidence

- **If you want to change a habit**: must find alternative routine,
odds of success go up dramatically when commit to changing as part of
group
- **Belief is essential**, grows out of communal experience (even if
community only as large as 2 people)
- **We know change *can* happen**: Alcoholics can stop drinking,
smokers can quit puffing, perennial losers can become champions
- Can stop biting nails/snacking at work/yelling at kids/staying up
all night/worrying over small concerns
- **Not just individual lives shift** when habits tended to — also
companies, organizations, communities (as next chapters explain)

### Footnotes on Addiction vs. Habit

- Line separating habits and addictions often difficult to measure
- **American Society of Addiction Medicine** defines addiction as
"primary, chronic disease of brain reward, motivation, memory and
related circuitry characterized by impairment in behavioral control,
craving, inability to consistently abstain, and diminished
relationships"
- By that definition: difficult to determine why $50/week on cocaine
is bad, but $50/week on coffee is okay
- Someone who craves latte every afternoon may seem clinically
addicted, but thinks $5 for coffee demonstrates "impairment in
behavioral control"
- Is someone who prefers running to breakfast addicted to exercise?

### Physical vs. Behavioral Addictions

- Many researchers: while addiction is complicated/poorly understood,
many behaviors we associate with it are driven by **habit**
- Some substances (drugs, cigarettes, alcohol) can create **physical
dependencies**
- But physical cravings often fade quickly after use discontinued
- Physical addiction to nicotine lasts only ~100 hours after last
cigarette
- Many lingering urges we think of as nicotine's addictive twinges =
really **behavioral habits** asserting themselves
- We crave cigarette at breakfast a month later not because
physically need it, but because remember so fondly rush it provided
each morning
- **Attacking behaviors we think of as addictions by modifying habits
surrounding them** = shown in clinical studies to be one of most
effective modes of treatment
- Worth noting: some chemicals (opiates) can cause prolonged physical
addictions, some studies indicate small group predisposed to seek
addictive chemicals regardless of behavioral interventions
- Number of chemicals causing long-term physical addictions relatively
small, number of predisposed addicts estimated much less than number
of alcoholics/addicts seeking help

### Changing Habits Requires Work

- Important to note: though process of habit change easily described,
**does not necessarily follow it is easily accomplished**
- Facile to imply smoking, alcoholism, overeating or other ingrained
patterns can be upended without real effort
- **Genuine change requires work and self-understanding of cravings
driving behaviors**
- Changing any habit requires determination
- **No one will quit smoking simply because they sketch a habit loop**
- By understanding habits' mechanics, gain insights making new
behaviors easier to grasp
- Anyone struggling with addiction/destructive behaviors can benefit
from help: trained therapists, physicians, social workers, clergy
- Even professionals agree: most alcoholics, smokers, and people
struggling with problematic behaviors **quit on their own, away from
formal treatment settings**
- Much of time: accomplished because people examine cues, cravings,
rewards driving behaviors, then find ways to replace self-destructive
routines with healthier alternatives (even if not fully aware of what
doing at time)
- **Understanding cues and cravings driving habits won't make them
suddenly disappear—but will give you way to plan how to change the
pattern**

<!-- pp. 101-120 -->

## Chapter 4: Keystone Habits (continued)

### Paul O'Neill's Background and Philosophy

- **O'Neill's career trajectory**: Made lists his entire life
- At Fresno State: finished in 3 years while working 30 hours/week,
  drafted lifetime list including "Make a Difference" near the top
- 1960: Applied for federal internship, was one of 300 chosen
  from 3,000 interviews
- **Veterans Administration career**: Middle manager learning computer
  systems, kept meticulous lists of successful vs. failed projects,
  promoted yearly
- **Pentagon transformation**: Mid-1960s recruited to Office of
  Management and Budget, promoted to deputy director at age 38
- **Discovered institutional habits**: Government spending driven by
  automatic routines, not logical decisions

### Organizational Habits Discovery

- **Healthcare spending example**: Post-WWII program to build community
  hospitals still running 25 years later
- Bureaucrats automatically built hospitals when funds allocated,
  regardless of actual need
- Towns didn't need more beds, but politicians wanted visible
  structures for votes

> "Most of the time, no one ever asked if the town wanted a hospital.
> The bureaucrats had gotten into a habit of solving every medical
> problem by building something so that a congressman could say,
> 'Here's what I did!'" — Paul O'Neill

- **Geoffrey Hodgson**: "Routines are the organizational analogue of
  habits."
- **Contrasting examples**: NASA applauded failed rocket launches to
  encourage risk-taking (became organizational habit); EPA's William
  Ruckelshaus engineered aggressive enforcement culture (by 1975,
  issuing 500+ new environmental rules annually)

> "Every time I looked at a different part of the government, I found
> these habits that seemed to explain why things were either succeeding
> or failing. The best agencies understood the importance of routines.
> The worst agencies were headed by people who never thought about it."
> — Paul O'Neill

### Move to Alcoa

- 1977: Left government after 16 years in D.C., joined International
  Paper, eventually became president
- **Alcoa situation (1987)**: Struggling company, poor quality, 15,000
  employees had gone on strike, brought dummies to parking lots and
  burned them
- Previous CEO tried mandating improvements and failed
- O'Neill's priority search: Needed something both unions AND
  executives could agree was important
- **The keystone habit chosen**: Worker safety — "Everyone deserves to
  leave work as safely as they arrive"
- **Audacious goal**: Zero injuries, period. Not reduced injuries —
  ZERO, no matter the cost

### The Safety Program's Radical Design

- **Understanding the "why"**: To prevent injuries, must understand WHY
  they happen in the first place
- To understand why injuries happened, study HOW manufacturing goes
  wrong
- To understand how, bring in quality control experts and teach
  efficient processes
- **Core insight**: Correct work is also safer work; protecting workers
  meant becoming the most streamlined aluminum company on earth

### The Automatic Routine (Habit Loop)

- **Cue**: Any injury occurs
- **Routine**: Unit president reports to O'Neill within 24 hours with
  prevention plan
- **Reward**: Only people who embraced the system got promoted

### Implementation Requirements

- Unit presidents needed injury reports from vice presidents within
  24 hours
- Vice presidents needed constant communication with floor managers
- Floor managers needed workers to raise warnings immediately and keep
  suggestion lists
- **Result**: Built new communication systems from bottom to top,
  transforming rigid hierarchy
- O'Neill was building new corporate habits

### Ripple Effects Begin

- Safety patterns shifted, other aspects of company changed with
  "startling speed"
- Unions embraced measuring individual worker productivity (helped
  identify safety risks)
- Managers welcomed workers shutting down production lines when pace
  became overwhelming (prevented injuries)
- **Safety habits spilled into personal lives**: "We do this stuff
  without thinking about it now"

### Safety Culture Examples

- **Jeff Shockey** (safety director): Saw bridge workers without
  harnesses, walked down 5 flights, lectured them on safety
- Another executive stopped weekend street excavation missing trench
  box, lectured city workers with kids in the back seat

### Business Results from Safety Focus

- Costs came down as routines moved through organization
- Quality went up, productivity skyrocketed
- Molten metal splashing → redesigned pouring system → fewer injuries
  AND less waste
- Broken machines replaced → less risk AND higher quality (equipment
  malfunctions were chief cause of subpar aluminum)
- **Aluminum siding plant**: Grouped painting machines together,
  switched pigments faster, became nimble with customer demand —
  profits doubled in one year

> "It turns out this guy had been suggesting this painting idea for a
> decade, but hadn't told anyone in management. Then he figures, since
> we keep on asking for safety recommendations, why not tell them about
> this other idea? It was like he gave us the winning lottery numbers."
> — Alcoa executive

### Keystone Habits in Individual Lives

- **Exercise studies**: People who exercise (even once weekly) start
  eating better, becoming more productive, smoking less, showing more
  patience, using credit cards less, feeling less stressed
- **James Prochaska** (University of Rhode Island): "Exercise spills
  over. There's something about it that makes other good habits
  easier."
- **Family dinner studies**: Families eating together raise children
  with better homework skills, higher grades, greater emotional
  control, more confidence
- **Making your bed**: Correlated with better productivity, greater
  well-being, stronger budgeting skills
- **Not causation but chain reaction**: Initial shift helps other good
  habits take hold

### Characteristics of Keystone Habits

- **"Small wins"**: Help other habits flourish by creating new
  structures and establishing cultures where change becomes contagious
- Offer what is known in academic literature as "small wins"
- Create structures that help other habits flourish
- Establish cultures where change becomes contagious
- Crossing gap between understanding principles and using them requires
  ingenuity

## Chapter 4, Section II: Michael Phelps and Small Wins

### Phelps's 2008 Beijing Race-Day Routine

- 6:30 AM alarm in Olympic Village
- Breakfast: eggs, oatmeal, four energy shakes (6,000+ calories over
  16 hours)
- 200-meter butterfly scheduled for 10 AM
- Two hours before: stretching regime starting with arms, back, ankles
  (ankles so flexible they extended 90+ degrees, farther than
  ballerina's *en pointe*)
- 8:30 AM: Pool warm-up (45 minutes): 800m mixed styles, 600m kicking,
  400m pulling buoy, 200m stroke drills, 25m sprints to elevate heart
  rate
- 9:15 AM: Squeezed into LZR Racer bodysuit (20 minutes to put on)
- Clamped headphones, played hip-hop mix, waited

### Bob Bowman's Keystone Habit Strategy

- **Phelps's background**: Started swimming at age 7 to burn off energy
  driving mom/teachers crazy, emotional, trouble calming down before
  races, parents divorcing, stress-coping problems
- **Bowman's insight**: Phelps had perfect physique (long torso, big
  hands, short legs = less drag) AND capacity for obsessiveness
- **What Bowman provided**: Habits to make him the strongest mental
  swimmer, targeting specific habits unrelated to swimming but creating
  the right mind-set

### The Videotape Visualization Habit

- **Cue**: End of each practice (as teenager)
- **Routine**: "Watch the videotape. Watch it before you go to sleep
  and when you wake up."
- **The visualization**: Mental movie of the perfect race — jumping off
  blocks, swimming flawlessly in slow motion, imagining strokes, pool
  walls, finish, water dripping off lips, ripping off cap
- Phelps would lie in bed with eyes shut watching entire competition,
  smallest details, again and again, until he knew each second by heart
- **During practices**: When Bowman ordered race speed, Phelps would
  shout "Put in the videotape!" and push maximum effort
- Eventually became automatic — Bowman just whispered "Get the
  videotape ready" and Phelps would settle down and crush competition

### Other Habits Fell Into Place

- Once core routines established (visualization, relaxation), other
  habits — diet, practice schedules, stretching, sleep — fell into
  place automatically
- **Core effectiveness**: The "small win" concept

### Small Wins Defined

- **Cornell professor (1984)**: "A steady application of a small
  advantage. Once a small win has been accomplished, forces are set in
  motion that favor another small win."
- Small wins fuel transformative changes by leveraging tiny advantages
  into patterns convincing people bigger achievements are within reach

### Gay Rights Movement Example

- **Late 1960s**: Initial efforts yielded only failures — laws to
  prosecute gays defeated in state legislatures, teachers fired for
  suggesting homosexuality should be embraced, larger goals (ending
  discrimination, police harassment, convincing American Psychiatric
  Association to stop defining homosexuality as mental disease) out of
  reach
- **Early 1970s**: American Library Association's Task Force on Gay
  Liberation focused on ONE modest goal — convincing Library of
  Congress to reclassify books from HQ 71-471 ("Abnormal Sexual
  Relations, Including Sexual Crimes") to less pejorative category
- **1972**: Library of Congress agreed, created HQ 76.5 ("Homosexuality,
  Lesbianism—Gay Liberation Movement, Homophile Movement")
- **Ripple effect**: News spread nationally, gay rights organizations
  started fundraising, openly gay politicians ran for office in
  California/New York/Massachusetts/Oregon citing the Library decision
- **1973**: American Psychiatric Association rewrote definition so
  homosexuality was no longer mental illness, paving way for state
  anti-discrimination laws
- Started with one small win

### Karl Weick on Small Wins

> "Small wins do not combine in a neat, linear, serial form, with each
> step being a demonstrable step closer to some predetermined goal.
> More common is the circumstance where small wins are scattered …
> like miniature experiments that test implicit theories about
> resistance and opportunity and uncover both resources and barriers
> that were invisible before the situation was stirred up."

### Phelps's Preparation Process

- **Bowman and Phelps**: Experimented until finding what worked,
  concentrated on tiny moments of success, built them into mental
  triggers
- "We worked them into a routine. There's a series of things we do
  before every race that are designed to give Michael a sense of
  building victory."
- **Before competition**: Phelps not thinking, just following the
  program — habits have taken over, race is natural extension of
  pattern that started earlier that day

### The Beijing Race with Broken Goggles

- 9:56 AM: Four minutes before race start, bouncing on toes at starting
  block
- Swung arms 3 times (as before every race since age 12)
- Stepped up on blocks, got into stance, gun sounded, leapt
- **Problem discovered**: Moisture inside goggles, couldn't tell if
  leaking from top or bottom, hoped leak wouldn't get too bad
- **Second turn**: Everything getting blurry
- **Third turn and final lap**: Goggles completely filled, couldn't see
  anything — not line on pool's bottom, not black T marking approaching
  wall, couldn't see how many strokes left
- **Most swimmers would panic** losing sight mid-Olympic final

### Phelps Stayed Calm

- Everything else had gone according to plan
- Leaking goggles were minor deviation he was prepared for
- **Bowman had once made him swim in Michigan pool in the dark**,
  believing he needed readiness for any surprise
- Videotapes in Phelps's mind featured problems like this
- Mentally rehearsed how to respond to goggle failure
- **Started last lap**: Estimated final push would require 19-20 strokes,
  maybe 21, started counting
- Felt totally relaxed swimming at full strength
- Midway through lap began increasing effort (final eruption technique
  for overwhelming opponents)
- **18 strokes**: Started anticipating wall, heard crowd roaring but
  blind
- **19 strokes, then 20**: Felt like he needed one more
- **Videotape in head said**: Make it a huge stroke, glide with arm
  outstretched, touch wall
- Timed it perfectly
- Ripped off goggles, looked up: "WR" (world record) next to his name,
  another gold

> "It felt like I imagined it would." — Michael Phelps

- One additional victory in a lifetime full of small wins

## Chapter 4, Section III: Alcoa Crisis and Keystone Habit Validation

### The Fatal Accident

- **Six months after O'Neill became CEO**: Middle-of-night call from
  Arizona plant manager — extrusion press stopped, young worker
  (joined weeks earlier, needed healthcare for pregnant wife) tried
  repair, jumped over yellow safety wall, walked across pit
- Aluminum jammed into hinge on swinging 6-foot arm
- Young man pulled scrap, removing it, machine fixed
- Behind him, arm restarted its arc, swinging toward his head, crushed
  his skull, killed instantly

### O'Neill's Response

- **14 hours later**: Ordered all plant executives and Pittsburgh top
  officers into emergency meeting
- Spent day painstakingly re-creating accident with diagrams and
  videotapes
- Identified dozens of errors: two managers saw man jump barrier but
  didn't stop him; training program hadn't emphasized he wouldn't be
  blamed for breakdown; lack of instructions to find manager before
  attempting repair; absence of sensors to auto-shut machine when
  someone stepped into pit

### O'Neill's Message

> "We killed this man. It's my failure of leadership. I caused his
> death. And it's the failure of all of you in the chain of command."

- Executives taken aback — tragic accidents were part of life at Alcoa
  (huge company with red-hot metal and dangerous machines)
- **Bill O'Rourke** (top executive): "Paul had come in as an outsider,
  and there was a lot of skepticism when he talked about safety. We
  figured it would last a few weeks, and then he would start focusing
  on something else. But that meeting really shook everyone up. He was
  serious about this stuff, serious enough that he would stay up nights
  worrying about some employee he'd never met. That's when things
  started to change."

### Immediate Actions

- Within a week: All safety railings at Alcoa's plants repainted
  bright yellow, new policies written
- Managers told employees not to be afraid to suggest proactive
  maintenance
- Rules clarified so no one would attempt unsafe repairs
- **Short-term result**: Noticeable decline in injury rate
- Alcoa experienced a small win

### O'Neill Pounced

- Wrote company-wide memo: "I want to congratulate everyone for
  bringing down the number of accidents, even just for two weeks. We
  shouldn't celebrate because we've followed the rules, or brought down
  a number. We should celebrate because we are saving lives."
- Workers copied note, taped to lockers
- Someone painted mural of O'Neill on smelting plant wall with quote
  from memo inscribed underneath
- **Just like Phelps's routines** (nothing to do with swimming,
  everything to do with success), O'Neill's efforts began snowballing
  into changes unrelated to safety but transformative nonetheless

### Workers Started Calling with Ideas

> "I said to the hourly workers, 'If your management doesn't follow up
> on safety issues, then call me at home, here's my number.' Workers
> started calling, but they didn't want to talk about accidents. They
> wanted to talk about all these other great ideas." — Paul O'Neill

### The Aluminum Siding Plant Transformation

- Struggled for years because executives tried anticipating popular
  colors, inevitably guessed wrong
- Paid consultants millions to choose paint shades
- Six months later: warehouse overflowing with "sunburst yellow," out
  of suddenly in-demand "hunter green"
- **Low-level employee suggestion**: Group all painting machines
  together, switch pigments faster, become nimble responding to
  customer demand shifts
- **Result**: Within a year, profits on aluminum siding doubled

> "It turns out this guy had been suggesting this painting idea for a
> decade, but hadn't told anyone in management. Then he figures, since
> we keep on asking for safety recommendations, why not tell them about
> this other idea? It was like he gave us the winning lottery numbers."
> — Alcoa executive

<!-- pp. 121-140 -->

## Chapter 4: Keystone Habits (continued)

### Barton's Firing and Cultural Enforcement at Alcoa

- **Barton fired two days after incident** despite being valuable executive
- Within Alcoa, firing seen as inevitable extension of O'Neill's culture
- **Keystone habits create cultures where new values become ingrained**
- Makes tough choices easier: when someone violates culture, it's clear
they must go
- Cultures manifest in special vocabularies ("Core Programs," "Safety
Philosophies" at Alcoa)
- These phrases act like suitcases containing whole conversations about
priorities

> "Not sharing an opportunity to learn is a cardinal sin." — Paul O'Neill

### Grit at West Point

- **West Point study**: researchers measured cadets' grades, physical
aptitude, military abilities, self-discipline
- All factors mattered less than **"grit"** — tendency to work strenuously
toward challenges, maintaining effort over years despite failure
- Grit emerges from culture cadets create for themselves
- Culture often emerges from keystone habits adopted at West Point

### The Musketeers: Peer Support Networks

- First summer "Beast Barracks" designed to grind cadets down — many quit
before school year starts
- Successful cadets form small groups (9 people calling themselves "the
musketeers")
- Daily gathering of like-minded friends becomes **keystone habit creating
culture**
- This habit helps find strength to overcome obstacles
- **Keystone habits transform us by creating cultures that clarify values**
in difficult moments

### O'Neill's Legacy Continues

- O'Neill retired 2000, became Treasury Secretary under Bush (2001-2002)
- Now teaches hospitals about worker safety and habits to lower medical
error rates
- Other companies embraced keystone habits: **IBM** (research/selling
routines), **McKinsey** (continuous improvement via internal critiques),
**Goldman Sachs** (risk assessment)
- Alcoa injury rate continued declining: 2010, 82% of locations had zero
lost days due to injury

### Jeff Shockey's Parking Spot Story

- New plant manager noticed reserved parking spots for important people
- Painted over all titles — whoever arrives earliest gets best spot
- Message: "Every person matters"
- Extension of O'Neill's worker safety culture
- "Electrified the plant"

## Chapter 5: Starbucks and the Habit of Success

### Travis Leach's Story: From Chaos to Success

- **Childhood in dysfunction**: parents were heroin addicts, frequent
evictions, chaotic home life
- Father overdosed when Travis was 9 — Travis called 911
- Dropped out at 16, tired of bullying, moved to Fresno
- Worked at car wash (fired), McDonald's, Hollywood Video — couldn't
control anger
- Would cry during shifts, yell at customers, hands shaking when line got
long
- Regular customer suggested Starbucks job — became barista on morning
shift
- **Now at 25**: manages two Starbucks, oversees 40 employees, $2M+ annual
revenue
- Salary $44k, has 401(k), no debt, never late

> "Starbucks is the most important thing that has ever happened to me. I
owe everything to this company." — Travis Leach

### Starbucks as Educator

- **137,000+ employees, 1M+ alumni** — one of nation's largest educators
- First year alone: 50+ hours in classrooms, dozens more hours with
workbooks
- Starbucks training program structured enough to earn college credits
- **Core focus: teaching willpower** — how to live, focus, master emotions

### Willpower Research: The Single Most Important Habit

- **2005 UPenn study of 164 eighth-graders**: willpower (self-discipline)
predicted academic performance **more robustly than IQ**
- High willpower students: higher grades, more selective schools, fewer
absences, less TV, more homework
- Self-discipline predicted grade improvement over school year; IQ did not

> "Self-discipline has a bigger effect on academic performance than does
intellectual talent." — University of Pennsylvania researchers

### Turning Willpower into Automatic Habit

- Best way to strengthen willpower: **make it into a habit**
- People with great self-control aren't working hard — they've made it
automatic

> "Their willpower occurs without them having to think about it." — Angela
Duckworth

### Starbucks' Willpower Curriculum

- Late 1990s growth strategy required cultivating environment justifying
$4 coffee
- Needed to train employees to deliver joy alongside lattes
- Unless baristas trained to set aside personal problems, emotions
inevitably spill into customer treatment
- Company spent **millions developing curricula** on self-discipline
- Workbooks serve as guides to make willpower a habit
- Growth: sleepy Seattle company → 17,000+ stores, $10B+ annual revenue

### Mark Muraven's Willpower Experiments

#### The Radish-and-Cookie Experiment (Case Western Reserve)

- Students faced bowl of fresh cookies and bowl of radishes — told to skip
meal beforehand
- **Half told to eat cookies, ignore radishes; half told opposite**
- Ignoring cookies requires willpower; ignoring radishes requires almost
none
- Then given impossible puzzle to solve
- **Cookie eaters (unused willpower)**: worked ~19 minutes on puzzle
- **Radish eaters (depleted willpower)**: worked only ~8 minutes (60% less
time), got frustrated, complained

> "Willpower isn't just a skill. It's a muscle, like the muscles in your
arms or legs, and it gets tired as it works harder, so there's less power
left over for other things." — Mark Muraven

### Willpower as Finite Resource

- Explains extramarital affairs (most likely late at night after using
willpower all day)
- Explains physician mistakes (after long, complicated tasks)
- If you want to exercise after work, conserve willpower muscle during day

> "If you use it up too early on tedious tasks like writing emails or
filling out complicated and boring expense forms, all the strength will be
gone by the time you get home."

### Australian Exercise Studies (Oaten & Cheng)

#### Exercise Program (2 months)

- Enrolled 24 people ages 18-50 in physical exercise program
- Increased willpower at gym resulted in **greater willpower at home**
- Started as couch potatoes
- After 2 months: fewer cigarettes, less alcohol/caffeine/junk food, more
homework, less TV, less depressed

#### Money Management Program (4 months)

- 29 people in financial management program
- Set savings goals, deny luxuries, keep detailed logs
- Finances improved
- **Also**: 2 fewer cups coffee, 2 fewer beers, 15 fewer cigarettes/day
(smokers)
- More productive at work and school
- **Willpower spillover**: strengthening in one area (gym, money) touched
everything

#### Academic Improvement Program

- 45 students focused on creating study habits
- Learning skills improved
- Also: smoked less, drank less, watched less TV, exercised more, ate
healthier
- All improvements **never mentioned in academic program**

> "When you learn to force yourself to go to the gym or start your
homework or eat a salad instead of a hamburger, part of what's happening
is that you're changing how you think. People get better at regulating
their impulses. They learn how to distract themselves from temptations.
And once you've gotten into that willpower groove, your brain is practiced
at helping you focus on a goal." — Todd Heatherton (Dartmouth)

### Willpower in Schools: KIPP

- **KIPP (Knowledge Is Power Program)**: collection of charter schools
serving low-income students nationwide
- Self-control teaching is core philosophy
- Philadelphia KIPP gave students shirts: "Don't Eat the Marshmallow"
- Schools dramatically raised test scores

> "Signing kids up for piano lessons or sports is so important. It has
nothing to do with creating a good musician or a five-year-old soccer
star. When you learn to force yourself to practice for an hour or run
fifteen laps, you start building self-regulatory strength. A five-year-old
who can follow the ball for ten minutes becomes a sixth grader who can
start his homework on time." — Heatherton

### Starbucks' Challenge: Entry-Level Workers Lack Self-Discipline

- **Christine Deputy** (oversaw training programs): many employees' first
professional experience
- Many lack self-discipline from families/communities
- Show up late, snap at customers, get distracted, quit for no reason
- Hard to make transition from being told what to do to dealing with
yelling customers and busy bosses

### Failed Attempts: Weight-Loss Classes and Gym Memberships

- Starbucks sponsored weight-loss classes, free gym memberships
- Attendance was spotty
- Hard to attend after full work day

> "If someone has trouble with self-discipline at work, they're probably
also going to have trouble attending a program designed to strengthen
their self-discipline after work." — Muraven

### Starbucks' Solution: Make Self-Discipline an Organizational Habit

- 2007: opening 7 new stores/day, hiring 1,500 employees/week
- Training essential: show up on time, don't get angry, serve with smile,
remember orders and names

> "We're not in the coffee business serving people. We're in the people
business serving coffee. Our entire business model is based on fantastic
customer service. Without that, we're toast." — Howard Behar (former
Starbucks president)

## Chapter 5: Starbucks and the Habit of Success (continued)

### Scottish Hip/Knee Surgery Study

- British psychologist recruited 60 patients from two orthopedic hospitals
- Average age 68, earned <$10k/year, didn't have more than high school
degree
- Recently undergone hip or knee replacement — many waited years (poor,
uneducated)
- Retirees, elderly mechanics, store clerks — most had no desire to read
- **Recovery is incredibly arduous**: severing joint muscles, sawing
through bones
- Smallest movements excruciating, but must exercise almost immediately
after surgery
- Risk of blood clots if don't start exercising
- Extreme agony makes people skip rehab — elderly often refuse to comply

### The Booklet Intervention

- Half received booklets after surgery with rehab schedule
- **13 additional blank pages** (one per week) with instructions: "My
goals for this week are __________? Write down exactly what you are going
to do."
- Patients filled pages with specific plans
- **3 months later**: patients with written plans walked almost **2x as
fast**, getting in/out of chairs unassisted **3x as fast**
- Putting on shoes, doing laundry, making meals much quicker

### Why Plans Worked: Anticipating Inflection Points

- Blank pages filled with **specific, detailed plans about mundane aspects
of recovery**
- One patient: "I will walk to bus stop to meet my wife from work" — noted
time, route, what to wear, which coat if raining, pills for pain
- Another: series of very specific schedules for bathroom exercises
- Third: minute-by-minute itinerary for walking around block
- **Plans focused on anticipated pain** — moments of temptation to quit
- Man exercising to bathroom wrote plan to **automatically take first
step** so wouldn't be tempted to sit
- **Inflection points**: moments when pain and temptation to quit would be
strongest

### Connection to Claude Hopkins' Pepsodent Strategy

- Patients identified simple cues and obvious rewards
- Bus stop patient: cue = *It's 3:30, she's on her way home!* Reward =
*Honey, I'm here!*
- Crafted self-discipline into habit by **identifying inflection point and
planning response**

### Starbucks' Inflection Points Problem

- Workers failing when running up against unexpected stresses or
uncertainties
- Willpower-challenged worker same as anyone else most of time
- But when faced with stress: customer yelling, impatient crowd —
self-control evaporates
- Needed **clear instructions for inflection points** — routine to follow
when willpower goes limp

### Starbucks Training Materials for Inflection Points

- Developed manuals spelling out routines for rough patches
- Taught workers how to respond to specific cues: screaming customer, long
line at register
- Managers drilled employees via role-playing until responses became
automatic
- Identified specific rewards: grateful customer, praise from manager
- **Gave employees willpower habit loops**

### The LATTE Method

- Travis's manager showed him largely blank page: "When a customer is
unhappy, my plan is to…"
- **LATTE**: **L**isten, **A**cknowledge, **T**ake action, **T**hank,
**E**xplain why problem occurred
- Workbook for imagining unpleasant situations and writing out response
plans

### Other Starbucks Routines

- **What What Why**: system for giving criticism
- **Connect, Discover, and Respond**: system for taking orders when hectic
- Learned habits help baristas distinguish patron types (hurried vs.
regular customer)
- Training manuals have **dozens of blank pages** for writing inflection
point plans
- Practice plans again and again until automatic

### How Willpower Becomes Habit

- **Choose behavior ahead of time, then follow routine when inflection
point arrives**
- Scottish patients filled out booklets
- Travis practiced LATTE method
- When inflection point appeared, habit took over

> "This is how willpower becomes a habit: by choosing a certain behavior
ahead of time, and then following that routine when an inflection point
arrives."

<!-- pp. 141-160 -->

### Corporate Training Programs

- **Starbucks**: After studying LATTE method, employees decide ahead
how to react to cues (painful muscle, angry customer), then routine
follows automatically
- **Deloitte Consulting**: "Moments That Matter" curriculum for
inflection points — preprogrammed routines like *Get Curious*,
*Say What No One Else Will*, *Apply the 5/5/5 Rule*
- **Container Store**: 185+ hours first-year training on inflection
points (angry coworker, overwhelmed customer) plus calming/defusing
routines

### Howard Schultz's Background

- **Brooklyn housing project**: shared two-bedroom with parents and
two siblings
- **Formative trauma**: Age seven, father broke ankle, lost diaper
truck job → family crisis
- **Father's spiral**: "My dad never found his way," Schultz said.
"I saw his self-esteem get battered. I felt like there was so much
more he could have accomplished."
- **School competitiveness**: Bloody elbows and knees from always
winning games, no matter the cost
- **Mother's influence**: Constant questions about study/test plans,
trained him to set goals

> "I've been really lucky. And I really, genuinely believe that if
you tell people that they have what it takes to succeed, they'll
prove you right."

### Starbucks Growth & Crisis

- **1987 purchase**: Six stores; within 3 years → 84 stores; within
6 years → 1000+
- **2000 handoff**: Schultz exhausted, handed operations to other
executives
- **Decline**: Complaints about quality and service; employees
unhappy; surveys showed people equating Starbucks with "tepid coffee
and empty smiles"
- **2008 return**: Schultz stepped back in as CEO, restructured
training to renew focus on **willpower and self-confidence** issues
("partners" in Starbucks lingo)

## Mark Muraven's Willpower Experiments

### The Cookie Study Setup

- **University of Albany undergrads**: Placed in room with warm,
fresh cookies
- **Group A (treated kindly)**: Researcher asked politely, explained
experiment purpose, thanked them, solicited feedback — "We want you
to help us make this experience as good as possible."
- **Group B (treated rudely)**: "You *must not* eat the cookies."
No explanation, no interest in feedback. Brusque instructions.

### Computer Test (Willpower Measurement)

- Both groups ignored cookies for 5 minutes after researcher left
- **Task**: Watch flashing numbers on screen (500ms each), hit space
bar when "6" followed by "4" — requires focus like working impossible
puzzle
- **Group A (kindly treated)**: Did well, maintained focus entire 12
minutes despite ignoring cookies
- **Group B (rudely treated)**: Kept forgetting to hit space bar,
said they were tired and couldn't focus — willpower muscle fatigued
by brusque instructions

### The Core Finding: Sense of Control

> "We've found this again and again. When people are asked to do
something that takes self-control, if they think they are doing it
for personal reasons—if they feel like it's a choice or something
they enjoy because it helps someone else—it's much less taxing. If
they feel like they have no autonomy, if they're just following
orders, their willpower muscles get tired much faster."

- **Autonomy preserves willpower**; following orders depletes it
- In both cases people ignored cookies, but treating them like cogs
vs. people made the difference

### Corporate Applications

- **Ohio manufacturing plant (2010)**: Assembly-line workers
empowered to make small decisions (schedules, work environment,
uniforms) → within 2 months, productivity up 20%, shorter breaks,
fewer mistakes
- **Starbucks today**: Employees redesign espresso machines and cash
register layouts, decide customer greetings and merchandise
placement. Store managers spend hours discussing where a blender
should go.
- **Kris Engskov** (Starbucks VP): "We've started asking partners to
use their intellect and creativity, rather than telling them 'take
the coffee out of the box, put the cup here, follow this rule.'"
People want control of their lives.
- **Results since Schultz's return**: Turnover down, satisfaction
up, revenues up $1.2 billion/year

## Travis's Personal Story (Section V)

### Family Addiction & Childhood

- **Mother's confession**: Became pregnant two years before Travis,
got abortion (already had two children, were drug addicts). Year
later, pregnant with Travis — considered abortion but "too much to
bear. It was easier to let nature take its course."

> "She told me that she had made a lot of mistakes, but that having
me was one of the best things that ever happened to her. When your
parents are addicts, you grow up knowing you can't always trust them
for everything you need. But I've been really lucky to find bosses
who gave me what was missing."

### Parents' Deaths

- **Mother**: Infection entered bloodstream through injection site
on arm → unconscious on arrival at hospital in Lodi, died 30 minutes
after life support removed
- **Father**: Week later, pneumonia, collapsed lung. Travis arrived
at 8:02 PM but nurse brusquely told him visiting hours over, come
back tomorrow.
- **Travis's response**: Gave up and walked away. "I said, 'All I
want to do is talk to him once,' and she was like, 'He's not even
awake, it's after visiting hours, come back tomorrow.' I didn't know
what to say. I felt so small."
- **Father died that night**

### Transformation Through Habits

- Travis hadn't learned emotional control habits yet — no practice
at Starbucks yet
- Reflects on distance traveled from world of overdoses and stolen
cars to successfully navigating hospital bureaucracy

> "If he had died a year later, everything would have been
different. By then, he would have known how to calmly plead with the
nurse. He would have known to acknowledge her authority, and then ask
politely for one small exception to have gotten inside the hospital."

- **Annual ritual**: On death anniversary, wakes early, extra-long
shower, plans day in careful detail, drives to work, always arrives
on time

## Chapter 6: The Power of a Crisis

### Rhode Island Hospital Surgery Error

- **Patient**: 86-year-old man, subdural hematoma from fall, blood
pooling in skull (72 hours buildup)
- **Hospital reputation**: Leading medical institution, main teaching
hospital for Brown University, only Level I trauma center in
southeastern New England, cutting-edge techniques (ultrasound tumor
destruction)
- **Also known for**: Internal tensions between nurses and
physicians; 2000 nurses' union strike over mandatory overtime

### The Toxic Culture

- **Nurses' perspective**: "This place can be awful. The doctors can
make you feel like you're worthless, like you're disposable. Like
you should be thankful to pick up after them."
- **Color-coded warning system**: Nurses wrote doctors' names in
different colors on whiteboards — blue = "nice," red = "jerk," black
= "whatever you do, don't contradict them or they'll take your head
off"
- **Abdominal surgery incident**: Doctor refused time-out, told
nurse: "Why don't you lead this? I'm going to step outside for a
call. Knock when you're ready." After nurse pushed back: "If I want
your damn opinion, I'll ask for it. Don't ever question my authority
again. If you can't do your job, get the hell out of my OR."
- **Result**: Nurse led time-out, procedure without complication.
She never contradicted a physician again or spoke up when safety
policies ignored.

> "Some doctors were fine, and some were monsters. We called it the
glass factory, because it felt like everything could crash down at
any minute."

### Informal Rules (Habits) at Rhode Island Hospital

- **Survival habits developed by nurses**: Double-checked error-prone
physicians' orders; wrote clearly on charts to prevent hasty surgeon
mistakes; color-coded doctors' names on whiteboards
- **Contrast with Alcoa**: At Alcoa, carefully designed keystone
habits created success. At Rhode Island Hospital, habits emerged
accidentally through whispered warnings → toxic patterns spread

> "Rhode Island Hospital was a place filled with a corrosive culture.
Unlike at Alcoa, where carefully designed keystone habits
surrounding worker safety had created larger and larger successes,
inside Rhode Island Hospital, habits emerged on the fly among nurses
seeking to offset physician arrogance."

### The Fatal Error

- **Emergency room**: Paged neurosurgeon during routine spinal
surgery; surgeon looked at brain scans mid-procedure, sent nurse
practitioner to get wife's consent
- **Consent form problem**: Didn't specify which side of head; no
clear indication which hemisphere
- **Surgeon's decision**: "I saw the scans before. It was the right
side of the head. If we don't do this quickly, he's gonna die."
- **Nurse's concern**: "Doctor, the consent form doesn't say where
the hematoma is."
- **Surgeon's response**: Grabbed paperwork, scribbled "right,"
initialed it. "There. We have to operate immediately."
- **Wrong side**: Nurse (worked there one year) knew this surgeon's
name often in black on hallway whiteboard = don't contradict
- **Procedure**: Opened right side of skull — no hematoma. "Oh my
God," someone said. "We need him turned!"
- **Correction**: Reattached bone triangle, shifted patient, shaved/
cleansed/drilled other side. Surgery ran almost twice as long.
- **Outcome**: Patient never regained full consciousness, died two
weeks later

### Investigation & Settlement

- Family argued trauma of medical error overwhelmed fragile body,
stress of two skull pieces removal plus surgery delay pushed him
over edge
- Hospital paid settlement; surgeon barred from ever working at
Rhode Island Hospital again

## Nelson & Winter: Organizational Routines

### *An Evolutionary Theory of Economic Change* (1982)

- **Authors**: Yale professors **Richard Nelson** and **Sidney
Winter**
- **Initially ignored**: Bland cover, daunting first sentence about
"evolutionary theory of capabilities and behavior of business firms";
known for Schumpeterian theory papers
- **Business impact**: Became bombshell — hailed as most important
text of century, quoted inside GE, Pfizer, Starwood Hotels

### Core Argument

> "Much of firm behavior is best 'understood as a reflection of
general habits and strategic orientations coming from the firm's
past,' rather than 'the result of a detailed survey of the remote
twigs of the decision tree.'"

- Companies *seem* to make rational choices, but actually guided by
**long-held organizational habits** — patterns emerging from
thousands of employees' independent decisions
- These habits have more profound impacts than previously understood

### Fashion Industry Example (Red Cardigan)

- Seems like deliberate CEO decision based on sales/marketing data
- Reality: VP constantly trolls Japanese fashion websites (red was
hip last spring); marketers routinely ask friends which colors "in";
executives back from Paris runway shows reported rivals using new
magenta pigments
- Dozens of uncoordinated habits/processes/behaviors converged →
consensus emerged: Red will be popular this year
- No single deliberate decision — patterns created inevitable choice

### Why Routines Matter

- **Without them**: Most companies couldn't function
- **Provide**: Hundreds of unwritten rules companies need to operate
- **Allow**: Workers to experiment without asking permission at
every step
- **Create**: "Organizational memory" so managers don't reinvent
processes every six months or panic when VP quits
- **Reduce uncertainty**: Study of earthquake relief in Mexico/LA
found relief worker habits (establishing communication networks via
hiring children as messengers) "absolutely critical, because without
them, policy formulation and implementation would be lost in a jungle
of detail"

### Truces Between Warring Groups

- **Most important benefit**: Create truces between potentially
warring groups/individuals within organization
- **Reality vs. economics theory**: Companies aren't big happy
families working toward common goal. They're made of fiefdoms
competing for power and credit, hidden skirmishes making rivals seem
worse. Divisions compete for resources, sabotage each other for
glory. Bosses pit subordinates against one another so no one can
mount coup.

> "Companies aren't families. They're battlefields in a civil war."

- **Despite warfare capacity**: Most companies roll along peacefully
year after year because routines/habits create truces allowing
everyone to set aside rivalries long enough to get work done

### Truce Mechanics

- **Basic promise**: Follow established patterns, abide by truce,
rivalries won't destroy company, profits roll in, everyone gets rich
- **Example — Salesperson**: Knows she can boost bonus giving hefty
discounts for larger orders. Also knows if every salesperson does
this, firm goes bankrupt. So routine emerges: Salespeople meet every
January, agree to limit discounts to protect company profits,
everyone gets raise at year end.
- **Example — Young executive**: One call to major customer could
kill sale and sabotage colleague's division (good for personal
promotion). Problem: sabotage usually bad for firm. So unspoken
compact emerges: Okay to be ambitious, but if you play *too* rough,
peers unite against you. Focus on boosting own department rather than
undermining rival → probably get promoted eventually.

### When Truces Fail

- **Most of the time**: Routines and truces work perfectly, rivalries
kept within bounds, business thrives
- **Sometimes**: Even truce proves insufficient, unstable peace as
destructive as civil war
- **Rhode Island Hospital example**: Unbalanced truce. Nurses gave
up all power to strike truce — double-checked medications, wrote
clearly on charts, absorbed abuse, separated kind physicians from
despots. Doctors didn't bother learning nurses' names. "The doctors
were in charge, and we were underlings. We tucked our tails and
survived."
- **Result at crucial moments**: When surgeon about to make hasty
incision and nurse tried to intervene, routines crumbled. Wrong side
of 86-year-old man's head opened up.

### Leadership's Role

- **Creating balanced peace isn't enough**: For organization to work,
leaders must cultivate habits that both create real and balanced
peace AND make absolutely clear who's in charge
- **Balance paradox**: Must be fair AND unambiguous authority
- Without this, truces can be as destructive as any war

## King's Cross Fire (1987)

### The Station

- **Philip Brickell**: 43-year-old London Underground employee,
inside King's Cross ticketing hall when commuter reported burning
tissue at bottom of nearby escalator
- **Station scale**: One of largest, grandest, most heavily
trafficked London subway stops; labyrinth of deep escalators,
passageways, tunnels (some almost century old); 250K+ passengers/day
on six train lines
- **Escalators**: Some stretched five stories into ground, built of
wooden slats and rubber handrails (materials from decades earlier)

### Initial Response

- **Brickell's action**: Left position, rode escalator down, found
smoldering tissue wad, beat out fire with rolled-up magazine,
returned to post
- **No investigation**: Didn't try figuring out why tissue was
burning, if larger fire elsewhere. Didn't mention to another employee
or call fire department.
- **Reasoning**: Separate department handled fire safety. Brickell
knew strict Underground divisions — better not step on anyone's toes.
Even if he *had* investigated, wouldn't know what to do with
information. Chain of command prohibited contacting another
department without superior's authorization.
- **Underground routines**: Handed down from employee to employee —
never refer to *anything* inside station as "fire" lest commuters
panic. Not how things were done.

### The Underground's Organizational Structure

- **Governance**: Theoretical rule book no one had seen/read (didn't
exist except in unwritten rules shaping employees' lives)
- **"Four Barons"**: Chiefs of civil, signal, electrical, mechanical
engineering departments — each with bosses and subbosses jealously
guarding authority
- **Cooperation system**: All 19,000 Underground employees cooperated
in delicate system passing passengers/trains among dozens (sometimes
hundreds) of hands all day
- **Dependence on balance**: Cooperation required balance of power
between four departments and lieutenants, which relied on thousands
of habits employees adhered to
- **Truce from habits**: Policies telling Brickell — looking for
fires isn't your job, don't overstep bounds

> "Even at the highest level, one director was unlikely to trespass
on the territory of another. Thus, the engineering director did not
concern himself with whether the operating staff were properly
trained in fire safety and evacuation procedures because he
considered those matters to be the province of the Operations
Directorate."

### Escalation

- **15 minutes later**: Another passenger noticed smoke wisp riding
up Piccadilly escalator, mentioned to Underground employee
- **Safety inspector Christopher Hayes**: Eventually roused to
investigate
- **Third passenger**: Saw smoke and glow from underneath escalator
stairs, hit emergency stop button, began shouting for exit
- **Policeman**: Saw slight smoky haze halfway down escalator's long
tunnel, walked up staircase to outdoors, called superiors (radio
didn't work underground)
- **7:36 PM**: Twenty-two minutes after Brickell alerted to flaming
tissue, fire brigade received call — "Small fire at King's Cross"
- **Hayes didn't call London Fire Brigade**: Hadn't seen smoke
himself; another unwritten rule = fire department should never be
contacted unless absolutely necessary

### The Catastrophe

- **7:36 PM**: Underground worker roped off Piccadilly escalator
entry, another diverted people to different stairway. New trains
arriving every few minutes. Platforms crowded with exiting passengers
from subway cars. Bottleneck building at bottom of open staircase.
- **Minutes later**: Many would be dead

<!-- pp. 161-180 -->

## Chapter 5: Starbucks and the Habit of Success (continued)

### The King's Cross Fire: When Organizational Truces Fail

- **King's Cross Underground station fire (1987)**: killed 31 people
- Safety inspector **Hayes** discovered sprinkler system in escalator
machine room but had no training to use it
- Fire Brigade had warned Underground years earlier about fire risks,
but warning went to different division and was never acted upon
- **Organizational truces at the Underground**: each department knew
their role, but no one responsible for things outside their scope
- Ticketing clerks focused only on selling tickets, not watching for
fires — this truce existed because Underground previously had
problems with understaffed kiosks
- Station employees weren't trained on sprinklers/extinguishers
because different division controlled them
- Fire Brigade insisted on using street-level hydrants instead of
Underground's internal pipes because of previous incident where
they wasted time on unfamiliar equipment

### Fire Timeline and Systemic Failures

- 7:42 PM: burning tissue noticed
- 7:43 PM: salesman **Mark Silver** noticed hazy air, train doors
closed without reopening (unofficial policy to avoid tardiness)
- 7:45 PM: arriving train pushed oxygen into station, creating
**flashover point** — temperature rose 150 degrees in half a second
- Explosion shot fireball into ticketing hall, nearly 50 people inside
- Fire department rules required connecting hoses to street-level
hydrants, not internal pipes
- Station layout blueprints were in locked office, no one had keys
- Fire extinguished at 1:46 AM — six hours after initial report
- **Final toll**: 31 dead, dozens injured

> "Why did they send me straight into the fire? I could see them
burning. I could hear them screaming. Why didn't someone take
charge?" — twenty-year-old music teacher from hospital bed

### Analysis: The Danger of Balanced Power

- **The Underground's truces made logical sense** — prevented turf
battles, kept trains running on time
- But during crisis: **no one person, department, or baron had
ultimate responsibility for passengers' safety**
- Sometimes one priority needs to overshadow everything else, even
if it threatens the balance of power
- **Crisis as opportunity**: Tony Dungy at Bucs, Paul O'Neill at
Alcoa, Howard Schultz at Starbucks all exploited crisis moments
- During turmoil, organizational habits become malleable enough to
assign responsibility and create equitable balance of power

> "Sometimes it's worth stirring up a sense of looming catastrophe
rather than letting it die down."

### Rhode Island Hospital: From Chaos to Excellence

- Four months after initial botched skull surgery, more errors
followed:
  - Wrong section of patient's head operated on (fined $50,000)
  - Wrong part of child's mouth during cleft palate surgery (18
  months later)
  - Wrong finger operated on (5 months after that)
  - Drill bit left inside man's head (10 months later)
  - **Total additional fines**: $450,000

- Hospital became poster child for medical errors, national media
attention
- **Dr. Mary Reich Cooper** (chief quality officer) saw crisis as
opportunity

> "I saw this as an opening. There's a long history of hospitals
trying to attack these problems and failing. Sometimes people need a
jolt, and all the bad publicity was a serious jolt."

### Rhode Island Hospital's Transformation

- Shut down all elective surgery units for entire day
- Intensive training program emphasizing teamwork and empowering
nurses/medical staff
- Chief of neurosurgery resigned, new leader selected
- Invited **Center for Transforming Healthcare** to redesign surgical
safeguards
- Video cameras in operating rooms to ensure time-outs and
checklists
- Computerized system for anonymous problem reporting
- **Resistance initially**: doctors/nurses didn't want surveillance or
outside interference
- **Crisis changed everything**: sense of emergency made everyone
open to change

### Results After 2009 Reforms

- **Zero wrong-site errors** since full implementation
- **Beacon Award**: most prestigious critical care nursing recognition
- American College of Surgeons honors for cancer care quality
- Hospital culture completely transformed

> "It felt like working in a war zone. There were TV reporters
ambushing doctors as they walked to their cars." — nurse describing
pre-reform environment

### Similar Hospital Transformations

- **Beth Israel Deaconess Medical Center**: spate of errors in late
1990s
- Public battles between nurses and administrators at meetings
- State officials threatened to close departments
- Hospital coalesced around solutions under attack
- **"Safety rounds"**: every three months, senior physician discussed
surgery/diagnosis mistake or near miss to audience of hundreds

> "It's excruciating to admit a mistake publicly. Twenty years ago,
doctors wouldn't do it. But a real sense of panic has spread through
hospitals now, and even the best surgeons are willing to talk about
how close they came to a big error." — **Dr. Donald Moorman**, Beth
Israel Deaconess associate surgeon in chief

### Crisis as Leadership Tool

- **NASA**: unsuccessful safety improvement until Challenger exploded
(1986), then agency overhauled quality standards
- **Airline industry**: Tenerife runway disaster (1977) killed 583
people, within 5 years cockpit design, runway procedures, air
traffic controller communication all overhauled
- **Wise leaders prolong emergency on purpose** — exactly what
happened after King's Cross fire

### Desmond Fennell Investigation

- Five days after King's Cross fire, **Desmond Fennell** appointed
special investigator
- Interviewed Underground leadership — everyone knew fire safety was
serious problem for years
- Previous reform proposals (new hierarchies, station managers with
more power) never implemented
- **Fennell turned inquiry into media circus**:
  - Public hearings lasted 91 days
  - Revealed organization ignoring multiple warnings
  - Implied commuters in grave danger
  - Cross-examined dozens of witnesses describing turf battles over
  safety
  - **Final report**: 250-page scathing indictment of bureaucratic
  ineptitude

> "Having set out as an Investigation into the events of one night,
the report's scope was necessarily enlarged into the examination of
a system."

### Underground Transformation Post-Fennell

- Commuters picketed Underground offices
- Leadership fired
- New laws passed, entire Underground culture overhauled
- **Today**: every station has manager whose primary responsibility
is passenger safety
- Employees obligated to communicate at smallest hint of risk
- Trains still run on time, but habits adjusted enough to clarify
fire prevention responsibility
- Everyone empowered to act regardless of whose toes they step on

### Crisis Enables Institutional Change

- **Toxic truces** can't be changed simply because leader orders it
- Leaders must seek or create moments of crisis, cultivate sense
that *something must change*
- **Rahm Emanuel** (Obama's chief of staff, 2008):

> "You never want a serious crisis to go to waste. This crisis
provides the opportunity for us to do things that you could not do
before."

- Obama administration post-financial crisis: $787 billion stimulus,
health care reform, consumer protection laws, dozens of statutes
from children's health insurance to wage discrimination lawsuits
- **One of biggest policy overhauls since Great Society and New Deal**

### Rhode Island Hospital 2010: New Culture

- Young nurse **Allison Ward** (27 years old) in operating room for
routine surgery
- Entire surgical team gathered for time-out before unconscious
patient
- Surgeon read from checklist on wall: "Does anyone have any concerns
before we start?"
- Ward reminded everyone to pause before first and second procedures
(not mentioned in initial checklist)
- Few years earlier, this comment might have earned rebuke or ended
her career
- Surgeon thanked her: "I'll remember to mention it next time."

> "I know this hospital has gone through some hard periods. But it's
really cooperative now. Our training, all the role models — the
whole culture of the hospital is focused on teamwork. I feel like I
can say anything. It's an amazing place to work." — Allison Ward

## Chapter 7: How Target Knows What You Want Before You Do

### Andrew Pole and Target's Predictive Analytics

- **Andrew Pole**: statistician hired by Target in 2002
- Marketing colleagues asked: "Can your computers figure out which
customers are pregnant, even if they don't want us to know?"
- **Pregnant women and new parents**: holy grail of retail —
profitable, product-hungry, price-insensitive
- People with infants buy everything at one store for years
- **Pole's challenge**: build mathematical models to identify pregnant
shoppers and predict what's happening in their homes

### Target's Data Collection Infrastructure

- Target built vast **Guest ID number** warehouse starting decade
earlier
- Every customer interaction tracked: credit card, frequent-buyer
tag, coupon redemption, survey, refund, email, Target.com visit,
online purchase
- Each purchase linked to Guest ID along with everything else they'd
bought
- **Demographic data purchased** from other firms: age, marital
status, kids, town, drive time to store, income estimate, recent
move, websites visited, credit cards, home/mobile phone numbers
- Additional purchased data: ethnicity, job history, magazines read,
bankruptcy, college, brand preferences (coffee, toilet paper,
cereal, applesauce)

### The Data Broker Ecosystem

- **InfiniGraph**: monitors online message boards and forums, tracks
favorably mentioned products
- **Rapleaf**: political leanings, reading habits, charitable giving,
car ownership, religious news vs. cigarette deals preference
- Some companies analyze consumer photos (obese/skinny, short/tall,
hairy/bald) to predict purchases
- **Tom Davenport** (leading researcher on business data/analytics):

> "It used to be that companies only knew what their customers
wanted them to know. That world is far behind us. You'd be shocked
how much information is out there — and every company buys it,
because it's the only way to survive."

### Target's Predictive Power Example

- Purchase Popsicles once a week at 6:30 PM on weekdays + megasized
trash bags July/October
- Target deduces: kids at home, stop for groceries after work, lawn
needs mowing (summer), leaves drop (fall)
- Notice cereal purchases but never milk → buying milk elsewhere
- **Target mails**: 2% milk coupons + chocolate sprinkles, school
supplies, lawn furniture, rakes, relaxation items
- Company personalizes ads/coupons to every customer — different
flyer than neighbors
- **Pole at 2010 retail statistics conference**:

> "With the Guest ID, we have your name, address, and tender, we
know you've got a Target Visa, a debit card, and we can tie that to
your store purchases. The company can link about half of all
in-store sales to a specific person, almost all online sales, and
about a quarter of online browsing."

### The Pregnancy Prediction Project

- Marketing wanted to identify pregnant customers without them
knowing
- Figuring out pregnancy could make Target millions
- **Pole's task**: become mathematical mind reader, decipher shoppers'
habits to convince them to spend more

> "I guess outsiders could say this is a little bit like Big
Brother. That makes some people uncomfortable."

<!-- pp. 181-200 -->

## Chapter 7: How Target Knows What You Want Before You Do (continued)

### Target's Pregnancy Prediction Algorithm

- **Andrew Pole**, Target statistician, tasked with identifying pregnant
customers before competitors
- Major life events (marriage, divorce, moving, having baby) make
consumers "vulnerable to intervention by marketers" — shopping patterns
shift during transitions
- **Having a baby** is the biggest life event for most people — habits
become maximally flexible when infant arrives
- Average parent spends **$6,800** on baby items before first birthday
(2010 estimate)
- Real profit: capturing *all* shopping once exhausted parents start
buying diapers at Target

> "As soon as we get them buying diapers from us, they're going to start
> buying everything else, too. If you're rushing through the store,
> looking for bottles, and you pass orange juice, you'll grab a carton."
> — Andrew Pole

- Target's goal: reach mothers *before* baby arrives, before Disney and
Procter & Gamble get to them

### Building the Prediction Model

- Target had baby shower registry data (due dates, names, addresses) but
only fraction of pregnant customers used it
- **Pole analyzed registry shoppers' purchase history** to identify
patterns as pregnancy progressed
- Discovered ~25 products that, analyzed together, created "pregnancy
prediction" score and estimated due date
- Examples:
  - Large quantities **unscented lotion** early in second trimester
  - Sudden purchases of **calcium, magnesium, zinc** supplements in first
  20 weeks
  - **Scent-free soap, cotton balls, washcloths, hand sanitizers** a few
  months after buying lotions/magnesium — signals approaching delivery
- Program could assign "pregnancy prediction" score to any regular
shopper

### Real Examples of Target's Predictions

- **Jenny Ward** (Atlanta, 23): bought cocoa butter lotion, large purse,
zinc, magnesium, bright blue rug → 87% chance pregnant, due late August
- **Liz Alter** (Brooklyn, 35): bought washcloths, sensitive skin
detergent, baggy jeans, DHA vitamins, moisturizers → 96% chance pregnant,
due early May
- **Caitlin Pike** (San Francisco, 39): bought $250 stroller but nothing
else → probably buying for friend's baby shower (also recently divorced)

### The Privacy Backlash

- Pole applied algorithm to Target's entire database → hundreds of
thousands of likely-pregnant women identified
- Marketing department ready to send targeted ads for diapers, lotions,
cribs, maternity clothes
- **Then someone raised privacy concern**: how will women react to
realizing Target knows they're pregnant?

> "If we send someone a catalog and say, 'Congratulations on your first
> child!' and they've never told us they're pregnant, that's going to
> make some people uncomfortable." — Pole

- Year after Pole created model: **angry father** walked into Minnesota
Target demanding to see manager
- His **high school daughter** received coupons for baby clothes and
cribs in the mail
- Manager apologized profusely, then called back few days later to
apologize again
- Father's response after talking to daughter: "She's due in August. I
owe you an apology."
- **Target's pregnancy predictor was more informed than the girl's own
father**

### Broader Privacy Concerns

- Other companies attacked for data collection: **McDonald's, CBS, Mazda,
Microsoft** sued in 2011 for monitoring Internet usage to profile buying
habits
- Class action lawsuits in California against Target, Walmart, Victoria's
Secret for collecting zip codes at checkout, then using them to ferret
out mailing addresses
- Using data to predict pregnancy was potential **public relations
disaster**

## Chapter 7: How Target Knows What You Want Before You Do (continued)

### II. The Music Industry's Data Revolution

### "Hey Ya!" by OutKast — A Predicted Hit That Failed

- Summer 2003: **Steve Bartels** (Arista Records) promoting "Hey Ya!" by
OutKast
- Described as "upbeat fusion of funk, rock, and hip-hop with a dollop of
Big Band swing"
- Arista executives certain it would be huge hit

> "It *sounded* like a hit, like the kind of song you'd be hearing at bar
> mitzvahs and proms for years." — Bartels

- Music industry undergoing transformation similar to retail — using
computer programs to forecast listeners' habits

### Hit Song Science Algorithm

- **Polyphonic HMI** (Spain): created **Hit Song Science** program
- Analyzed mathematical characteristics of songs (tempo, pitch, melody,
chord progression) against thousands of hits in database
- Successfully predicted **Norah Jones's *Come Away with Me*** would be
hit after industry dismissed it (sold 10 million copies, won 8 Grammys)
- Predicted **"Why Don't You and I" by Santana** would be popular despite
DJs' doubts (reached #3 on *Billboard* Top 40)
- When executives ran "Hey Ya!" through Hit Song Science, **score was
among highest anyone had ever seen**

### The Listener Backlash

- September 4, 2003: Top 40 station **WIOQ** (Philadelphia) started
playing "Hey Ya!" at 7:15 PM
- Aired 37 times throughout the month
- **Arbitron** technology tracked listener behavior — showed people tuning
out
- Data revealed: **listeners hated "Hey Ya!"**
- Nearly **1/3 changed station within first 30 seconds** of song
- Pattern repeated at stations in Chicago, Los Angeles, Phoenix, Seattle

> "I thought it was a great song the first time I heard it. But it didn't
> sound like other songs, and so some people went nuts when it came on."
> — **John Garabedian**, syndicated Top 40 radio host (2+ million
> listeners/weekend)

### The Problem of Unfamiliarity

- People listen to Top 40 to hear **familiar songs** or songs that sound
like their favorites
- When something different comes on, they're offended — don't want
anything unfamiliar
- Hit songs valuable because they convince listeners to abandon video
games/Internet for radio, sell sports cars and clothing, root of dozens
of spending habits

### Rich Meyer and the Science of "Sticky" Songs

- **Rich Meyer**: onetime station manager who started **Mediabase** (1985)
in Chicago basement with wife Nancy
- Tracked which tunes were rising or declining in popularity by analyzing
station recordings
- Studied **"sticky" songs** — listeners never wanted to change dial
- Office filled with charts plotting characteristics of sticky songs

### Why Songs Are Sticky

- Some sticky for obvious reasons: "Crazy in Love" by Beyoncé and
"Señorita" by Justin Timberlake (established stars)
- Others sticky for mysterious reasons:
  - **"Breathe" by Blu Cantrell** (summer 2003): forgettable, beat-driven,
  DJs found bland, yet almost no one changed dial
  - **"Here Without You" by 3 Doors Down**: featureless
  - **Maroon 5 songs**: so tepid critics created term **"bath rock"** to
  describe them, yet almost no one changed station
- **Christina Aguilera and Celine Dion**: male listeners said they hated
them in surveys, but when songs played, men stayed tuned in
  - In LA market, Dion at end of each hour could boost audience by **3%**
  (huge figure in radio)
  - Male listeners may have *thought* they disliked Dion, but stayed glued
  when songs played

### The Familiarity Principle

- Meyer discovered: sticky songs **sound familiar** — like everything else
on radio but "a little more polished, a bit closer to the golden mean"

> "When it comes on the radio, your subconscious says, 'I know this song!
> I've heard it a million times! I can sing along!' Sticky songs are what
> you *expect* to hear on the radio. Your brain secretly wants that song,
> because it's so familiar to everything else you've already heard and
> liked. It just sounds right." — Meyer

- Preference for familiarity is **product of our neurology**
- Brain regions processing music (auditory cortex, thalamus, superior
parietal cortex) also handle **pattern recognition**
- Music is complicated — without ability to focus on some sounds and
ignore others, would be cacophony of noise
- **Listening habits exist because** without them, impossible to determine
if we should concentrate on child's voice, coach's whistle, or noise from
busy street

### Why "Hey Ya!" Failed Initially

- "Hey Ya!" *wasn't familiar* — radio listeners didn't want to make
conscious decision each time presented with new song
- Brains wanted to follow habit — react to cues ("sounds like all other
songs I've liked") and rewards ("fun to hum along")
- Much of the time, we don't actually *choose* if we like/dislike a song
— would take too much mental effort
- Instead, react to cues and rewards without thinking, either start
singing or change station

### The Familiarity Loop

- **THE FAMILIARITY LOOP**: [Diagram showing Routine connecting Cue
(musical notes) to Reward (musical notes)]
- Arista and radio DJs faced variation of problem Andrew Pole confronted
at Target
- Listeners happy to sit through song they might say they dislike, as long
as it seems like something they've heard before
- Pregnant women happy to use coupons in mail, unless those coupons make
it obvious Target is spying into their wombs (unfamiliar and creepy)

## Chapter 7: How Target Knows What You Want Before You Do (continued)

### III. Making Organ Meat Familiar During WWII

### The Wartime Protein Crisis

- Early 1940s: U.S. shipped domestic meat supply to Europe and Pacific
theater for WWII troops
- By late 1941: NYC restaurants using horse meat for hamburgers, black
market for poultry emerged
- **Herbert Hoover** (former president) wrote in 1943 government pamphlet:

> "Our farms are short of labor to care for livestock; and on top of it
> all we must furnish supplies to the British and Russians. Meats and fats
> are just as much munitions in this war as are tanks and aeroplanes."

### The Committee on Food Habits

- Department of Defense recruited **Margaret Mead, Kurt Lewin** and other
leading sociologists, psychologists, anthropologists
- Assignment: convince Americans to eat **organ meats** (livers, hearts,
kidneys, brains, stomachs, intestines) left behind after rib eyes and
roast beef went overseas
- At the time, **organ meat unpopular** — middle-class woman in 1940 would
sooner starve than serve tongue or tripe

### The Research Findings

- Committee conducted 200+ studies
- Core finding: **To change people's diets, the exotic must be made
familiar, and camouflaged in everyday garb**

### Making Organ Meat Familiar

- To convince Americans to eat livers and kidneys, housewives had to make
foods look, taste, smell as similar as possible to what families
*expected* on dinner table
- Example: **Subsistence Division of Quartermaster Corps** served fresh
cabbage to troops in 1943 → rejected
  - Mess halls chopped and boiled cabbage until it looked like every other
  vegetable on soldier's tray → troops ate without complaint

> "Soldiers were more likely to eat food, whether familiar or unfamiliar,
> when it was prepared similar to their prior experiences and served in a
> familiar fashion." — present-day researcher

- Government sent housewives mailers: "every husband will cheer for steak
and kidney pie"
- Butchers handed out recipes explaining how to slip liver into meatloaf

### Success of the Campaign

- By WWII's end, organ meats fully integrated into American diet
- **Offal consumption rose 33%** during war
- By 1955, up **50%**
- Kidney became staple at dinner, liver for special occasions
- America's dining patterns shifted so much that organ meats became
emblems of comfort

### Contrasting with Modern Diet Campaigns

- U.S. government launched dozens of other diet improvement efforts since:
"Five a Day" campaign, USDA food pyramid, push for low-fat cheeses/milks
- **None adhered to Committee's findings** — none tried to camouflage
recommendations in existing habits
- **All campaigns failed**
- Only government program to cause lasting change in American diet: organ
meat push of 1940s

## Chapter 7: How Target Knows What You Want Before You Do (continued)

### Making "Hey Ya!" Familiar Through Sandwiching

- To make "Hey Ya!" a hit, DJs needed to make song feel familiar
- Problem: computer programs like Hit Song Science good at predicting
habits, but sometimes find habits that haven't emerged yet
- Companies risk going out of business if they market to habits we haven't
adopted or are unwilling to admit (secret affection for sappy ballads)

### The "Sandwiching" Strategy

- **Tom Webster** (radio consultant): "Play a new song between two
consensus popular hits"
- WIOQ (Philadelphia) and other stations started **sandwiching "Hey Ya!"
between sticky hits**
- DJs didn't air "Hey Ya!" alongside just any hits — sandwiched between
songs **Rich Meyer** identified as uniquely sticky: Blu Cantrell, 3 Doors
Down, Maroon 5, Christina Aguilera
- Some stations used same song twice in sandwich

### Sample WIOQ Playlists

**September 19, 2003:**
- 11:43 "Here Without You" by 3 Doors Down
- 11:54 "Breathe" by Blu Cantrell
- 11:58 "Hey Ya!" by OutKast
- 12:01 "Breathe" by Blu Cantrell

**October 16:**
- 9:41 "Harder to Breathe" by Maroon 5
- 9:45 "Hey Ya!" by OutKast
- 9:49 "Can't Hold Us Down" by Christina Aguilera
- 10:00 "Frontin'" by Pharrell

**November 12:**
- 9:58 "Here Without You" by 3 Doors Down
- 10:01 "Hey Ya!" by OutKast
- 10:05 "Like I Love You" by Justin Timberlake
- 10:09 "Baby Boy" by Beyoncé

> "Managing a playlist is all about risk mitigation. Stations have to take
> risks on new songs, otherwise people stop listening. But what listeners
> really want are songs they already like. So you have to make new songs
> seem familiar as fast as possible." — Webster

### The Results

- When WIOQ first started playing "Hey Ya!" in early September, **26.6%**
of listeners changed station
- After sandwiching strategy started, tune-out factor dropped to **13.7%**
by October
- By December: **5.7%** tune-out
- Other major stations used same technique — tune-out rate followed same
pattern
- As listeners heard "Hey Ya!" again and again, **it became familiar**
- **"Hey Ya!" habit emerged** — WIOQ playing song 15 times/day
- Song won Grammy, sold more than 5.5 million albums, earned radio
stations millions

> "This album cemented OutKast in the pantheon of superstars. This is what
> introduced them to audiences outside of hip-hop. It's so fulfilling now
> when a new artist plays me their single and says, *This is going to be
> the next 'Hey Ya!'*" — Bartels

## Chapter 7: How Target Knows What You Want Before You Do (continued)

### Target's Solution: Camouflaged Advertising

- After Pole built pregnancy-prediction machine and identified hundreds of
thousands likely-pregnant shoppers, Target needed strategy
- Marketing department decided to conduct small experiments before
national campaign
- Randomly chose women from Pole's pregnancy list to test combinations of
advertisements

### Making Targeted Ads Seem Random

- Target executive with firsthand knowledge:

> "We have the capacity to send every customer an ad booklet, specifically
> designed for them, that says, 'Here's everything you bought last week,
> and a coupon for it.'"

- With pregnancy products, learned some women react badly
- Started mixing in ads for things they knew pregnant women would never
buy (baby ads looked random)
- Put **lawnmower ad next to diapers**, **wineglasses coupon next to
infant clothes** — looked like products chosen by chance

> "And we found out that as long as a pregnant woman thinks she hasn't
> been spied on, she'll use the coupons. She just assumes that everyone
> else on her block got the same mailer for diapers and cribs. As long as
> we don't spook her, it works."

### The Core Strategy: Dress New in Old Clothes

- Answer to Target and Pole's question (how advertise to pregnant woman
without revealing you know she's pregnant) same as DJs used to hook
listeners on "Hey Ya!"
- Target started **sandwiching diaper coupons between nonpregnancy
products**
- Made advertisements seem anonymous, familiar, comfortable
- **Camouflaged what they knew**

### Explosive Growth

- Target's "Mom and Baby" sales exploded
- Between 2002 (when Pole hired) and 2009: **Target revenues grew from $44
billion to $65 billion**
- 2005: company president **Gregg Steinhafel** boasted to investors about
"heightened focus on items and categories that appeal to specific guest
segments such as mom and baby"

> "As our database tools grow increasingly sophisticated, Target Mail has
> come into its own as a useful tool for promoting value and convenience
> to specific guest segments such as new moms or teens. For example,
> Target Baby is able to track life stages from prenatal care to car seats
> and strollers. In 2004, the Target Baby Direct Mail Program drove
> sizable increases in trips and sales." — Steinhafel

### The Universal Lesson

- Whether selling new song, new food, or new crib: **If you dress a new
something in old habits, it's easier for the public to accept it**

## Chapter 7: How Target Knows What You Want Before You Do (continued)

### IV. The YMCA and the Science of Social Habits

### The YMCA's Retention Problem

- 2000: **Bill Lazarus and Dean Abbott** hired by YMCA to use data-driven
analysis
- YMCA has 2,600+ branches (most are gyms and community centers)
- Leaders worried about staying competitive

### The Research Findings

- Gathered data from 150,000+ YMCA member satisfaction surveys
- Accepted wisdom: people wanted fancy exercise equipment and sparkling,
modern facilities
- YMCA had spent millions building weight rooms and yoga studios
- **Reality**: while facility attractiveness might cause people to join,
**retention driven by emotional factors**
  - Whether employees knew members' names
  - Whether employees said hello when members walked in
- People often go to gym looking for **human connection**, not treadmill
- If member made friend at YMCA, much more likely to show up for workouts

### The Social Habits Strategy

- People who join YMCA have certain **social habits**
- If YMCA satisfied them, members were happy
- To encourage exercise, YMCA needed to **leverage existing patterns** and
teach employees to remember visitors' names
- Variation of lesson learned by Target and radio DJs: **sell new habit
(exercise) by wrapping it in something people already know and like**
(instinct to make friends)

> "We're cracking the code on how to keep people at the gym. People want
> to visit places that satisfy their social needs. Getting people to
> exercise in groups makes it more likely they'll stick with a workout.
> You can change the health of the nation this way." — Lazarus

### The Future of Predictive Analytics

- Soon predictive analytics experts believe companies will know our tastes
and predict habits better than we know ourselves
- However, knowing someone might prefer certain brand of peanut butter not
enough to get them to act
- **To market new habit** (groceries or aerobics), must understand **how
to make the novel seem familiar**

### Personal Anecdote: The Author and Target

- Author mentioned wife was seven months pregnant with second child to
Pole
- Author and wife shop at Target occasionally, had given company their
address
- Recently, as wife's pregnancy progressed, author noticed **subtle
upswing in advertisements** for diapers, lotions, baby clothes arriving
at house
- Author planning to use coupons that weekend — also thinking of buying
crib, drapes for nursery, Bob the Builder toys for toddler

> "Just wait till the baby comes. We'll be sending you coupons for things
> you want before you even know you want them." — Pole

<!-- pp. 201-220 -->

## Chapter 8: Saddleback Church and the Montgomery Bus Boycott

### Rosa Parks's Arrest (December 1, 1955)

- **Rosa Parks**, 42-year-old seamstress at Montgomery Fair department
store, refused to give up her seat in the middle section of a crowded bus
- Bus driver **James F. Blake** demanded she move; Parks said "You may
do that" when threatened with arrest
- Parks wasn't in the white section—she sat in the middle row where
either race could sit
- Police arrested her with the line: "But the law is the law and you're
under arrest"

### Why Montgomery Became Ground Zero

- Parks wasn't the first to be arrested for bus segregation violations:
  - 1946: **Geneva Johnson** arrested for talking back to driver
  - 1949: **Viola White, Katie Wingfield**, and two black children
  arrested for sitting in white section
  - 1949: Two black teenagers from New Jersey arrested and jailed
  for sitting next to a white man and boy
  - 1952: Montgomery policeman shot and killed a black man in bus
  dispute
  - 1955: **Claudette Colvin** and **Mary Louise Smith** arrested for
  refusing to give up seats

> "There weren't many real activists in Montgomery at the time.
People didn't mount protests or marches. Activism was something
that happened in courts. It wasn't something average people did."
— **Taylor Branch**, Pulitzer Prize-winning civil rights historian

- When **Martin Luther King, Jr.** arrived in Montgomery (1954), he
found most blacks accepted segregation "without apparent protest"
- Political climate was shifting: *Brown v. Board of Education* (1954)
ruled segregation illegal in public schools; *Brown II* ordered
integration proceed with "all deliberate speed"
- **But**: *Brown* seemed abstract to Montgomery residents—a
far-off courthouse decision with unclear local impact

### The Power of Rosa Parks's Social Network

- Parks was "deeply respected and embedded within her community"
- Member of dozens of social networks across Montgomery:
  - Secretary of local NAACP chapter
  - Attended Methodist church
  - Helped oversee youth organization at Lutheran church
  - Volunteered at shelter and with botanical club
  - Wednesday nights: knit blankets for local hospital
  - Provided dressmaking services to poor families
  - Did last-minute gown alterations for wealthy white debutantes

> "Rosa Parks was one of those rare people of whom everyone agreed
that she gave more than she got. Her character represented one of
the isolated high blips on the graph of human nature, offsetting a
dozen or so sociopaths." — **Taylor Branch**, *Parting the Waters*

- Parks had **"strong ties"** (firsthand relationships) with dozens of
groups that didn't usually interact
- This crossed Montgomery's racial and economic hierarchies—unusual
for the time
- **Sociological principle**: Most people have friends who are like
them (similar income, race, background)
- Parks's friendships spanned Montgomery's social and economic
hierarchies

### The Initial Response: Strong Ties Activate

- Parks called her parents from police station
- Mother called wife of **E. D. Nixon** (former head of Montgomery
NAACP)
- Nixon called Parks's husband, then called white lawyer **Clifford
Durr** (Parks had hemmed dresses for his three daughters)
- Nixon and Durr posted bail and asked Parks to let them fight her
case in court
- Parks's husband opposed: "The white folks will kill you, Rosa"
- But Parks had worked with Nixon at NAACP and helped Durr's
daughters prepare for cotillions—her friends were asking for a favor

> "If you think it will mean something to Montgomery and do some
good, I'll be happy to go along with it."

### The Boycott Spreads: Within 24 Hours

- **Jo Ann Robinson** (president of schoolteachers' political group,
friend of Parks) heard about the arrest
- Robinson called impromptu meeting at midnight, suggested boycott on
Monday (four days hence, when Parks would appear in court)
- Robinson made copies of flyer in her office's mimeograph room:

> "Another Negro woman has been arrested and thrown into jail because
she refused to get up out of her seat on the bus for a white person
to sit down. This woman's case will come up on Monday. We are,
therefore, asking every Negro to stay off the buses Monday in
protest of the arrest and trial."

- Early next morning, Robinson distributed flyers to schoolteachers
and parents
- Within 24 hours: word spread to local NAACP, large political group,
black schoolteachers, and parents
- Many who received flyer knew Rosa Parks personally—sat next to her
in church or at volunteer meetings

> "There's a natural instinct embedded in friendship, a sympathy that
makes us willing to fight for someone we like when they are treated
unjustly."

- **Social habits of friendship** kicked in—natural inclination to
help someone we respect
- First mass movement of modern civil rights era began with Rosa Parks
because she had "a large, diverse, and connected set of friends"

### Three-Part Process of Social Movements

Historians and sociologists identify a **three-part process**:

1. **Movement starts** because of social habits of friendship and
strong ties between close acquaintances
2. **Movement grows** because of habits of a community and weak ties
that hold neighborhoods and clans together
3. **Movement endures** because leaders give participants new habits
that create a fresh sense of identity and feeling of ownership

- Parks's experience demonstrates **social habits**—behaviors that
occur unthinkingly across dozens/hundreds/thousands of people
- Social habits fill streets with protesters who may not know each
other but move in same direction
- Why some initiatives become world-changing movements while others
fail to ignite

### Weak Ties: The Power of Peer Pressure

- **Mark Granovetter** (Harvard PhD student, late 1960s) studied how
282 men found their current employment
- Tracked how they learned about positions, whom they called for
referrals, who provided helping hand
- Expected finding: Strangers were rejected, friends helped
- **Surprising finding**: Job hunters also received help from casual
acquaintances—"friends of friends"

> "Weak ties" — connections that represent links between people who
have acquaintances in common, who share membership in social
networks, but aren't directly connected by strong ties of friendship

- **Weak-tie acquaintances were often MORE important** than strong-tie
friends for landing jobs
- Weak ties give access to social networks where we don't otherwise
belong
- Close friends share same information we already have; weak-tie
acquaintances tell us about jobs we wouldn't otherwise hear about

> "Individuals with few weak ties will be deprived of information
from distant parts of the social system and will be confined to the
provincial news and views of their close friends." — **Mark
Granovetter**

- Without weak ties, momentum doesn't spread *beyond* the clique
- Most people don't care about latest outrage unless it's a close
friend who's been insulted or jailed

### Peer Pressure as a Tool

- Activists rely on peer pressure to compel protest even when people
don't necessarily *want* to participate
- Peer pressure = sense of obligation that neighborhoods/communities
place upon themselves
- **Social habits of peer pressure**:
  - Spread through weak ties
  - Gain authority through communal expectations
  - Ignoring social obligations = risk losing social standing and
  access to social benefits

- If you don't help the job-seeker, he might complain to his tennis
partner, who mentions it in locker room to someone you're hoping to
attract as client
- On playground, peer pressure is dangerous; in adult life, it's how
business gets done and communities self-organize

> "When strong ties of friendship and weak ties of peer pressure
merge, they create incredible momentum. That's when widespread
social change can begin."

### Freedom Summer (1964): Strong + Weak Ties in Action

- **Mississippi Summer Project** (Freedom Summer): 10-week program to
register black voters in the South
- Students from Harvard, Yale, other northern universities applied
- Newspapers and magazines predicted violence (which proved accurate—
three volunteers killed outside Longdale, Mississippi, one week after
program began)
- Over 1,000 applicants accepted, but when time came to head south in
June, more than 300 invited participants stayed home

### Doug McAdam's Study

- **Doug McAdam** (University of Arizona sociologist, 1980s) analyzed
720 applications (five pages each) to understand divergence in
participation
- Initial hypothesis: Self-interested motives vs. other-oriented
motives would explain who went vs. who stayed home
- **Hypothesis was wrong**: Selfish and selfless went South in equal
numbers; motives didn't explain differences

- Second hypothesis: Opportunity costs (spouses, jobs, unpaid break)
- **Wrong again**: Being married or holding full-time job *enhanced*
chances of going south

### The Real Factor: Social Networks

- Each applicant listed memberships in student/political
organizations and 10+ people to keep informed of summer activities
- McAdam charted each applicant's social network by comparing
memberships in clubs
- **Answer**: Strong and weak ties working in tandem
- Students who participated in Freedom Summer were enmeshed in
communities where both close friends *and* casual acquaintances
expected them to get on the bus
- Those who withdrew were in communities of different kind—where
social pressures and habits didn't compel them to go to Mississippi

> "On the day you signed up for Freedom Summer, you filled out the
application with five of your closest friends and you were all
feeling really motivated. Now, it's six months later and departure
day is almost here. All the magazines are predicting violence in
Mississippi. You called your parents, and they told you to stay at
home." — **Doug McAdam**

- Then you see people from your church group coordinating rides on
campus
- These aren't your closest friends, but you see them at club meetings
and in dorm—they're important within your social community
- They all know you've been accepted and said you want to go
- **Loss of social standing** if you withdraw creates real
consequences

### Religious Communities: 100% Participation Rate

- McAdam found mixed participation levels among applicants citing
"Christian duty to help those in need"
- **BUT**: Among applicants who mentioned religious orientation *and*
belonged to religious organization, **every single one** went to
Mississippi
- Once their communities knew they'd been accepted, impossible to
withdraw

### Contrast: Secular Organizations

- Applicants accepted who didn't go to Mississippi also belonged to
campus organizations and clubs
- **BUT**: Organizations they belonged to—newspaper, student
government, academic groups, fraternities—had different expectations
- Within those communities, someone could withdraw from Freedom Summer
with little/no decline in social hierarchy

> "When faced with the prospect of getting arrested (or worse) in
Mississippi, most students probably had second thoughts. However,
some were embedded in communities where social habits—the
expectations of their friends and peer pressure of their
acquaintances—compelled participation."

### Martin Luther King, Jr. and the Boycott

- **E. D. Nixon** called **Martin Luther King, Jr.** morning after
bailing Parks out of jail (5 A.M.)
- King was 26 years old, had been in Montgomery only one year, still
trying to figure out his role in community
- Nixon asked for King's endorsement and permission to use his church
for boycott meeting that night
- King was wary: "Brother Nixon, let me think about it and you call
me back"
- Nixon didn't stop there—reached out to **Ralph D. Abernathy** (one
of King's closest friends, strongest of King's strong ties)
- Few hours later, Nixon called King again

> "I'm glad to hear your say so, because I've talked to eighteen
other people and told them to meet in your church tonight. It would
have been kind of bad to be getting together there without you."

- King drafted into serving as president of organization coordinating
boycott

### Sunday: The Black Churches Commit

- Three days after Parks's arrest, city's black ministers explained to
congregations that every black church had agreed to one-day protest
- Message clear: It would be embarrassing for any parishioner to sin
on city buses
- Sunday's newspaper (*Advertiser*) contained article about boycott:
"a 'top secret' meeting of Montgomery Negroes who plan a boycott of
city buses Monday"
- Reporter had gotten copies of flyers that white women took from
their maids
- Black parts of city "flooded with thousands of copies" of leaflets
- Once article was written, black residents assumed everyone else was
already on board (like white readers did)

### Monday: The Boycott Succeeds

- Many people participated because of friendships with Parks
- Others didn't know Parks but sensed community was rallying behind
her cause
- If seen riding bus on Monday, it would look bad
- Flyer in churches: "If you work, take a cab, or share a ride, or
walk"
- Black taxi drivers agreed to carry passengers on Monday for 10 cents
(same as bus fare)
- **Community's weak ties** drawing everyone together—you were either
with boycott or against it

- King woke before dawn, got coffee
- Wife Coretta sat at front window waiting for first bus (South
Jackson line, normally filled with maids)
- First bus rolled by with no passengers; next bus empty; next bus
empty
- King drove around checking other routes—counted eight black
passengers in an hour (would have seen hundreds one week earlier)

> "I was jubilant. A miracle had taken place.… Men were seen riding
mules to work, and more than one horse-drawn buggy drove the streets
of Montgomery.… Spectators had gathered at the bus stops to watch
what was happening. At first, they stood quietly, but as the day
progressed they began to cheer the empty buses and laugh and make
jokes. Noisy youngsters could be heard singing out, 'No riders
today.'"

### The Verdict and the Rally

- That afternoon, Parks found guilty of violating state's segregation
laws
- 500+ blacks crowded hallways and stood in front of building awaiting
verdict
- Boycott and impromptu rally at courthouse = most significant black
political activism in Montgomery's history
- **All came together in five days**
- Started among Parks's close friends, drew power from sense of
obligation among community (social habits of weak ties)

> "The community was pressured to stand together for fear that anyone
who didn't participate wasn't someone you wanted to be friends with
in the first place."

- Some would have participated without such encouragement
- But tens of thousands across city wouldn't have decided to stay off
buses without encouragement of social habits

### Chapter 8 Continues: Rick Warren and Saddleback Church

### Rick Warren's Search (Summer 1979)

- **Rick Warren**: young white seminary student, Baptist pastor with
pregnant wife and less than $2,000 in bank
- Wanted to start new congregation among people who didn't already
attend church, but had no idea where
- Posted map on wall of Texas home, drew circles around major U.S.
cities from Seattle to Miami

> "I figured I would go somewhere all my seminary friends didn't want
to go."

- Spent summer in libraries studying census records, phone books,
newspaper articles, maps
- Wife in ninth month—Warren would jog to pay phone every few hours to
check if labor started, then return to stacks

### Discovering Saddleback Valley

- Warren found description of **Saddleback Valley** in Orange County,
California
- Book said it was fastest-growing region in fastest-growing county in
one of fastest-growing states in America
- Number of churches in area, but none large enough to accommodate
quickly expanding population
- Warren contacted religious leaders in Southern California who said
many locals self-identified as Christian but didn't attend services

> "In the dusty, dimly lit basement of that university library, I
heard God speak to me: 'That's where I want you to plant a church!'"
— **Rick Warren**

> "From that moment on, our destination was a settled issue."

### Donald McGavran's Influence

- Warren's focus on building congregation among unchurched began five
years earlier as missionary in Japan
- Discovered old Christian magazine article: "Why Is This Man
Dangerous?"
- About **Donald McGavran**, controversial author focused on building
churches where most people hadn't accepted Christ
- McGavran's philosophy: Missionaries should imitate tactics of other
successful movements (including civil rights campaign) by appealing
to people's social habits

> "The steady goal must be the Christianization of the entire fabric
which is the people, or large enough parts of it that the social
life of the individual is not destroyed." — **Donald McGavran**

> "Only the evangelist who helps people 'to become followers of
Christ *in their normal social relationship* has any chance of
liberating multitudes."

- McGavran's revelation to Warren: Someone applying rational logic to
topic usually couched in language of miracles
- Religion had to be, for lack of better word, **marketed**

### McGavran's Strategy

- Instructed church builders to:
  - Speak to people in their "own languages"
  - Create places of worship where congregants saw their friends
  - Hear kinds of music they already listened to
  - Experience Bible's lessons in digestible metaphors
- **Most important**: Ministers needed to convert *groups* of people
(not individuals) so community's social habits would encourage
religious participation

### Saddleback's Growth

- December after seminary graduation and having baby, Warren loaded
family and belongings into U-Haul, drove to Orange County, rented
small condo
- First prayer group: all of seven people in his living room
- **Today** (30 years later): Saddleback Church = one of largest
ministries in world
  - 20,000+ parishioners visiting 120-acre campus each week
  - Eight satellite campuses
  - Warren's book *The Purpose-Driven Life*: sold 30 million copies
  (among biggest sellers in history)
  - Thousands of other churches modeled on his methods
  - Warren chosen to perform invocation at President Obama's
  inauguration
  - Considered one of most influential religious leaders on earth

### Core Philosophy: Social Habits

> "We've thought long and hard about habitualizing faith, breaking it
down into pieces. If you try to scare people into following Christ's
example, it's not going to work for too long. The only way you get
people to take responsibility for their spiritual maturity is to
teach them *habits* of faith."

> "Once that happens, they become self-feeders. People follow Christ
not because you've led them there, but because it's who they are."

### Building the Church: Door-to-Door Research

- Warren spent 12 weeks going door-to-door in Saddleback Valley,
asking strangers why they didn't go to church
- Answers were practical: boring, bad music, sermons didn't seem
applicable to lives, needed child care, hated dressing up, pews
uncomfortable

### Warren's Solutions

- Told people to wear shorts and Hawaiian shirts if they felt like it
- Electric guitar brought in
- Sermons from start focused on practical topics:
  - "How to Handle Discouragement"
  - "How to Feel Good About Yourself"
  - "How to Raise Healthy Families"
  - "How to Survive Under Stress"
- Lessons easy to understand, focused on real daily problems, could be
applied as soon as parishioners left church

### Rapid Growth

- Started to work: Warren rented school auditoriums for services and
office buildings for prayer meetings
- Congregation hit 50 members, then 100, then 200 in less than a year
- Warren working 18 hours a day, seven days a week: answering calls,
leading classes, coming to homes for marriage counseling, looking for
new venues

### Warren's Breakdown

- One Sunday mid-December, Warren stood up to preach during 11 o'clock
service
- Felt light-headed, dizzy, gripped podium, words on page blurry
- Began to fall, caught himself, motioned to assistant pastor to take
lectern

> "I'm sorry, folks. I'm going to have to sit down."

- For years, had suffered from anxiety attacks and occasional bouts of
melancholy (friends told him like mild depressions)
- Never hit this bad before
- Next day, Warren and family began driving to Arizona (wife's family
had house there)
- Slowly recuperated over nearly a month away from church
- Full-fledged depression darker than anything experienced before—
wasn't certain if he'd ever become healthy enough to return

### Epiphany in the Desert

- Warren prone to epiphanies—had occurred when he found McGavran
magazine article and in Texas library
- Walking through desert, another one struck:

> "You focus on building people. And I will build the church."

- Unlike previous revelations, this one didn't suddenly make path
clear
- Warren would continue to struggle with depression for months (and
during periods throughout life)
- On that day, made two decisions:
  1. Go back to Saddleback
  2. Figure out how to make running the church less work

### The Small Groups Solution

- Warren expanded small experiment started few months earlier: hoped
to make it easier to manage church
- Never certain he'd have enough classrooms to accommodate everyone who
showed up for Bible study
- Had asked few church members to host classes inside their homes
- Worried people might complain about going to someone's house rather
than proper church classroom
- **BUT**: Congregants loved it—small groups gave chance to meet
neighbors

- After returning from leave, Warren assigned every Saddleback member
to small group that met every week
- **One of most important decisions he ever made**: Transformed church
participation from decision into habit that drew on already-existing
social urges and patterns

> "Now, when people come to Saddleback and see the giant crowds on
the weekends, they think that's our success. But that's just the tip
of the iceberg. Ninety-five percent of this church is what happens
during the week inside those small groups."

> "The congregation and the small groups are like a one-two punch.
You have this big crowd to remind you why you're doing this in the
first place, and a small group of close friends to help you focus on
how to be faithful. Together, they're like glue. We have over five
thousand small groups now. It's the only thing that makes a church
this size manageable. Otherwise, I'd work myself to death, and 95
percent of the congregation would never receive the attention they
came here looking for."

### Reverse Engineering the Montgomery Boycott

- Without realizing it, Warren replicated structure that propelled
Montgomery bus boycott—but in reverse
- Montgomery boycott started among people who knew Rosa Parks, became
mass protest when weak ties of community compelled participation
- **Saddleback Church**: works other way around
  - People attracted by sense of community and weak ties congregation
  offers
  - Once inside, pushed into small group of neighbors (petri dish for
  growing close ties)
  - Faith becomes aspect of their social experience and daily lives

### The Limits of Small Groups Alone

- Creating small groups isn't enough
- When Warren asked what people discussed in one another's living
rooms:
  - Bible and prayed together for 10 minutes
  - Then spent rest of time discussing kids or gossiping

- Warren's goal: Create
<!-- pp. 221-240 -->

## Chapter 8: Saddleback Church and the Montgomery Bus Boycott (continued)

### Rick Warren's Strategy: Teaching Habits to Create Self-Sustaining Growth

- Warren's goal wasn't just friendship but building a **community of the faithful**
- Small groups created tight bonds but lacked leadership structure
- Warren recalled **McGavran's philosophy**: teach people Christian habits, they'll act as Christians automatically without constant guidance
- Created **curricula designed to teach parishioners new habits**

> "If you want to have Christ-like character, then you just develop the habits that Christ had. All of us are simply a bundle of habits.... Our goal is to help you replace some bad habits with some good habits that will help you grow in Christ's likeness."

- Every Saddleback member signs a **"maturity covenant card"** promising to adhere to core habits: daily quiet time for reflection and prayer, tithing 10% of income, membership in a small group
- Giving everyone new habits became the church's focus

> "Once we do that, the responsibility for spiritual growth is no longer with me, it's with you. We've given you a recipe. We don't have to guide you, because you're guiding yourself. These habits become a new self-identity, and, at that point, we just need to support you and get out of your way."

### The Third Aspect of Social Habits: Self-Propelling Movements

- Warren could expand the church like **Martin Luther King grew the boycott**: by relying on strong and weak ties
- Transforming a church into a movement required something more—**self-perpetuating momentum**
- Warren needed to teach habits that caused people to live faithfully because of **who they are**, not just their ties
- **Third aspect of social habit-driven movements**: For an idea to grow beyond a community, it must become self-propelling—achieved by giving people new habits that help them figure out where to go on their own

### Montgomery Boycott: Testing the Movement's Endurance

- As boycott expanded from days to weeks to months, Montgomery's black community commitment began to wane
- Police commissioner threatened to arrest cabbies who drove blacks at a discount
- Boycott leaders signed up 200 volunteers to participate in a carpool
- Police started issuing tickets and harassing people at carpool spots
- Drivers began dropping out

> "It became more and more difficult to catch a ride. Complaints began to rise. From early morning to late at night my telephone rang and my doorbell was seldom silent. I began to have doubts about the ability of the Negro community to continue the struggle."

### The Bombing and King's Nonviolence Message

- A bomb exploded at King's house while his wife and infant daughter were inside
- No injuries, but front windows shattered, crater in porch
- Hundreds of blacks arrived; policemen told crowds to disperse
- A cop was shoved, bottle thrown, policeman swung baton
- Police chief asked King to stop a riot

> "Don't do anything panicky. Don't get your weapons. He who lives by the sword shall perish by the sword."

> "We must love our white brothers, no matter what they do to us. We must make them know that we love them. Jesus still cries out in words that echo across the centuries: 'Love your enemies; bless them that curse you; pray for them that despitefully use you.'"

### King's Reframing: From Struggle to Sacred Calling

- King's **message of nonviolence** drew on Gandhi and Jesus's sermons
- Argument listeners hadn't heard in this context before: nonviolent activism, overwhelming love and forgiveness, promise it would bring victory
- Civil rights movement had been framed in language of battles and struggles
- King gave people **a new lens**: not a war but an embrace
- King cast the boycott in **new and different light**: part of God's plan, same destiny that ended British colonialism and slavery, newest stage in centuries-old movement
- Required **new responses, different strategies, and behaviors**
- Needed participants to **offer the other cheek**
- People could show allegiance by **adopting the new habits King was evangelizing**

> "We must meet hate with love. If I am stopped, our work will not stop. For what we are doing is right. What we are doing is just. And God is with us."

- The crowd quietly walked home
- One white policeman: "If it hadn't been for that nigger preacher, we'd all be dead."

### Self-Organizing Leadership Emerges

- Next week, dozens of new drivers signed up for carpool
- Phone calls to King's home slowed
- People began **self-organizing, taking leadership** of the boycott, propelling the movement
- When more bombs exploded at other organizers' homes, same pattern: Montgomery's blacks showed up en masse, bore witness without violence or confrontation, went home
- Self-directed unity became visible

> "They were kind of like Dr. King's speech after the bombing—they took Christian teachings and made them political. They made them political."

- **Taylor Branch**: "A movement is a saga. For it to work, everyone's identity has to change. People in Montgomery had to learn a new way to act."
- Like **Alcoholics Anonymous**—draws power from group meetings where addicts learn new habits and believe by watching others demonstrate their faith
- Montgomery's citizens learned in mass meetings new behaviors that expanded the movement

> "People went to see how other people were handling it. You start to see yourself as part of a vast social enterprise, and after a while, you really believe you are."

### Mass Arrests and the Transformation

- When police resorted to mass arrests three months after boycott started, community embraced the oppression
- 90 people indicted by grand jury—almost all rushed to courthouse to present themselves for arrest
- Some went to sheriff's office to see if their names were on the list, were "disappointed when they were not"

> "A once fear-ridden people had been transformed."

- In future years, as movement spread with waves of killings, attacks, arrests, beatings, protesters stood their ground and told white vigilantes they were ready to forgive when hatred ceased
- Instead of fighting back or retreating, they used tactics that before Montgomery had been activist mainstays—simply stood ground

> "Instead of stopping the movement, the opposition's tactics had only served to give it greater momentum, and to draw us closer together. They thought they were dealing with a group who could be cajoled or forced to do whatever the white man wanted them to do. They were not aware that they were dealing with Negroes who had been freed from fear."

### The Critical Factor: Social Habits Creating Self-Directing Leaders

- Montgomery bus boycott succeeded due to **third aspect of social habits**: King's philosophy was a set of new behaviors that converted participants from followers into self-directing leaders
- Not habits as conventionally thought about them
- When King recast Montgomery's struggle by giving protesters **new sense of self-identity**, protest became a movement fueled by people acting because they had taken ownership of a historic event
- Social pattern became automatic, expanded to other places and groups whom King never met
- They could take on leadership simply by **watching how participants habitually behaved**

### Victory and Beyond

- **June 5, 1956**: federal panel ruled Montgomery's bus segregation law violated Constitution
- City appealed to U.S. Supreme Court
- **December 17**: more than a year after Parks's arrest, highest court rejected final appeal
- Three days later, city officials received the order: buses had to be integrated
- **Morning of 5:55 A.M.**: King, E.D. Nixon, Ralph Abernathy, others climbed aboard city bus for first time in over 12 months, sat in front

> "I believe you are Reverend King, aren't you?" asked the white driver.
> "Yes, I am."
> "We are very glad to have you this morning."

### Thurgood Marshall's Counterargument

- **NAACP attorney and future Supreme Court justice Thurgood Marshall** claimed boycott had little to do with ending bus segregation in Montgomery
- It was the Supreme Court, not capitulation by either side, that changed the law

> "All that walking for nothing. They could just as well have waited while the bus case went up through the courts, without all the work and worry of the boycott."

### The Real Impact: New Social Habits Spread

- Marshall was wrong in one important respect
- Montgomery bus boycott **birthed a new set of social habits** that quickly spread to Greensboro, Selma, Little Rock
- Civil rights movement became a wave of **sit-ins and peaceful demonstrations**, even as participants were violently beaten
- By early 1960s: Florida, California, Washington D.C., halls of Congress
- President Lyndon Johnson signed **Civil Rights Act of 1964**—outlawed all forms of segregation and discrimination against minorities and women

> "One hundred and eighty-eight years ago this week, a small band of valiant men began a long struggle for freedom. Now our generation of Americans has been called on to continue the unending search for justice within our own borders."

### Movements as Habit-Driven Phenomena

- Movements don't emerge because everyone suddenly decides to face same direction at once
- They rely on **social patterns that begin as habits of friendship, grow through habits of communities, sustained by new habits that change participants' sense of self**
- King saw the power of these habits as early as Montgomery

> "I cannot close without giving just a word of caution. As we go back to the buses let us be loving enough to turn an enemy into a friend. We must now move from protest to reconciliation..... With this dedication we will be able to emerge from the bleak and desolate midnight of man's inhumanity to man to the bright and glittering daybreak of freedom and justice."

## Chapter 9: The Neurology of Free Will

### I. Angie Bachmann's Story: The Gambler

- **Angie Bachmann** sat at home, bored, reorganizing the silverware drawer
- Youngest daughter started kindergarten, two older daughters in middle school
- Husband (land surveyor) left at 8 A.M., home at 6 P.M.—house empty
- First time in almost 20 years since marriage at 19 she felt genuinely alone
- Friends told her she should become a model, but she dropped out and married a guitar player, settled on being a mom
- Made a deal: if she could make it until noon without going crazy or eating cake in fridge, she would leave house and do something fun

### Bachmann's First Trip to the Casino

- At noon, drove to **riverboat casino** 20 minutes away
- Casino filled with people at noon on Thursday doing things besides soap operas and laundry
- Band playing, woman handing out free cocktails
- Ate shrimp from buffet, played hooky, made her way to blackjack table
- When $40 in chips were gone, two hours had flown by
- Had something to talk about at dinner besides outguessing contestant on *The Price Is Right*

### Family Background and Self-Perception

- Father: truck driver who remade himself into semi-famous songwriter
- Brother had also become a songwriter, won awards
- Bachmann: "the one who became a mom"

> "I always felt like the untalented one. I think I'm smart, and I know I was a good mom. But there wasn't a lot I could point to and say, that's why I'm special."

### The Habit Develops

- Started going to riverboat once a week on Friday afternoons
- **Strict rules for herself**: no more than one hour at blackjack table per trip, only gambled what was in wallet

> "I considered it kind of like a job. I never left the house before noon, and I was always home in time to pick up my daughter. I was very disciplined."

- Got good—within six months, picked up enough tricks for 2-3 hour shifts
- One afternoon: sat down with $80, left with $530—enough to buy groceries, pay phone bill, put a bit in rainy day fund
- **Harrah's Entertainment** (casino owner) sending her coupons for free buffets
- Would treat family to dinner on Saturday nights

### Iowa's Gambling History

- **Iowa legalized gambling only a few years earlier**
- Prior to 1989, lawmakers worried about temptations of cards and dice
- **George Washington** (1783): gambling "is the child of avarice, the brother of iniquity and the father of mischief.... In a word, few gain by this abominable practice, while thousands are injured."
- Lawmakers have eagerly seized the prerogative to define and regulate "bad" habits: prostitution, gambling, liquor sales, pornography, usurious loans, sexual relations outside marriage
- Iowa initially limited activity to riverboats, mandated no one could wager more than $5 per bet, maximum loss of $200 per person per cruise
- After some casinos moved to Mississippi (no-limit gaming allowed), Iowa legislature lifted restrictions
- **2010**: Iowa's coffers swelled by more than $269 million from taxes on gambling

### Escalation of Bachmann's Gambling

- **2000**: Bachmann's parents (longtime smokers) showed signs of lung disease
- She began flying to Tennessee every other week to help
- When she came back, stretches seemed even lonelier
- Started going to casino couple times a week when not visiting parents, then every Monday, Wednesday, Friday
- Still had rules, but had been gambling for years and knew the axioms serious players lived by
- Never put down less than $25 a hand, always played two hands at once

> "You have better odds at a higher limit table than at a lower table. You have to be able to play through the rough patches until your luck turns. I've seen people walk in with $150 and win $10,000. I knew I could do this if I followed my rules. I was in control."

- Didn't have to think about whether to take another card or double her bet—**acted automatically**, like Eugene Pauly (the amnesiac) eventually learned to always choose the right cardboard rectangle

### The Big Win and Casino Line of Credit

- One day in 2000: went home from casino with $6,000—enough to pay rent for two months, wipe out credit card bills
- Another time: walked away with $2,000
- Sometimes lost, but part of the game—smart gamblers knew you had to go down to go up
- Eventually, **Harrah's gave her a line of credit** so she wouldn't have to carry cash
- Other players sought her out, sat at her table because she knew what she was doing
- Buffet hosts would let her go to front of line

> "I know how to play. I know that sounds like somebody who's got a problem not recognizing their problem, but the only mistake I made was not quitting. There wasn't anything wrong with how I played."

### Losses Expand

- Bachmann's rules gradually became more flexible as size of winnings and losses expanded
- One day: lost $800 in an hour, then earned $1,200 in 40 minutes
- Then luck turned again: walked away down $4,000
- Another time: lost $3,500 in morning, earned $5,000 by 1 P.M., lost another $3,000 in afternoon
- Casino had records of how much she owed and earned—she'd stopped keeping track herself
- One month: didn't have enough in bank account for electricity bill
- Asked parents for small loan, then another
- Borrowed $2,000 one month, $2,500 the next

### The Compulsion Takes Hold

- Bachmann never had problems with drinking, drugs, or overeating
- Normal mom with same highs and lows as everyone else
- The **compulsion to gamble**—insistent pull that made her feel distracted or irritable on days she didn't visit casino, way she found herself thinking about it all the time, rush on a good run—caught her completely off guard
- New sensation, so unexpected she hardly knew it was a problem until it had taken hold of her life
- In retrospect: seemed like there had been no dividing line—one day fun, next it was uncontrollable

### Full Addiction by 2001

- **By 2001**: going to casino every day
- Went whenever she fought with husband or felt unappreciated by kids
- At tables: numb and excited, all at once, anxieties grew so faint she couldn't hear them anymore
- High of winning was so immediate, pain of losing passed so fast

> "You want to be a big shot," her mother told her when Bachmann called to borrow more money. "You keep gambling because you want the attention."

- That wasn't it, though

> "I just wanted to feel good at something. This was the only thing I'd ever done where it seemed like I had a skill."

- By summer of 2001: Bachmann's debts to Harrah's hit $20,000
- Had been keeping losses secret from husband
- When mother finally cut off stipends, she broke down and confessed

### Bankruptcy and Apparent Recovery

- Hired bankruptcy attorney, cut up credit cards, sat at kitchen table to write plan for more austere, responsible life
- Took dresses to used clothing store, withstood humiliation of 19-year-old turning down almost all of them because "they were out of style"
- Eventually started to feel like the worst was over—the compulsion was gone
- But it wasn't even close to the end

### The Lawsuit and the Question of Responsibility

- Years later, after she had lost everything and ruined her life and her husband's, after throwing away hundreds of thousands of dollars, her lawyer argued before state's highest court that **Angie Bachmann gambled not by choice, but out of habit, and thus shouldn't bear culpability** for her losses
- She had become an object of scorn on Internet, compared to Jeffrey Dahmer and parents who abuse their kids

> "How much responsibility do I actually bear?"

> "I honestly believe anyone in my shoes would have done the same things."

## Chapter 9 (continued)

### II. Brian Thomas: The Sleepwalker Who Killed

- **July morning 2008**: desperate man vacationing on west coast of Wales called emergency operator

> "I think I've killed my wife. Oh my God. I thought someone had broken in. I was fighting with those boys but it was Christine. I must have been dreaming or something. What have I done? What have I done?"

- Police arrived to find **Brian Thomas** crying next to camper van
- Previous night: he and wife sleeping in van when young men racing around parking lot awoke them
- Moved camper to edge of lot, went back to sleep
- Few hours later: Thomas woke to find a man in jeans and black fleece lying on top of his wife
- Screamed at the man, grabbed him by throat, tried to pull him off
- Reacting automatically—the more the man struggled, the harder Thomas squeezed
- Eventually man stopped moving—then Thomas realized it wasn't a man but his wife
- Dropped her body, began gently nudging her shoulder, trying to wake her
- Too late

> "I thought somebody had broken in and I strangled her. She's my world."

### Thomas's History of Sleepwalking

- For next ten months as Thomas sat in prison awaiting trial, portrait of murderer emerged
- As child: started **sleepwalking**, sometimes multiple times each night
- Would get out of bed, walk around house, play with toys or fix himself something to eat, next morning remember nothing
- Became a family joke—once a week seemed, he would wander into yard or someone else's room
- Mother would explain when neighbors asked why her son was walking across lawns barefoot in pajamas
- As he grew older: would wake with cuts on feet, no memories of where they came from
- Once swam in a canal without waking
- After marriage: wife grew so concerned about possibility he might stumble out of house into traffic that she locked door and slept with keys under pillow
- Every night: couple would crawl into bed, "have a kiss and a cuddle," then he would go to his own room and sleep in his own bed
- Otherwise his restless tossing, turning, shouting, grunting, occasional wanderings would keep Christine up all night

### The Neurology of Sleepwalking

- **Mark Mahowald** (professor of neurology, University of Minnesota, pioneer in understanding sleep behaviors):

> "Sleepwalking is a reminder that wake and sleep are not mutually exclusive. The part of your brain that monitors your behavior is asleep, but the parts capable of very complex activities are awake. The problem is that there's nothing guiding the brain except for basic patterns, your most basic habits. You follow what exists in your head, because you're not capable of making a choice."

- By law, police had to prosecute Thomas for murder
- But all evidence indicated he and wife had happy marriage prior to that awful night
- No history of abuse, two grown daughters, recently booked Mediterranean cruise for 40th wedding anniversary

### Sleep Study Results

- Prosecutors asked **Dr. Chris Idzikowski** (Edinburgh Sleep Centre) to examine Thomas and evaluate theory: had been unconscious when killed wife
- In two separate sessions (one in laboratory, other inside prison): researcher applied sensors all over Thomas's body, measured brain waves, eye movement, chin and leg muscles, nasal airflow, respiratory effort, oxygen levels while he slept
- Thomas wasn't first person to argue he had committed crime while sleeping and shouldn't be held responsible
- Long history of wrongdoers contending they aren't culpable due to "automatism"
- Past decade: as understanding of neurology of habits and free will has become more sophisticated, those defenses have become more compelling
- Society (as embodied by courts and juries) has agreed that **some habits are so powerful they overwhelm our capacity to make choices**, thus we're not responsible for what we do

### Sleep Terrors vs. Sleepwalking

- Sleepwalking is odd outgrowth of normal aspect of how brains work while we slumber
- Most of the time as bodies move in and out of different phases of rest, **most primitive neurological structure—the brain stem—paralyzes our limbs and nervous system**, allowing brains to experience dreams without bodies moving
- Usually people can make transition in and out of paralysis multiple times each night without problems
- Within neurology: known as **"the switch"**

- Some people's brains experience switching errors—go into incomplete paralysis as they sleep, bodies active while they dream or pass between sleep phases
- This is root cause of sleepwalking—for majority of sufferers, annoying but benign problem
- Someone might dream about eating a cake, next morning find a ravaged box of doughnuts in kitchen
- Someone will dream about going to bathroom, later discover wet spot in hall

- Sleepwalkers can behave in complex ways—open their eyes, see, move around, drive a car or cook a meal—all while essentially unconscious
- Parts of brain associated with seeing, walking, driving, cooking can function while asleep without input from brain's more advanced regions, such as prefrontal cortex
- Sleepwalkers have been known to boil water and make tea, operated a motorboat, turned on an electric saw and started feeding in pieces of wood before going back to bed
- But in general: will not do things dangerous to themselves or others
- Even asleep, there's an instinct to avoid peril

### The Critical Distinction: Sleep Terrors

- However, scientists have found a distinction between *sleepwalking*—in which people might leave beds and start acting out dreams or other mild impulses—and something called *sleep terrors*
- When sleep terror occurs, activity inside people's brains is markedly different from when they are awake, semi-conscious, or even sleepwalking
- People in midst of sleep terrors seem to be in grip of terrible anxieties, but are not dreaming in normal sense
- Their brains shut down except for most primitive neurological regions, which include what are known as **"central pattern generators"**
- These areas same ones studied by **Dr. Larry Squire** and MIT scientists who found neurological machinery of habit loop
- To neurologist: brain experiencing sleep terror looks very similar to brain following a habit

### Central Pattern Generators and Automatic Behaviors

- Behaviors of people experiencing sleep terrors *are* habits, though of most primal kind
- **"Central pattern generators"** at work during sleep terror are where such behavioral patterns as walking, breathing, flinching from loud noise, or fighting an attacker come from
- We don't usually think about these behaviors as habits, but that's what they are: **automatic behaviors so ingrained in our neurology** that, studies show, they can occur with almost no input from higher regions of brain

- However, these habits, when they occur during sleep terrors, are different in one critical respect
- **Because sleep deactivates prefrontal cortex and other high cognition areas**, when sleep terror habit is triggered, there is no possibility of conscious intervention
- If fight-or-flight habit is cued by a sleep terror, there is no chance someone can override it through logic or reason

> "People with sleep terrors aren't dreaming in the normal sense. There's no complex plots like you and I remember from a nightmare. If they remember anything afterward, it's just an image or emotions—impending doom, horrible fear, the need to defend themselves or someone else."

> "Those emotions are really powerful, though. They are some of the most basic cues for all kinds of behaviors we've learned throughout our lives. Responding to a threat by running away or defending ourselves is something everyone has practiced since they were babies. And when those emotions occur, and there's no chance for the higher brain to put things in context, we react the way our deepest habits tell us to. We run or fight or follow whatever behavioral pattern is easiest for our brains to latch on to."

### Sleep Terror Crimes: Following the Habit Loop

- When someone in midst of sleep terror starts feeling threatened or sexually aroused—two of most common sleep terror experiences—they react by following the habits most associated with those stimuli
- People experiencing sleep terrors have jumped off tall roofs because they believed they were fleeing from attackers
- They have killed their own babies because, they believed, they were fighting wild animals
- They have raped their spouses, even as their victims begged them to stop, because once the sleepers' arousal began, they followed the ingrained habit to satisfy the urge
- Sleepwalking seems to allow some choice, some participation by our higher brains that tell us to stay away from edge of roof
- Someone in grip of sleep terror simply **follows the habit loop no matter where it leads**

### Cases of Sleep Terror Violence

- Some scientists suspect sleep terrors might be genetic; others say diseases such as Parkinson's make them more likely
- Causes aren't well understood, but for a number of people, sleep terrors involve violent impulses

> "Violence related to sleep terrors appears to be a reaction to a concrete, frightening image that the individual can subsequently describe."

- Group of Swiss researchers (2009): among people suffering one type of sleep dysfunction, "attempted assault of sleep partners has been reported to occur in 64% of cases, with injuries in 3%."
- **In both United States and United Kingdom**: history of murderers arguing that sleep terrors caused them to commit crimes they would have never consciously carried out

**Examples:**
- Four years before Thomas arrested: man named **Jules Lowe** found not guilty of murdering his 83-year-old father after claiming attack occurred during a sleep terror
- Prosecutors argued it was "far-fetched in the extreme" to believe Lowe was asleep while he punched, kicked, and stamped his father for more than 20 minutes, leaving him with over 90 injuries
- Jury disagreed and set him free
- **September 2008**: 33-year-old **Donna Sheppard-Saunders** nearly suffocated her mother by holding a pillow over her face for 30 seconds—later acquitted of attempted murder by arguing she had acted while asleep
- **2009**: British soldier admitted to raping a teenage girl, but said he was asleep and unconscious while he undressed himself, pulled down her pants, and began having sex
- When he woke mid-rape, he apologized and called the police

> "I've just sort of committed a crime. I honestly don't know what happened. I woke up on top of her."

- He had a history of suffering from sleep terrors and was found not guilty
- **More than 150 murderers and rapists** have escaped punishment in past century using automatism defense
- Judges and juries, acting on behalf of society, have said that since criminals didn't *choose* to commit their crimes—since they didn't consciously participate in violence—they shouldn't bear the blame

### Brian Thomas's Trial

- For Brian Thomas, also looked like a situation where a sleep disorder, rather than murderous impulse, was at fault

> "I'll never forgive myself, ever."

- After Dr. Idzikowski observed Thomas in laboratory, he submitted findings: **Thomas was asleep when he killed his wife. He hadn't consciously committed a crime.**

- As trial started, prosecutors presented evidence to jury: Thomas admitted to murdering his wife, knew he had history of sleepwalking, failure to take precautions while on vacation made him responsible for his crime

- But as arguments proceeded, became clear prosecutors were fighting an uphill battle
- Thomas's lawyer argued client hadn't meant to kill wife—in fact, wasn't even in control of his own actions that night
- Instead: reacting automatically to a perceived threat
- Following a habit almost as old as our species: **instinct to fight an attacker and protect a loved one**
- Once most primitive parts of his brain were exposed to a cue—someone strangling his wife—his habit took over and he fought back, with no chance of his higher cognition interceding
- Thomas was guilty of nothing more than being human, lawyer argued, and reacting in the way his neurology—and most primitive habits—forced him to behave

### Defense Psychiatrist's Testimony

- Even prosecution's own witnesses seemed to bolster the defense
- Though Thomas had known he was capable of sleepwalking, prosecution's own psychiatrists said, there was nothing to suggest to him it was therefore foreseeable he might kill
- He had never attacked anyone in his sleep before
- He had never previously harmed his wife

- When prosecution's chief psychiatrist took the stand, Thomas's lawyer began cross-examination:
- Did it seem fair that Thomas should be found guilty for an act he could not know was going to occur?

- **Dr. Caroline Jacob**: Thomas could not have reasonably anticipated his crime
- If he was convicted and sentenced to Broadmoor Hospital (where some of Britain's most dangerous and mentally ill criminals were housed): "he does not belong there."

### Verdict: Not Guilty

- Next morning, head prosecutor addressed jury:

> "At the time of the killing the defendant was asleep and his mind had no control over what his body was doing. We have reached the conclusion that the public interest would no longer be served by continuing to seek a special verdict from you. We therefore offer no further evidence and invite you to return a straight not guilty verdict."

- The jury did so

- Before Thomas was set free, judge told him:

> "You are a decent man and a devoted husband. I strongly suspect you may well be feeling a sense of guilt. In the eyes of the law you bear no responsibility. You are discharged."

### The Ethical Question: Are We Responsible for Our Habits?

- It seems like a fair outcome
- After all, Thomas was obviously devastated by his crime
- He had no idea what he was doing when he acted—**simply following a habit**, and his capacity for decision making was, in effect, incapacitated
- Thomas is the most sympathetic murderer conceivable, someone so close to being a victim himself that when trial ended, judge tried to console him

- Yet many of those same excuses can be made for **Angie Bachmann, the gambler**
- She was also devastated by her actions
- She would later say she carries a deep sense of guilt
- As it turns out, **she was also following deeply ingrained habits that made it increasingly difficult for decision making to intervene**

- But in eyes of law: **Bachmann is responsible for her habits, and Thomas isn't**
- Is it right that Bachmann, a gambler, is guiltier than Thomas, a murderer?
- What does that tell us about the ethics of habit and choice?

### III. Bachmann's Relapse and Inheritance

- Three years after Angie Bachmann declared bankruptcy, her father passed away
- She'd spent the last half decade flying between her home and her parents' house, tending to them as they became increasingly ill
- His death was a blow
- Then, two months later, her mother died

> "My entire world disintegrated. I would wake up every morning, and for a second forget they had passed, and then it would rush in that they were gone and I'd feel like someone was standing on my chest. I couldn't think about anything else. I didn't know what to do when I got out of bed."

- When their wills were read: Bachmann learned she had inherited almost **$1 million**
- Used $275,000 to buy family a new home in Tennessee, near where her mother and father had lived
- Spent a bit more to move her grown daughters nearby so everyone was close
- **Casino gambling wasn't legal in Tennessee**, and "I didn't want to fall back into bad patterns"

### The Return to Gambling

- Changed her phone numbers, didn't tell the casinos her new address—"It felt safer that way"
- Then one night, driving through old hometown with husband, picking up last of their furniture from previous home, started thinking about her parents
- How would she manage without them? Why hadn't she been a better daughter?
- She began hyperventilating—felt like beginning of a panic attack
- Had been years since she had gambled, but in that moment **felt like she needed to find something to take her mind off the pain**
- She looked at her husband—she was desperate—this was a one-time thing

> "Let's go to the casino."

### Harrah's Sophisticated Tracking Systems

- When they walked in, one of the managers recognized her from when she was a regular
- Invited them into the players' lounge
- He asked how she had been, and it all came tumbling out: parents' passing and how hard it had hit her, how exhausted she was all the time, how she felt like she was on the verge of a breakdown
- Manager was a good listener—felt so good to finally say everything she had been thinking and be told that it was normal to feel this way

- Sat down at a blackjack table and played for three hours
- For first time in months, the anxiety faded into background noise
- She knew how to do this—she went blank and lost a few thousand dollars

- **Harrah's Entertainment**—company that owned the casino—was known within gaming industry for sophistication of its customer-tracking systems
- At core of that system were **computer programs much like those Andrew Pole created at Target**
- **Predictive algorithms** that studied gamblers' habits and tried to figure out how to persuade them to spend more
- Company assigned players a **"predicted lifetime value"**
- Software built calendars that anticipated how often they would visit and how much they would spend
- Company tracked customers through loyalty cards, mailed out coupons for free meals and cash vouchers; telemarketers called people at home to ask where they had been
- Casino employees were trained to encourage visitors to discuss their lives, in hopes they might reveal information that could be used to predict how much they had to gamble with
- One Harrah's executive called this approach **"Pavlovian marketing"**
- Company ran thousands of tests each year to
<!-- pp. 241-260 -->

### Angie Bachmann's Descent (continued)

- **Harrah's tracking precision**: Customer tracking increased profits
by billions, tracking spending down to the cent and minute
- **Bachmann's bankruptcy**: Had declared bankruptcy, walked away
from $20,000 in gambling debts years earlier
- **Casino courtship intensifies**: After conversation with manager,
received weekly calls with free limos to Mississippi casinos, Lake
Tahoe trips, Eagles concert tickets with front-row seating, $10,000
to play with
- **Escalating play**: Started small with casino money, then $200-$300
per hand, two hands at a time, sometimes dozen hours straight
- Won $60,000 one night, twice walked away up $40,000, once came
with $100,000 in her bag and left with nothing
- **Rationalization**: Inheritance justified enjoyment, bank account
still so large she never had to think about money
- **Relentless casino pressure**: Host told her he'd get fired if she
didn't come in that weekend
- **Night before grandmother's funeral**: Lost $250,000 in twelve hours
- "A quarter of a million dollars gone" — scale didn't register at
the time

> "They would say, 'We sent you to this concert and we gave you this
nice room, and you haven't been gambling that much lately.' Well,
they did do those nice things for me."

### The Psychology of Losing

- **Self-deception cascade**: Had lied to herself about marriage
quality, friendships (appeared for Vegas trips), being good mom
(daughters making same mistakes), parents' approval
- Two choices: continue lying or admit dishonoring everything parents
worked for
- **Depression deepens**: Felt tired all the time, losses too big to
ignore
- **Desperation logic**: "This desperation starts once you realize how
much you've lost, and then you feel like you can't stop because
you've got to win it back"
- Believed she might win it back — "If you couldn't win, then
gambling wouldn't be legal, right?"

### Reza Habib's Neuroscience Study (2010)

- **Experiment design**: Twenty-two people in MRI watching slot machine
spin, half pathological gamblers, half social gamblers
- Programmed for three outcomes: win, loss, **near miss** (slots
almost matched but didn't align)
- **Key finding**: Pathological gamblers' brains showed more excitement
about winning in emotion/reward areas than non-pathological gamblers

> "We were particularly interested in looking at the brain systems
involved in habits and addictions. What we found was that,
neurologically speaking, pathological gamblers got more excited about
winning."

- **Near misses critical**: To pathological gamblers, near misses
looked like wins neurologically
- Non-pathological gamblers recognized near miss as still a loss
- **Hypothesis**: Near misses trigger habits in problem gamblers to
place another bet, while triggering "I should quit before it gets
worse" in others
- **Brain regions**: Basal ganglia and brain stem — same areas where
habits reside and sleep terrors start
- **Pharmaceutical lawsuits**: Class action suits in US, Australia,
Canada alleging pharmaceuticals (Parkinson's medications) caused
compulsive betting, eating, shopping, masturbation by targeting
habit circuitry
- 2008 Minnesota federal jury: awarded patient $8.2 million against
drug company after gambling away $250,000+

### Gaming Industry Exploitation

- **Slot machine reprogramming**: Machines now deliver more constant
supply of near wins
- State lottery consultant: "Adding a near miss to a lottery is like
pouring jet fuel on a fire"
- **Scratch-off design**: Every ticket designed to make you feel like
you almost won
- Late 1990s slot manufacturer hired video game executive to redesign
machines for more near wins
- Now contain "free spins" sounds and small payouts making players
feel they're winning when actually putting in more than getting back

> "No other form of gambling manipulates the human mind as beautifully
as these machines."

### Habib on Responsibility

> "In those cases, we can definitively say that patients have no
control over their obsessions, because we can point to a drug that
impacts their neurochemistry. But when we look at the brains of
people who are obsessive gamblers, they look very similar—except they
can't blame it on a medication. They tell researchers they don't want
to gamble, but they can't resist the cravings. So why do we say that
those gamblers are in control of their actions and the Parkinson's
patients aren't?"

### Bachmann's Final Night (March 18, 2006)

- Flew to Harrah's casino, bank account almost empty
- Told Harrah's she was almost broke but man on phone offered credit
line
- **Inability to refuse**: "It felt like I couldn't say no, like
whenever they dangled the smallest temptation in front of me, my
brain would shut off"
- Started playing $400/hand, two hands at a time
- Husband joined briefly, went to bed at midnight
- By 2 A.M., money gone; signed promissory notes six times for total
$125,000
- **Hot streak at 6 A.M.**: Won five times in a row, needed $20,000
more to pull ahead
- Dealer hit 21 three times in a row
- By 10 A.M., all chips gone; casino said no more credit
- Left table dazed, floor shaking, trailed hand along wall
- Didn't tell husband she'd taken line of credit on house months
earlier and gambled it away

## Appendix: Responsibility and Free Will

### The Legal Question

- **Brian Thomas vs. Angie Bachmann**: Thomas murdered wife
unconsciously (sleep terror), Bachmann squandered inheritance — is
there difference in responsibility?
- **Thomas's defense**: Acted unconsciously, automatically, belief of
intruder attacking; never chose to kill
- **Bachmann parallel**: Also driven by powerful cravings per Habib's
research
- First day maybe made choice, but years later losing $250,000 in
single night, after desperate to fight urges, no longer conscious
decisions

> "Historically, in neuroscience, we've said that people with brain
damage lose some of their free will. But when a pathological gambler
sees a casino, it seems very similar. It seems like they're acting
without choice."

### Court Decision

- **Thomas**: Set free by society
- **Bachmann**: Held accountable — ten months later Harrah's sued for
debts plus $375,000 penalties
- **Bachmann's defense**: By extending credit, free suites, booze,
Harrah's preyed on someone with no control over habits
- Once offers started rolling in, habits took over, impossible to
control behavior
- **Court ruling**: Bachmann wrong — no common law duty on casino to
refrain from enticing/contacting compulsive gamblers
- State had voluntary exclusion program allowing self-ban, suggesting
legislature intended pathological gamblers take personal
responsibility

> "There is no common law duty obligating a casino operator to refrain
from attempting to entice or contact gamblers that it knows or should
know are compulsive gamblers." — Justice Robert Rucker

### The Fairness Question

- Easier to sympathize with devastated widower than housewife who
threw everything away
- **But why?** Why does bereaved husband seem victim while bankrupt
gambler got just deserts?
- More important: **Is it right to make distinction in first place?**

### Aristotle on Habit

- **Nicomachean Ethics**: "Some thinkers hold that it is by nature
that people become good, others that it is by habit, and others that
it is by instruction"
- Behaviors occurring unthinkingly are evidence of truest selves
- "Just as a piece of land has to be prepared beforehand if it is to
nourish the seed, so the mind of the pupil has to be prepared in its
habits if it is to enjoy and dislike the right things"

### The Book's Central Argument

- **Habits aren't destiny**: Even rooted habits can be chosen once you
know how
- Everything we know from neurologists studying amnesiacs and
organizational experts shows any habit can be changed if you
understand how they function
- Hundreds of habits influence our days — different cues, unique
rewards, varying complexity
- **Every habit is malleable**: Most addicted alcoholics can become
sober, dysfunctional companies can transform, high school dropout can
become successful manager

### The Requirement for Change

- **Must decide to change**: Must consciously accept hard work of
identifying cues/rewards and finding alternatives
- Must know you have control and be self-conscious enough to use it
- **Key distinction**: Though both claimed no control over actions
unfolding automatically, fair they be treated differently
- Bachmann should be held accountable, Thomas go free because Thomas
never knew patterns existed
- Bachmann aware of habits; once you know habit exists, have
responsibility to change it
- Others have done so even facing greater temptations

> "That, in some ways, is the point of this book. Perhaps a
sleepwalking murderer can plausibly argue he wasn't aware of his
habit, and so he doesn't bear responsibility for his crime. But
almost all the other patterns that exist in most people's lives—how
we eat and sleep and talk to our kids, how we unthinkingly spend our
time, attention, and money—those are habits that we know exist. And
once you understand that habits can change, you have the freedom—and
the responsibility—to remake them."

### William James's Crisis

- **Background**: From accomplished family (wealthy theologian father,
brilliant writer brother Henry), William was unaccomplished into
thirties
- Sick as child, wanted to be painter, enrolled in medical school,
left for Amazon expedition, quit that
- Visited hospital for insane, saw man hurling himself against wall
- Chastised himself in diary for not being good at anything, uncertain
if he could get better

> "Today I about touched bottom, and perceive plainly that I must face
the choice with open eyes. Shall I frankly throw the moral business
overboard, as one unsuited to my innate aptitudes?"

- **The decision (1870, age 28)**: Would conduct yearlong experiment
believing he had control over himself and destiny, could become
better, had free will to change
- No proof it was true, but would free himself to believe

> "I think that yesterday was a crisis in my life. Regarding his
ability to change, I will assume for the present—until next year—that
it is no illusion. My first act of free will shall be to believe in
free will."

### James's Transformation

- Practiced daily, writing in diary as if control was never in
question
- Got married, started teaching at Harvard
- Befriended **Oliver Wendell Holmes Jr.** (future Supreme Court
justice) and **Charles Sanders Peirce** (semiotics pioneer) in
**Metaphysical Club**
- Two years later wrote philosopher Charles Renouvier thanking for
Essays providing "intelligible and reasonable conception of freedom"

> "I can say that through that philosophy I am beginning to experience
a rebirth of the moral life; and I can assure you, sir, that this is
no small thing."

### The Will to Believe

- Later wrote: will to believe is most important ingredient in
creating belief in change
- One of most important methods for creating that belief was **habits**
- Habits allow us to do things with difficulty first time, then
"finally, with sufficient practice, do it semi-mechanically, or with
hardly any consciousness at all"
- Once we choose who we want to be, people grow "to the way in which
they have been exercised, just as a sheet of paper or a coat, once
creased or folded, tends to fall forever afterward into the same
identical folds"

### The Real Power of Habit

- **If you believe you can change — if you make it a habit — the
change becomes real**
- Insight that your habits are what you choose them to be
- Once that choice occurs and becomes automatic, it's not only real,
starts to seem inevitable

> "All our life, so far as it has definite form, is but a mass of
habits—practical, emotional, and intellectual—systematically organized
for our weal or woe, and bearing us irresistibly toward our destiny,
whatever the latter may be." — William James

### David Foster Wallace's Fish Parable

- Two young fish swimming meet older fish who asks: "Morning, boys.
How's the water?"
- Young fish swim on, then one asks: "What the hell is water?"
- **Water is habits**: unthinking choices and invisible decisions
surrounding us every day
- Just by looking at them, become visible again

### James on Water as Metaphor

- **The Principles of Psychology**: devoted entire chapter to habits
- Water is most apt analogy for how habit works
- Water "hollows out for itself a channel, which grows broader and
deeper; and, after having ceased to flow, it resumes, when it flows
again, the path traced by itself before"

> "You now know how to redirect that path. You now have the power to
swim."

<!-- pp. 261-280 -->

## Appendix: A Reader's Guide to Using These Ideas

### Step Four: Have a Plan

- Once you've identified the habit loop (reward, cue, routine), you can begin to shift behavior
- Change requires **planning for the cue** and **choosing a behavior** that delivers the reward
- **Implementation intentions**: psychology term for plans that specify actions in response to cues

#### Author's Cookie Habit Example

- **Cue identified**: roughly 3:30 PM
- **Routine**: go to cafeteria, buy cookie, chat with friends
- **Reward discovered**: not the cookie itself — **socialization and distraction**
- **The plan**: "At 3:30, every day, I will walk to a friend's desk and talk for 10 minutes"

#### Implementation Process

- Set alarm on watch for 3:30 to ensure memory of the plan
- Initial failures: too busy, easier to grab cookie, fell off wagon
- When he followed the plan: felt better at end of workday, hadn't eaten cookie, felt accomplished
- After a few weeks: routine became **automatic** — hardly thought about it
- Six months later: watch lost, but at 3:30 he **absentmindedly** stands up, finds someone to talk to
- **The behavior became a habit** — occurs without conscious thought

> "It has become a habit." — Duhigg on his new 3:30 PM routine

#### Key Insight on Habit Change

- Framework provides a **starting point** for change
- Some habits more difficult than others
- Change often requires **repeated experiments and failures**
- Once you understand how a habit operates — diagnose cue, routine, reward — you **gain power over it**

