pseudonyms illustrating types of customers Target's models can detect
(not real shoppers).
- **Profile their buying habits** — McDonald's, CBS, Mazda, Microsoft
sued for "History Sniffing" per Forbes.com, January 2011.
- **Ferret out their mailing addresses** — California ruling sets off
more credit card suits per Reuters, February 2011.
- **Forecasted if a tune was likely to succeed** — Polyphonic HMI study
mixing music with math per Harvard Business Review, August 2005.
- **Thirty-seven times throughout the month** — Data from Adam Foster,
director of data services at Nielsen BDS.
- **Listeners didn't just dislike "Hey Ya!"** — Acknowledgment to Paul
Heine (now of Inside Radio) for insights on fine-tuning people meter
data and Mscore data showing varying relationship with airplay.
- **Make "Hey Ya!" into a hit** — Fact-checking confirmed Steve Bartels
(Arista promotions executive) saw polarization of "Hey Ya!" as good
thing. Song released and promoted with another tune ("The Way You
Move") from OutKast's two-disc release Speakerboxxx/The Love Below.
Bartels noted smarter program directors looked at polarization as
opportunity to give station identity; quick turn-off reaction didn't
mean failure.
- **They stayed glued** — Multiple sources including Stephanie Clifford
article on radio meter differences (NY Times, December 2009) and Tim
Feran piece on radio's changing tune (Columbus Dispatch, June 2010).
- **The superior parietal cortex** — Extensive neuroscience research on
neural mechanisms of popularity's influence on adolescent music
ratings. Studies show music perception and cognition following
bilateral lesions of auditory cortex, neural processing of complex
sounds, cortical processing in primate cerebral cortex, neural
substrates processing syntax and semantics in music, musical structure
processed in language areas of brain (Brodmann Area 47 temporal
coherence role), auditory-motor interactions in music perception and
production.
- **A cacophony of noise** — Research on relative utility of
pleasantness vs. liking dimensions in predicting emotions expressed by
music. Familiarity influences attractiveness across numerous senses —
studies show predictability modulates human brain response to reward,
psychophysics toolbox applications, neural correlates of subjective
value during intertemporal choice, behavioral preference for
culturally familiar drinks, neurons in orbitofrontal cortex encode
economic value, marketing actions modulating neural representations of
experienced pleasantness. References include Muzafer Sherif's
Psychology of Social Norms (1936), Wendy Wood on attitude change and
social influence, Gustave Le Bon's The Crowd: A Study of the Popular
Mind (2001), neurobiology studies on social influence in consumer
decisions and aversive outcomes.

