- **You bear no responsibility** — Same principle applies.
- **To perfect their methods** — Christina Binkley on casino chain
mining data on gamblers and striking pay dirt (WSJ, November 2004);
Rajiv Lal on Harrah's Entertainment (Harvard Business School case); K.
Ahsan et al. on Harrah's Entertainment real-time CRM in service supply
chain (Harvard Business Review case, May 2006); V. Chang and J.
Pfeffer on Gary Loveman and Harrah's Entertainment (HBR case, November
2003); Gary Loveman on diamonds in data mine (HBR case, May 2003).
- **To the cent and minute** — Caesars Entertainment settlement
statement (May 2011) precludes both sides from discussing certain
details. Company contested several points about alleged conversations
between Bachmann and unnamed Caesars employees. Because she didn't
provide names, no independent verification of accounts exists.
Statement emphasizes like most large service companies, they pay
attention to customer purchasing decisions for monitoring satisfaction
and evaluating marketing effectiveness. They look for ways to attract
and maintain loyal customers. When customers change established
patterns, they try to understand why and encourage return (no different
than hotel chain, airline, dry cleaner). Good customer service
philosophy. Caesars (formerly Harrah's) has been industry leader in
responsible gaming: first gaming company with written Code of
Commitment governing guest treatment, first casino company with
national self-exclusion program allowing customers to ban themselves
from all properties if they feel problem exists (or for any reason),
only casino company funding national television advertising campaign
promoting responsible gaming. Company hopes reporting reflects this
history and fact that none of Bachmann's statements cited have been
independently verified.
- **"Did do those nice things for me"** — Caesars statement clarified
they would never fire or penalize host if guest stopped visiting
(unless direct result of something host did). No host would be allowed
to tell guest they'd be fired or penalized if guest didn't visit.
- **Watch a slot machine spin around** — Research by M. Dixon and R.
Habib on neurobehavioral evidence for near-miss effect in pathological
gamblers, gambling severity predicting midbrain response to near-miss
outcomes, gambling near-misses enhancing motivation to gamble and
recruiting win-related brain circuitry, decision-making during
gambling integrating cognitive and psychobiological approaches.
- **Bounced checks at a casino** — H. Lesieur and S. Blume on South
Oaks Gambling Screen (SOGS) as instrument for identifying pathological
gamblers (American Journal of Psychiatry 144, no. 9, 1987). Habib
fact-checking letter clarified many subjects categorized as
pathological gamblers based on other behavior types screening form asks
about. Sufficient for participant to have been counted as pathological
gambler if they simply: 1) gambled to win money previously lost
gambling, and 2) on some occasions gambled more than intended. Very low
threshold used to classify subjects as pathological gamblers.
- **Circuitry involved in the habit loop** — Research on drug insight
into impulse control disorders and dopamine therapies in Parkinson's
disease, impulse control disorders with dopaminergic agents in restless
legs syndrome case control study.
- **Hundreds of similar cases are pending** — Ed Silverman on
compulsive gambler winning lawsuit over Mirapex (Pharmalot, July 2008).
- **"Gamblers are in control of their actions"** — Neurology of
gambling research extensive. Studies include problem gamblers sharing
deficits in impulsive decision-making with alcohol-dependent
individuals, habit gambling behavior caused by ischemic lesions
affecting cognitive territories of basal ganglia, veterans and problem
gambling literature review, drug-induced deactivation of inhibitory
networks predicting pathological gambling in PD, treatment of
pathological gambling, executive functions in pathologic gamblers
selected in ecologic setting, gambling and increased sexual desire with
dopaminergic medications in restless legs syndrome.

